im Support\u201d\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[The Eustace Bros.|Paradise Heights]]''\n|Marion Eustace\n|6 episodes \n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Clocking Off]]''\n|Pat Fletcher\n|6 episodes \n|-\n|2003\u20132006\n|''[[Rosemary & Thyme]]''\n|Laura Thyme\n|22 episodes \n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Agatha Christie's Marple]]'' \n|Elspeth McGillicuddy\n|Episode: [[4.50 from Paddington|\u201c4:50 from Paddington\u201d]]\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Jane Eyre (2006 miniseries)|Jane Eyre]]''\n|Grace Poole\n|4 episodes \n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Lilies (BBC TV series)|Lilies]]''\n|Alice Bird\n|Episode: \u201cThe Serpent\u201d\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Little Dorrit (TV series)|Little Dorrit]]'' \n|Mrs. Hortensia General\n|6 episodes \n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Gavin & Stacey]]''\n|Catherina \"Cath\" Smith\n|2 episodes \n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Grandma's House]]''\n|Deborah Adler\n|Episode: \u201cThe Day Simon Announced He Was in Control of the Universe\u201d\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Midsomer Murders]]''\n|Liz Tomlin\n|Episode: \u201cEchoes of the Dead\u201d\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Luther (TV series)|Luther]]''\n|Baba\n|3 episodes \n|-\n|2012\u20132016\n|''[[Call the Midwife]]''\n|Sister Evangelina\n|36 episodes \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|274913|Pam Ferris}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferris, Pam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Welsh film actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh television actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh radio actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh emigrants to New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Welsh expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:People from Hanover]]\n[[Category:People from Bridgend County Borough]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh actresses]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Pam Ferris\n| birth_name         = Pamela E. Ferris<ref name=\"researcha\">[http://web.researcha.com/iccquery/detail/?did=8463227&c=uk]{{dead link|date=June 2012}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1948|05|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Hanover]], [[Lower Saxony]], Germany\n| image              = Pam-Ferris.jpg\n| caption            = Ferris in 2012\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 1971\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Roger Frost|1986}}\n| parents            = Fred Ferris<br/>Ann Perkins \n}}\n\n'''Pamela E. Ferris''' (born 11 May 1948) is a Welsh [[actress]]. She starred on television as Ma Larkin in ''[[The Darling Buds of May (TV series)|The Darling Buds of May]]'', as Laura Thyme in ''[[Rosemary & Thyme]]'', Peggy Snow in ''[[Where the Heart Is (UK TV series)|Where the Heart Is]]'' and as Sister Evangelina in ''[[Call the Midwife]]''. She has also played parts in family films based on works by British authors, such as Ms. Trunchbull in [[Matilda]] and Aunt Marge in ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (film)|Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]'' (2004). She played the role of Mrs. Faulker in the 2019 [[biopic]] ''[[Tolkien (film)|Tolkien]]''. She also played the role of Mrs. Bevan in ''[[Nativity!]]'' (2009).\n\n==Biography==\nFerris was born in [[Hanover]], [[Lower Saxony]], Germany,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://company-director-check.co.uk/director/902329745|title=MS PAMELA FERRIS director information. Free director information. Director id 902329745|first=company check|last=ltd|website=Company Check|accessdate=16 September 2017}}</ref> to [[Welsh people|Welsh]] parents, while her father was serving in the [[Royal Air Force]]. After her parents returned to Wales, Ferris spent her childhood in the [[Aberkenfig]] area, near [[Bridgend]]. Her father, Fred Ferris, was a policeman, and her mother, Ann Perkins, worked in her family's bakery business.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/southeast/sites/bridgend/pages/pamferris.shtml |title=Coming Home: Pam Ferris |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=16 September 2017 |date=12 March 2007 |publisher=[[BBC]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070919164928/http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/southeast/sites/bridgend/pages/pamferris.shtml |archive-date=19 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=August 2018}}\nFerris performed in her younger years at the [[Mercury Theatre (Auckland)|Mercury Theatre]] in [[Auckland]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://0-www.aucklandcity.govt.nz.www.elgar.govt.nz/dbtw-wpd/virt-exhib/realgold/Arts/mercury-theatre.html |title=Mercury Theatre Records (1966\u20131990) |work=Auckland City Government |access-date=27 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724221113/http://0-www.aucklandcity.govt.nz.www.elgar.govt.nz/dbtw-wpd/virt-exhib/realgold/Arts/mercury-theatre.html |archive-date=24 July 2008}}</ref> and later with various regional companies in the UK. She played motherly Ma Larkin in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''[[The Darling Buds of May (TV series)|The Darling Buds of May]]'', which ran from 1991 to 1993. She has also acted in a succession of television dramas, including ''[[Meantime (film)|Meantime]]'', in which she played the Cockney mother of [[Phil Daniels]] and [[Tim Roth]], ''[[Connie (TV series)|Connie]]'', ''[[Hardwicke House]]'', ''[[Oranges Are Not the Only Fruit (TV serial)|Oranges Are Not the Only Fruit]]'', ''[[Where the Heart Is (UK TV series)|Where the Heart Is]]'' and ''[[The Eustace Bros.|Paradise Heights]]''. From 2003 to 2006, she played the gardening sleuth, Laura Thyme, in ''[[Rosemary & Thyme]]''.\n\nHer roles in [[costume drama]]s include parts in television adaptations of ''[[Middlemarch]]'', ''[[The Tenant of Wildfell Hall]]'', ''[[Our Mutual Friend]]'', ''[[The Turn of the Screw]]'', ''[[Pollyanna]]'', and ''[[Jane Eyre]]''.\nIn 1996, Ferris portrayed the brutish, authoritarian school headmistress Agatha Trunchbull in ''[[Matilda (1996 film)|Matilda]]''. In 2004, she played the callous [[Marge Dursley|Aunt Marge]] in ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (film)|Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]''. In 2006, Ferris took on the role of Miriam, a motherly activist in ''[[Children of Men]]''. She has also acted in productions for [[BBC Radio 4]].\n\nHer career in the theatre has included parts in [[Royal Court Theatre]] and [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] productions. In 2007 she played Phoebe Rice in an acclaimed revival of [[John Osborne]]'s'' [[The Entertainer (play)|The Entertainer]]'' at London's [[Old Vic Theatre]]. In 2007, Ferris took part in the [[BBC Wales]] programme ''[[Coming Home (UK TV series)|Coming Home]]'' about her Welsh family history. In 2008 she played Mrs General in an all-star cast [[BBC]] adaptation of the [[Charles Dickens]] novel ''[[Little Dorrit]]''. From 2009 to 2010, she appeared in the final series of the BBC comedy ''[[Gavin & Stacey]]'' as Cath Smith. In 2010, she made a guest appearance in the sitcom ''[[Grandma's House]]''. From 2012-2016, Ferris played the part of Sister Evangelina in the series ''[[Call the Midwife]]''. She chose to leave as filming was moved to a different location and the\nextra journey time was too stressful. In June and July 2015 Ferris was the guest of [[Sarah Walker (music broadcaster)|Sarah Walker]] on [[BBC Radio 3]]'s ''Essential Classics''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b060brt5 |title=Monday - Sarah Walker with Pam Ferris, Essential Classics |work=[[BBC Radio 3]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |access-date=16 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1986 she married actor Roger Frost. She lives in [[Elham, Kent]], England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/news/meridian/update/2015-06-07/darling-buds-of-may-star-back-in-kent-high-life/ |title='Darling Buds of May' star back in Kent high life |work=[[Itv.com]] |access-date=16 September 2017 |date=7 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|