s Marple]]'' \n|Elspeth McGillicuddy\n|Episode: [[4.50 from Paddington|\u201c4:50 from Paddington\u201d]]\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Jane Eyre (2006 miniseries)|Jane Eyre]]''\n|Grace Poole\n|4 episodes \n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Lilies (BBC TV series)|Lilies]]''\n|Alice Bird\n|Episode: \u201cThe Serpent\u201d\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Little Dorrit (TV series)|Little Dorrit]]'' \n|Mrs. Hortensia General\n|6 episodes \n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Gavin & Stacey]]''\n|Catherina \"Cath\" Smith\n|2 episodes \n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Grandma's House]]''\n|Deborah Adler\n|Episode: \u201cThe Day Simon Announced He Was in Control of the Universe\u201d\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Midsomer Murders]]''\n|Liz Tomlin\n|Episode: \u201cEchoes of the Dead\u201d\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Luther (TV series)|Luther]]''\n|Baba\n|3 episodes \n|-\n|2012\u20132016\n|''[[Call the Midwife]]''\n|Sister Evangelina\n|36 episodes \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|274913|Pam Ferris}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ferris, Pam}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Welsh film actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh television actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh radio actresses]]\n[[Category:Welsh emigrants to New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Welsh expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:People from Hanover]]\n[[Category:People from Bridgend County Borough]]\n[[Category:20th-century Welsh actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Welsh actresses]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Matilda\u2192Matilda (1996 film)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pam_Ferris"}
{"title_page": "Sapta Puri", "text_new": "A List of Seven Holy Pilgrimage Sites in Hinduism, which bless the Pilgrims with Moksha (Liberation from Cycle of Birth and Death).{{Sapta Puri}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n\nThe '''Sapta Puri''' are seven holy pilgrimage centres in India. The [[Tirtha (Hinduism)|tirtha]]s are: [[Ayodhya]] [Ayodyapuri] ([[Vishnu]] as [[Rama]]), [[Mathura]] [Madurapuri] ([[Vishnu]] as [[Krishna]]), [[Haridwar]] [Mayapuri] ([[Shakti]] as [[Maya Devi Temple, Haridwar|Mayadevi]]), [[Varanasi]] [Kasipuri] ([[Shiva]] as [[Kashi Vishwanath Temple|Vishwanath]]), [[Kanchipuram]] [Kanchipuri] ([[Durga]] as [[Kamakshi]]), [[Ujjain]] [Avantikapuri] ([[Shiva]] as [[Mahakaleshwar]]), [[Dwarka]] [Dwarakapuri] ([[Vishnu]] as [[Krishna]]).<ref name=Bansal>{{Cite book|last=Bansal|first=Sunita Pant| title=Hindu Pilgrimage |work=Teertha|pages=6\u20139 & 34\u201335|accessdate=2009-08-07|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=F303Zb7EC0kC&pg=PT34&dq=panch+prayag&as_brr=3&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=panch%20prayag&f=false|publisher=Pustak Mahal|year=2008|isbn= 9788122309973}}</ref><ref name=Morgan>{{Cite book|last=Morgan|first= Kenneth W|author2=D S Sarma |title= The Religion of the Hindus |work= Sacred Pilgrimage Places|pages=188\u2013191|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ulz9mO9cK54C&pg=PA189&dq=Ujjain&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=Ujjain&f=false|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass Publ|year=1987|isbn= 9788120803879}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amirdham.com/documents/sri_maha_rudra_yagna.pdf|title=The efficacy of Sri \u2018Maha rudra\u2019 Yagna|last=Guruji Kalyanarama Iyer|first=|date=|website=amirtham.com|page=18|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Sapta Puri are places of birth of religious and spiritual masters, places where gods have descended as [[avatar]]s (incarnations) such as Ayodhya where [[Rama]] was born, and places considered as ''Nitya tirthas'', naturally endowed, with spiritual powers since ages such as Varanasi and Haridwar. Kanchipuram is known for its [[Kamakshi Amman Temple]] dedicated to the mother goddess. Dwarka represents the place where god [[Krishna]], after leaving Mathura spent 100 years before He left for his divine abode from here, according to the epic [[Mahabharata]]. Mathura is the embodiment of events in the life of Krishna during his childhood and young days. Haridwar with shrines of both [[Shiva]] and Vishnu, represents the gateway to [[Uttarakhand]], as the sacred river [[Ganges]] emerges from the hills into the plains at this place. Varanasi is the place of salvation as it is strongly believed that death at this place will bring salvation. [[Varanasi]] is the holiest of all and it is favorite to lord [[Shiva]], thus it is often referred as ''City of Lord Shiva''. In Hinduism, one should visit the major temples in Varanasi in his/her life. Ujjain, also known by the ancient name Avanti, has one of the 12 [[Jyotirlingas]] installed in the [[Mahakaleshwar Temple]]. Each of these cities is also famous for the spectacular melas or fairs held. Haridwar and Ujjain are famous for the [[Kumbh Mela]] held once every 12 years. Marriage festival of [[Kamakshi]] at Kanchipuram is a special occasion. [[Krishna Janmashtami]] ( birth day of Krishna - generally held in August as per Hindu calendar) is a special occasion in Dwarka and Mathura.<ref name=Bansal/><ref name=Morgan/>\nThe seven religious cities are within India's territorial ambit and pilgrimage to these places greatly enhances the unity of the nation, in spite of its linguistic and cultural diversity. The seven sacred urban centers are well connected by road, rail and air transport with the rest of the country.<ref name=Bansal/>\n\n==Haridwar==\n[[File:Clock Tower, at Har-ki-Pauri, Haridwar.jpg|thumb|left|Har-ki-Pauri at Haridwar]]\n\"Haridwar\", also written as \"Hardwar\", literally means \"gateway to god Vishnu (Hari)\" or \"gateway to god Shiva (Har)\". It is the holiest city in the state of [[Uttarakhand]]. It is strategically located ({{coord|29.96|N|78.16|E}}) on the western bank of the river [[Ganges]] as it emerges into the plains at the exact location where the Har-Ki-Pauri ghat has been built to facilitate pilgrims to take a holy bath. It is thus also called the ''Gangadwara'', the place where the Ganges descends to the plains. Every year, thousands of people flock to Haridwar, also called Hardwar, to bathe at the Har-Ki-Pauri ghat (ghat is an embankment structure built out of stone slabs leading to the river edge to facilitate bathing) since it is believed that the feet of Vishnu is imprinted on a rock preserved here. Every evening at sun set time at the ghat, thousands of pilgrims offer [[Arti (Hinduism)|arti]], a Hindu ritual of offering lights of earthen lamps on small floating leaf holders with flowers, as the temple bells reverberate amidst chanting of hymns.<ref name=\"Bansal p.44-47\">Bansal p.44-47</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttp://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/vp/vp043.htm|title=SACRIFICE OF DAKSHA 1 (From the Vayu Purana)|accessdate=2009-08-16|publisher= The Vishnu Purana, translated by [[Horace Hayman Wilson]], 1840. p. 62, 62:2}}</ref><ref name=Hoiberg>{{Cite book|last=Hoiberg|first=Dale|author2=Indu Ramchandani |title=Students' Britannica India|work=Haridwar|pages=248|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AE_LIg9G5CgC&pg=PA248&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=h0h-Svv3BpqUkAT2jpSPCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher=Popular Prakashan|year= 2000|isbn= 9780852297605}}</ref>\n\nLegend from Hindu scriptures state that Haridwar is one among the four sites where drops of [[Amrita]], the elixir of immortality, accidentally spilled over from the pitcher, in which it was being carried away by the celestial bird [[Garuda]], after the [[Samudra manthan]] (churning of the ocean); the other three places are said to be Ujjain, [[Nasik]], and [[Allahabad]].<ref name=Harid>{{Cite web|url=http://sahajaharidwar.tripod.com/About_Haridwar.html|title=About Haridwar|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher=sahajaharidwar.com}}</ref>\n\nAnother legend narrated for this pilgrim place is that sage [[Kapila]] had cursed the ancestors of prince [[Bhagiratha]]. Bhagiratha, therefore, wanted to atone for their sins by performing penance to god Shiva here. Shiva pleased with the prayers of Bhagiratha, allowed the Ganges to trickle through his locks and fall on earth from heaven.<ref name=Davidson>{{Cite book|last=Davidson|first=Linda Kay|author2=David Martin Gitlitz  |title= Pilgrimage |work= Haridwar (Uttar Pradesh, India: Hinduism Seventh century)|pages =228\u2013229|accessdate=2009-08-10|url=\nhttps://books.google.com/books?id=YVYkrNhPMQkC&pg=PT258&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=q1x-SoiED5-qkASVvdiWCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year= 2002|isbn= 9781576070048}}</ref>\n\nIt is from here that the Ganges emerging out of the [[Siwalik Hills|Shivalik]] hills of the Rudra-[[Himalayas]] travels a distance of {{convert|2000|km|mi}} through the fertile Gangetic plains of [[North India]]. It is also the site where the river has been tapped for beneficial uses of irrigation and hydro-power generation by a complex system of barrages (low gated weirs) with large canal systems. Its hoary history, closely spun around the epic [[Mahabharata]] (also substantiated in the travelogues of the Chinese chronicler [[Hiuen Tsang]]), records that [[Timurlane]] had ransacked this town in the year 1399 AD. Apart from the holy ghat, there are a large number of temples in the city dedicated to Shiva, goddess [[Shakti]] or [[Durga]] (a cable car way has been built to approach this temple, apart from the ancient approach by steps over the hills), Vishnu and a galaxy of other deities. It is the pious location where, Hindus from all parts of the country, particularly North India, immerse ashes of the dead and perform last rites.<ref name=Davidson/><ref name=Bradnock>{{Cite book|last=Bradnock|first= Roma|title= Indian Himalaya handbook |work=Haridwar|pages=103\u2013105|accessdate=2009-08-10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TyZGp_YVzb8C&pg=PA109&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=P2B-SqiEA5uOkQTylZStCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher= Footprint Travel Guides|year=2000|isbn= 9781900949798}}</ref>\n\nApart from the regular annual pilgrimage season from April to November, during February\u2013March ''Magh Mela'' ('mela' means \"fair\") is also held on a large scale. Other spectacular events that are held here are the Ardh Kumbha Mela  (half Kumbh Mela) held every six years. The 12 years cycle [[Kumbh Mela]] is held during January or February depending on the Hindu [[Panchanga|Calmanac]]. It is the occasion when lakhs of people congregate here for a holy dip in the Ganges.<ref name=\"Bansal p.44-47\"/><ref name=Davidson/><ref name=Bradnock/><ref name=\"SinghBindloss2007\">{{cite book |last1=Singh |first1=Sarina |last2=Bindloss |first2=Joe |last3=Bainbridge |first3=James |last4=Brown |first4=Lindsay |last5=Elliott |first5=Mark |last6=Butler |first6=Stuart |display-authors=2 |date=2007 |title=India |publisher=Lonely Planet |page=[https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetindi00sari/page/454 454] |isbn=978-1-74104-308-2 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetindi00sari/page/454 }}</ref> The Kumbh Mela (literal meaning is ('festival of pots') is the \"confluence of faith\" since lakhs of people irrespective of their caste affiliations attend it. Astrological combination of planets decide the date for the event; generally when Jupiter, Sun and Moon are in the same zodiacal sign of the Aquarius, but in Haridwar it is fixed when Sun is in Aries and Jupiter in Aquarius, which is called the 'Vaishaki snan' ([[Vaisakha|Vaishakha]] is the second month of Hindu calendar and ''snan'' means bathing).<ref name=Mishra>{{Cite book|last=Mishra|first=J.S.|title=Pilgrimage, purification and piety |work=Mahakumbh, the greatest show on earth|pages=14\u201320|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1pCXqynwwQcC&pg=PA14&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=1GR-SsTHC5PolQT2peCuCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher=Har-Anand Publications|year=2004|isbn= 9788124109939}}</ref>\n\n{{location map+|India|float=right|width=375|caption=Location of Sapta Puri.\n|places=\n{{Location map~|India|label='''Ayodhya'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=bottom|lat=26.80|long=82.20}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Mathura'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=27.29|long=77.40}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Haridwar'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=29.956|long=78.17}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Varanasi'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=25.28|long=82.96}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Kanchipuram'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=12.82|long=79.71}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Ujjain'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=23.18|long=75.77}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Dwarka'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=22.23|long=68.97}}\n}}\nA lyrical poetic expression of the place by Mavis Jones, which succinctly describes the environment and the religiosity of the pilgrims is quoted below.<ref name=Jones>{{Cite book|last=Jones|first=Mavis|title=her festival clothes|work =Poem haridwar|page=10|accessdate=2009-08-10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VEz2w6LYxbwC&pg=PA10&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=q1x-SoiED5-qkASVvdiWCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press -MQUP|year=2001|isbn= 9780773519091}}</ref>\n\nA green so light, not jade, not sky.<br>\nIce water rushed out of the Himalayan<br>\nsilence into this wide scarred channel.\n\nAlong the other shore ashrams<br>\nare seashell-coloured, beige,<br>\ncream, coral, sea green.\n\nThe pilgrims who wash on the flooded steps<br>\nemerge new from the sacred waters.<br>\nThey are transfigured in scarlet,\n\nsaffron, emerald. Even the birds<br>\nare blessed with such colour.<br>\nThe kingfisher is as royal\n\nas any prince his ''gazi'' a white-fronted<br>\nwaterhen in grey and russet.<br>\nNow the song rich as honey,\n\nof the black-headed oriole<br>\ncalling pilgrims out of the dry land.<br>\nThis benediction of water, overflowing.\n\nAs many gods are here, as many devotees<br>\nas specks of sun-lit dust rising<br>\nfrom a cremation ghat.\n\nHaridwar is at a road distance of {{convert|214|km|mi}} from Delhi, the capital of the nation, and {{convert|52|km|mi}} from [[Dehradun]], the provincial capital of Uttarakhand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uttaranchalonline.info/Garhwal/Haridwar/Distance_From_Haridwar.html|title=Distances from Haridwar|accessdate=2009-08-13}}</ref>\n\n==Dwarka==\n[[File:Dwarka.jpg|thumb|left|A Painting depicting Krishna's Dwarka made during [[Akbar]]'s reign from the [[Smithsonian Institution]]]]\n[[Krishna]], an incarnation of god Vishnu, is believed to have migrated from Mathura to Dwarka ({{coord|22.23|N|68.97|E}}) 5000 years ago and made Dwarka his capital., as noted in the scripture [[Bhagavata Purana]].<ref name=\"Bansal p.10 & 20\">Bansal p.10 & 20</ref> He established the city on the bank of the [[Gomti River]]. But after the death of Krishna, there was downfall of his dynasty, [[Yadava dynasty|the Yadavas]]. This was further compounded by floods and eventual submergence of Krishna's city in the [[Arabian Sea]]. Presently, Dwarka is a small city located at the western tip of [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] peninsular in [[Gujarat]] state on the shores of the Arabian Sea.<ref name=\"Bansal p.10 & 20\"/><ref name=guju>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=224|title=Dwarka|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher= Gujarat Tourism}}</ref>\n\nChronology of the recorded historic events witnessed at the temple city linked directly to the temple, is dated from 400 B.C. when Vajranabha built an umbrella type temple and deified his grand father Krishna's image there. It has undergone several changes with times under different rulers and in 800 AD, [[Adi Shankara]]charya is said to have got the [[Dwarkadheesh temple, Gujrat|Dwarakadheesh temple]] renovated and also added a shrine of goddess Adya Shakti. Over the next few centuries more renovations took place with grant of additional land till 1261 AD, when the temple was destroyed by Mohamed Shah. In subsequent years also, renovation took place but there was dispute between two groups for the control of the temple. In 1504, [[Vallabhacharya]] established the image of Dwarakadeesh in a well in Ladva village to protect it from Muslim marauders and again it was shifted to [[Dungarpur]] where the temple was renovated. In 1861, Maharaja Khanderao renovated the temple. During British rule, the temple tower was rebuilt. A golden pitcher was fixed on the temple tower by Maharaja [[Gaekwad]] in the year 1903 and further renovations were undertaken by the then Shankarachrya of Dwarka Peet. Since 1960, the conservation of the temple is under the control of the Government of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dwarkadhish.org/little-history.aspx|title=Events|accessdate=2009-08-13|publisher=Dwarkadhish.org Official Website of Jagad Mandir \u2013 Dwarka}}</ref>\n\nThe present Dwarakhadheesh temple, also called the Jagat Mandir (universal shrine) or ''trilok sundar'' (most beautiful in all three worlds), is a seven storied structure, {{convert|43|m|ft}} in height, appears to be raising above the Arabian sea. It is dated to the 13th century AD on the basis of oceanographic explorations undertaken to trace the ancient temple, which was submerged in the Arabian sea. The elegantly carved temple [[shikara]] (tower) is adorned with a huge flag, which is said to be {{convert|52|yard|ft}} in length with seven colours that can be seen flying from a distance of {{convert|10|km|mi}} (hoisting this flag has a great religious significance). There is an approach to the back side of the temple from the Gomti River end, which is built of 56 steps. The temple built in soft limestone has a sanctum enclosed within a large hall with covered entrance from three sides. While the external carvings depict erotic scenes, the temple sanctum is austere in design but the main image is elaborately ornamented.<ref name =Dwar>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=227&webpartid=872|title= Dwarkadhish Temple|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher=Gujarat Tourism}}</ref><ref name=submerge>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dwarkadhish.org/about-us/dwarka-nagari/submerged-dwarka/|title=Dwarka Nagari - Submerged Dwarka|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher=Dwarkadhish.org Official Website of Jagad Mandir \u2013 Dwarka}}</ref>\n\nA temple dedicated to [[Rukmini]], Krishna's consort, is located in Bet Dwarka, {{convert|2|km|mi}}  away from Dwarka. The temple is said to be 2500 years old but in its present form it is inferred to be of 12th century vintage. It is a richly carved temple decorated with sculptures of gods and goddesses on the exterior with the sanctum housing the main image of Rukmini. Carved ''naratharas'' (human figures) and carved ''gajatharas'' (elephants) are depicted in panels at the base of the tower. An interesting legend is narrated to justify separate dwelling temples, far away from each other, for Rukmini and her husband Krishna. It is said that at the request of sage [[Durvasa]] (who was renowned for his short temper and bestowing curses) Krishna and Rukmini pulled a chariot taking sage Durvasa to their house for dinner. On the way, when Rukmini asked for water to quench her thirst, Krishna drew Ganges water, by prodding the ground with his toe, for her to drink. Rukmini quenched her thirst with the Ganges water. But Durvasa felt insulted since Rukmini did not have the courtesy to offer him water to drink. He, therefore, cursed her that she would live separately from her husband.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=227&webpartid=877|title=Rukmini Devi Temple |accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher= Gujarat Tourism}}</ref><ref name=Myths>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dwarkadhish.org/popular-myths.aspx|title=Dwarka Nagari - Popular Myths|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher=Dwarkadhish.org Official Website of Jagad Mandir \u2013 Dwarka}}</ref>\n\nAnother legend states, while Dwarka was the official capital of Krishna where he held his assembly, his residence was at Bet Dwarka.<ref name=Myths/>\n\n==Kanchipuram==\n\nKanchipuram ({{coord|12.82|N|79.71|E}}), the pilgrimage city, in [[Tamil Nadu]], also known as Canjeevaram during the [[United Kingdom|British]] rule, built during the [[Pallava Dynasty]] between 6th and 8th centuries, located on the bank of the [[Palar River]], has an architectural legacy of over 1000 years. Before this period, it was the capital of early [[Cholas]] in the 2nd century BC. After the rule of the [[Pallava Dynasty]], the [[Vijayanagara empire]] and the [[Nayak (ethnic group)|Nayaka]] dynasty period followed, in that order. Prior to the Pallava reign, it is conjectured, based on the chronicles of the [[Xuanzang]], the Chinese pilgrim who visited Pallavas court, that the city was under the influence of [[Ashoka]], the [[Mauryan]] emperor in 3rd century BC. Xuanzang had also noted that [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] had visited this place. [[Jain]] and [[Buddhist]] temples and [[stupas]] of the [[Chola Dynasty]] reign have been recorded but mostly do not exist on ground. But South Indian architecture got a fillip only during the Pallava rule, particularly of rock cut temples during Mahendarvarman I's reign after he converted from Jainism to Hinduism . He was considered a man with vision and intelligence, a scholar, musician and a playwright. Kanchipuram was considered second only to Varanasi city in fame and learning. [[Adi Shankara]], the Hindu philosopher saint, who propagated the [[Advaita]] philosophy lived and taught here in the eighth century AD.<ref name=\"Ring p.435-436\">Ring p.435-436</ref><ref name=kanchi>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kanchi.tn.nic.in/dist_profile_history.html |title=Historical Importance of Kanchipuram |accessdate=2009-08-10 |publisher=National Informatic Centre, Kanchi |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090806052722/http://www.kanchi.tn.nic.in/dist_profile_history.html |archivedate=6 August 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe city has 108 [[Shaiva]] and 18 [[Vaishnava]] temples. The Hindu philosopher [[Ramanujacharya]] who propagated the [[Vishishtadvaita]] philosophy studied here. The temples are distributed in three zones of the city namely, the Vishnu temples are in the east zone, the Shiva shrines are on the outskirts of the city in the northern zone and the Jain mandirs are on the east across the Palar River.<ref name=\"Ring p.435-436\"/><ref name=brit>{{Cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/310889/Kanchipuram|title= Kanchipuram|accessdate=2009-08-10}}</ref>\n\nSome of the exquisitely designed and built temples of the Vijayanagar period in [[Vijayanagara architecture]] style are the Ekamabaranath temple tower which is {{convert|192|ft|m}} in height, and the Varadaraja Swamy temple, which has a 1000-pillar hall.<ref name=kanchi/>\n\n[[Kamakshi Amman temple]] is an ancient temple here and the most famous of all the temples in the city. It is associated with Adi Shankara. Legend has it that [[Kamakshi]] offered worship to a [[Lingam|Shivaling]] made out of sand and gained Shiva's hand in marriage. The temple covers an area of about {{convert|5|acre|ha}} and the sanctum is covered with gold plated [[Vimana]]. Kamakshi is enshrined in the temple in a sitting posture called the ''Parabramha Swaroopini'', seated with the trinity of [[Bramha]], Vishnu and Shiva.<ref>Bansal p.149</ref>\n\nIt is located {{convert|75|km|mi}} from [[Chennai]], the provincial capital of [[Tamil Nadu]] and {{convert|277|km|mi}} from [[Bangalore]], the provincial capital of [[Karnataka]]. It has a good net work of roads, rail links and transport services to all parts of the country, and the nearest domestic and international airports are at Chennai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kanchi.tn.nic.in/|title= Kanchipuram|accessdate=2009-08-10}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mustseeindia.com/driving-directions-from-Bangalore-to-Kanchipuram/travel-direction|title=Bangalore to Kanchipuram|accessdate=2009-08-22}}</ref>\n\n==Ujjain==\n[[File:Mahakal Temple Ujjain.JPG|thumb|left|Mahakal temple at Ujjain, [[Madhya Pradesh]] ]] \nUjjain ({{coord|23.182778|N|75.777222|E}}) with an ancient scriptural name of Avantika compliments both rich historical and religious traditions. The history dates its links to the period of [[Vikramaditya]] and [[Ashoka]] (3rd century BC). The religious tradition links it to god Shiva triumphing over the demon king [[Tripurasura]] and then renaming the city as Ujjainyini (meaning 'conquers with pride').<ref name=Ujjain>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ujjain.nic.in/tourist/what_to_see.htm|title=Ujjain|accessdate=2009-08-09|publisher=Ujaajin.nic.in}}</ref>\n\nUjjain, probably, also marks the spread of Hindu religious beliefs to the [[Central Asia]] region. Particular mention could be made to the reign of [[Vima Kadphises]], during the [[Kushan Dynasty]], who considered Shiva as his divine patron. During his reign, apart from the influence of [[Greece|Greek]] religious practices, worship of Shiva, in particular, was also seen as an accepted practice in [[Iran]]. This leaning is attributed to Vima Kadphises's victory over Indian territory. Inscriptions of his times in [[Iran]] establish that he had converted the temple of [[Dioscuri]] (built during Greeko \u2013 [[Bactria]]n period) at Dilberjin into a sanctuary for Shiva by decorating the place with a painting of Shiva and his wife [[Parvati]]. He got the wall painting of Shiva (''Oeso'') done by craftsmen he had taken from Ujjayani (Ujjain), apart from constructing a water conveyance system to the sanctuary of Shiva. Inscriptions further testify that the Kushan king attributed his rise to power to Srava (=Shiva) and Candavira. It is deduced that Candavira may be the same god as Candishvara, the God of Mahakala temple at Ujjain. It is also conjectured that the support of the Indian community (who worshipped Shiva) settled in eastern Iran and the encouragement he got from their priesthood, before and during his Indian campaign, and his relations with Ujjain, contributed to his deep involvement with the cult of Shiva. This devotion was continued by him even after his Indian campaign.<ref name=Harmatta>{{Cite book|last=Harmatta|first=Janos|title= History of civilizations of Central Asia | work=Religious Life under Vima Kaldphises |pages=318\u2013321|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DguGWP0vGY8C&pg=PA319&dq=Ujjain&lr=&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=Ujjain&f=false|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass Publ|year=1999|isbn= 9788120814080}}</ref><ref>Ring p.835-837</ref>\n\nEmperor Ashoka also played a significant role as the Viceroy of Ujjain in enhancing its importance. Ashoka who ruled for three decades between 268 and 233 BC started his career in [[Taxila]] (now in [[Pakistan]]) in the north west by subduing a revolt. Thereafter, his father [[Bindusara]], of the [[Mauryan Dynasty]], transferred Ashoka as his Viceroy to Ujjain, which was the famous capital of the earlier kingdom of Avanti, in [[Central India]].<ref name=Kulkae>{{Cite book|last=Kulkae|first=Hermann|author2=Dietmar Rothermund |title= A History of India |work=Ashoka the beloved to the Gods|pages=62\u201365|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V0GEtXp-GsUC&pg=PA65&dq=Ujjain&lr=&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=Ujjain&f=false|publisher= CRC Press|year=1998|isbn=  9780203443453}}</ref>\n\nIt was once the largest city and capital of [[Malwa]] region. In the ancient city of Ujjain, [[Jai Singh II of Amber|Jai Singh II]] ruled in the 18th century. Jai Singh II built an observatory here, called the [[Jantar Mantar]]. The reason for building the observatory here was that it was the centre of [[Hindu Astronomy]] since ancient times and it was located on the prime or first meridian (of longitude) established on the canons of Hindu astronomy. According to [[Indian astronomy]], the first [[meridian (geography)|meridian]] of longitude passes through Ujjain. The modern calculations have established that the [[Tropic of Cancer]] passes through Ujjain.<ref name=\"Harmatta\"/><ref>Bansal p.50-51</ref><ref name=Sharma>{{Cite book|last=Sharma|first=Virendra Nath|title= Sawai Jai Singh and His Astronomy |work=Ujjain Observatory|pages=212\u2013213|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QRA2mgZnXXMC&pg=PA212&dq=Ujjain&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=Ujjain&f=false|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|year=1995|isbn=9788120812567 }}</ref>\n\nUjjain is about {{convert|776|km|mi}} south from [[Delhi]], the capital city of India, and {{convert|183|km|mi}} west of [[Bhopal]], the provincial capital of [[Madhya Pradesh]].<ref name= distance>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mapsofindia.org/distance-chart-india/delhi.html|title=Distances from Delhi to Metro cities in India|accessdate=2009-08-13}}</ref> It is {{convert|402|km|mi}}away from\n[[Ahmedabad]], and {{convert|655|km|mi}} north-west of [[Mumbai]].<ref name=Ujjain/>\n\n==Varanasi==\n[[File:Benares 1890.jpg|thumb|right|Famous Dashashwamedh Ghat]]\n[[File:Ganga Aarti at Varanasi ghats.jpg|right|thumb|Festival of the [[Ganges River]] worship by [[Arti (Hinduism)|arti]] at [[Dashashwamedh Ghat]], [[Utter pradesh]]]]\nVaranasi ({{coord|25.282|N|82.9563|E}}) also called Kashi, Benares, is an ancient city, said to be the oldest inhabited one. The city was known by several names such as ''Avimuktaka'', ''Anandakanana'', ''Mahasmasana'', ''Surandhana'', ''Brahma Vardha'', ''Sudarsana'', and ''Ramya''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.up-tourism.com/destination/varanasi/intro.htm | title=Uttar Pradesh Tourism - Varanasi | publisher=Department of Tourism - Government of UP | accessdate=2009-05-01 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061114082739/http://www.up-tourism.com/destination/varanasi/intro.htm | archivedate=14 November 2006 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn view of its ancient historic, cultural and religious heritage it is considered as \u201cthe most holy of the seven sacred cities of Hinduism\u201d. Its historical and religious legacy dates to the Budhha period (6th Century BC) and has been the centre of religious \u201cBrahminical learning\u201d with sages, philosophers, writers and musicians making it their home in the past several centuries. But much of its temple glory was subject to plundering and destruction by Mohammad Ghauri in the 12th century. The temples and religious institutions seen now in the city are mostly of the 18th century vintage.<ref name=online>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bl.uk/onlinegallery/onlineex/apac/photocoll/r/019pho0000050s2u00064000.html|title=Ramnath [Sumeri] Temple, Benares.|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher=British Library On Line Gallery}}</ref>\n\nThe temples and the bathing ghats (ghats are embankments made in steps of stone slabs along the river bank where pilgrims perform ritual ablutions) are located on the left west bank of the holy [[Ganges]] river and the count of temples in the city is claimed to be 23,000 and the bathing ghats number 81. The most venerated and frequented ghats for devotional worship by the pilgrims are the Manikarnika Ghat, Harishchandra Ghat, [[Dashashwamedh Ghat]] (pictured), Assi Ghat and Panchganga Ghat. At two of the ghats (Manikarnika and Harishchandra Ghats), Hindus cremate their dead. The rivers 'Varuna' and 'Asi' combined form the name of the city \"Varanasi\". These two rivers flowing on the left bank of the Ganges enclose the old city of Varanasi. The ghats at the confluence sites of these two streams with the Ganges are also held in veneration. All these factors have contributed to the city being called the religious capital of Hinduism.<ref name=\"Bansal p.48-49\">Bansal p.48-49</ref><ref name=Varun>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9074835/Varanasi|title=Varanasi|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online]]|accessdate=2009-08-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Alexander |last=Cunningham |author2=Surendranath Majumdar Sastri  |authorlink=Alexander Cunningham |title=Ancient Geography of India |pages=131\u2013140 |publisher=Munshiram Manoharlal |origyear=1924 |year=2002 |isbn=81-215-1064-3  }}</ref>\n\nVaranasi is also known as the favourite city of the Hindu deity [[Shiva]] as it has been mentioned in the [[Rigveda]] that this city in older times was known as [[Varanasi|Kashi]] or \"Shiv ki Nagri\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9074835/Varanasi |title=Varanasi |publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] |accessdate=30 October 2012}}</ref> The [[Pandavas]] went to Kashi in search of Shiva to atone for their sins of fratricide and bramhanahatya that they had committed during the epic [[Kurukshetra war]] of [[Mahabharata]] epic.<ref name=\"Bansal p.48-49\"/>\n\nAmong the innumerable temples in the city,  most worshipped are: the [[Kashi Vishvanath Temple]] of Shiva; the [[Sankat Mochan Hanuman Temple (Varanasi)|Sankat Mochan Hanuman Temple]]; and the Durga Temple known for the band of monkeys that reside in the large trees nearby. In addition, there are two new temples, the Tulasi Manas and the Vishvanatha temple located in the [[Banaras Hindu University]] campus. Ancient Buddhist monasteries are seen at [[Sarnath]], but they are mostly in ruins. There are also temples built by the [[Maha Bodhi Society]] and by the Chinese, Burmese, and Tibetan Buddhists.<ref name=Varun/>\n\nReligious festivals are held here. On the occasion of the [[Mahashivaratri]] (meaning great night of Shiva) a procession of Shiva is taken from the Mahamrityunjaya Temple to the Kashi Vishvanath Temple. Another popular festival is the Ganges festival held in November or December when the Ganges is venerated by [[Arti (Hinduism)|arti]] offered by thousands of pilgrims who also release lighted lamps to float in the river from the ghats (pictured). The historic event of Rama returning after 14 years of exile, termed vanavas (living in forest) in Sanskrit, and meeting his younger brother [[Bharata (Ramayana)|Bharat]] is celebrated during October or November as ''Bharat Milap'' ('Milap' means \"meeting\") festival. At the Tulsi Ghat, a classical musical soiree, particularly of [[dhrupad]] style, is held during March for 5 days where iconic artists from all parts of India are invited to perform.<ref name=Varun/>\n\nIn one sentence, [[Mark Twain]], the renowned [[Indophile]], has extolled the greatness of Varanasi thus: \"Benares is older than history, older than tradition, older even than legend, and looks twice as old as all of them put together.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Twain |first=Mark | authorlink = Mark Twain |title=Following the Equator: A journey around the world |url=\nhttp://www.literaturecollection.com/a/twain/following-equator/\n|accessdate=2007-02-07 |year=1897 |publisher=Hartford, Connecticut, American Pub. Co. |isbn=0-404-01577-8 | oclc = 577051 |chapter=L | chapterurl = http://www.literaturecollection.com/a/twain/following-equator/51/\n}}</ref>\n\nVaranasi is {{convert|780|km|mi}} from Delhi, the national capital and {{convert|300|km|mi}}  from Lucknow, the provincial capital of Uttar Pradesh.<ref name= distance/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mapsofindia.com/distances/lucknow.html|title=Distance Chart from Lucknow to over Hundreds of Cities & Towns (Highways in km)|accessdate=2009-08-22}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Varanasi panorama.jpg|1800px|alt=Varanasi|[[Varanasi]] or Kashi, the holiest and most ancient of the Sapta Puri.}}\n\n==Ayodhya==\n[[File:A View of Part of the City of Oudh.jpg|thumb|left| A view of [[Ayodhya]] in 1783 then called [[Oudh]], [[Utter pradesh]] ]]\nAyodhya ({{coord|26.8|N|82.2|E}}) is the legendary place where god [[Rama]] was born and it is also sometimes referred to as [[Ram Janmabhoomi]] (\"Rama's birth place\"). The modern town is located on the banks of river [[Sarayu]], also spelt Saryu. There is a surfeit of temples in this town, numbering over 100. Some of the important ones are: Temple of Rama and his wife [[Sita]], called the Kanak Bhavan; [[Hanuman]] temple called the Hanuman Garhi on top of a hill where, apart from a Hanuman statue in a sitting posture, there is also a {{convert|6|in|cm}} tall image of Hanuman always bedecked by flowers; the Kshireshwaranath temple of Sita, established by [[Kausalya]], Rama's mother. In addition, there are several kunds or ponds and ghats (bathing steps to approach river or tank water level) with linkage to mythological characters; such as the [[Brahma]] kund built in honour of Brahma's visit here, Sita kund, [[Bharat (Ramyana)|Bharat]] kund, [[Lakshman]] ghat where Lakshman, Rama's brother took bath, Rama ghat (also called Swargadwar meaning gateway to heaven).<ref name=Bansal/><ref name=\"SinghBindloss2007\" /><ref name=Ring>{{Cite book |last1=Ring |first1=Trudy |last2=Salkin |first2=Robert M. |last3=Schellinger |first3=Paul E. |last4=La Boda |first4=Sharon |title= International Dictionary of Historic Places: Asia and Oceania |work=Ayodhya|pages=47\u201350|accessdate=2009-08-10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vWLRxJEU49EC&pg=PA435&dq=Kanchipuram#v=onepage&q=Kanchipuram&f=false|publisher= Taylor & Francis|year= 1996|isbn= 9781884964046}}</ref>\n\nThere is a legend related to [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]], son of Rama, in support of the Nageshwaranath temple here. The armlet, which Kusha had lost in the Sarayu river was found by a nag-kanya (a damsel of the serpent family), a devotee of god Shiva, who fell in love with Kusha. A temple was built by Kusha in her honour and is stated to be the only surviving ancient temple dated to the reign of [[Vikramaditya]].<ref>Bansal p.39</ref>\n\nThe historic legacy of this place is traced to sixth century BC, as established by archaeological and literary references. Ramayana epic is traced to late centuries of BC of the [[Ikshvaku Dynasty]] and early centuries of AD. [[Dasaratha]], father of Rama belonged to this dynasty.<ref name=Ring/>\n\nIt is also the place where the [[Babri Masjid]] was built by the [[Mughals]] in the 16th century (since destroyed in 1992),<ref name=Bansal/> which has been described in the [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] 1986 edition as: \"Rama\u2019s birthplace, is marked by a mosque, erected by the Moghul emperor Babar in 1528 on the site of an earlier temple\".<ref>15th edition of the Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, 1986, entry \"Ayodhya\", Chicago: Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Inc.</ref> This is an issue under intense debate and the matter is subjudice since a special Ayodhya Bench of the [[Lucknow]] [[High Court]] is addressing the dispute.<ref name=\"Ring\"/>\n\nRoad distances from Ayodhya to Delhi is {{convert|799|km|mi}}, to Lucknow {{convert|134|km|mi}} and to Varanasi {{convert|209|km|mi}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oktatabyebye.com/travel-directions/driving-directions-from-New_Delhi-to-Ayodhya.html|title=How to reach Ayodhya from New Delhi|accessdate=2009-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.whereincity.com/india/uttar-pradesh/ayodhya.php|title=India Information|accessdate=2009-08-22}}</ref>\n\n==Mathura==\n[[File:Krishna Killing King Kamsa and Balarama Slaying a Wrestler LACMA AC1995.163.1.jpg|thumb|200px|Krishna kills his uncle [[Kamsa|Kansa]], the evil king of Mathura, at Mathura.]]\nMathura ({{coord|27.45|N|77.72|E}}), [[Utter pradesh]] located on the right bank of the [[Yamuna River]] in the district headquarters of Mathura district, also called Mathura Mandala or [[Braj Bhoomi]], is considered the heart of Indian culture. Krishna was born here and hence it is also popularly known as 'Krishnajanmabhoomi' (\"Krishna's birth place\").<ref name=Schweig>{{cite book|last=Schweig|first=G.M.|title=Dance of divine love: The Rasa Lila of Krishna from the Bhagavata Purana, India's classic sacred love story.|publisher=Princeton University Press, Princeton, NJ; Oxford|year=2005|isbn=0-691-11446-3}}p. 2</ref><ref name=Singh>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Surendra|title=Urbanization in Garhwal Himalaya: a geographical interpretation |work=Growth patern in haridwar|pages=160\u2013162|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X4FsjWPEeM4C&pg=PA160&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=h0h-Svv3BpqUkAT2jpSPCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher=M.D. Publications Pvt. Ltd.|year=1995|isbn= 9788185880693}}</ref>\n\nMathura is replete with several historic events. Based on archeological findings of ancient pottery, tools and tackles, Mathura's ancient history has been traced to about 1200 BC. [[Vedic period|Vedic]] and [[Puranas|Puranic]] literature also link founding of Mathura by [[Shatrughna]] (youngest brother of Rama). The Puranas also mention about two clans namely, Andhaka and Vrsni, the later clan was more organized under Krishna, attesting to historic linkage to the period between sixth century and fifth century BC. Mauryan empire's influence from the fourth century BC, when there was domination of Jain and Buddhist religious culture, have been noted from the sculptures recorded in Mathura. From this period, it has been inferred that \"the city had a significant impact on the development of figurative sculpture elsewhere in the country\". It was also a commercial hub during this period, imbibing composite culture and religious ethos, apart from establishing a prospering commerce both within and across the borders of the region. Following the [[Maurya]]n rule, the [[Kushans]] ruled till 3rd century AD when the sacred and secular life styles coalesced. Then a number of rulers followed, with the [[Gupta empire]] under [[Samudra Gupta]] ruling between 330 AD and 380 AD. During the Gupta empire, which lasted till sixth century AD, there was decline in the prosperity of Mathura. The [[Huns]] sacked the city in the sixth century. Thereafter, the city was controlled by [[Maukhari Dynasty]] of [[Kanauj]] when the Krishna cult evolved from the 7th century onwards to make the city a hub of Krishna worship in the country. Then [[Mahmud of Ghazni]] invaded and ransacked Mathura and decamped with all religious treasures made of gold and silver. This was followed by ushering in the rule of [[Slave Dynasty]] or [[Delhi Sultanate]] from 1193 AD and subsequently by the [[Mughal Dynasty]] rule, which lasted till the [[United Kingdom|British]] took over.  The Mughal rule, in particular of [[Aurangzeb]] saw the highest level of persecution, when in 1669 the Keshava temple was demolished and in its place a mosque was built. Even though the [[jat]] community of the region tried unsuccessfully to restore some of the temples but repeated Muslim depredation continued and it was not until the [[British Raj]] came into effect, after the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857|Sepoy Mutiny]] in 1857, that Krishna worship in Mathura got a reprieve. British archeologists were successful in recreating the ancient historicity of the city and providing insight to Indian culture. Krishna temples and ancient history are now both major attractions of the city.<ref>Ring p.572-57</ref>\n\nThe present [[Keshav Dev Temple]] has been built at the same location where several major temples had been built in the 5000 years of hoary past, which is traced to the Vajranabha, the great grandson of Krishna. A grand temple was rebuilt during the reign of [[Chandragupta II|Chandra Gupta]] [[Vikramaditya]] in the 5th century that was sacked by Mahmud of Ghazni. Thereafter, at the same location Raja Veer Singh Deva Bundela had built a {{convert|250|ft|m}} high temple during [[Jahangir]]'s reign, which was also destroyed by [[Aurangzeb]] in 1669 and a mosque built in its place, which can be seen adjoining the present temple. The present temple (see picture in infobox) was completed in 1958 with installation of images of [[Radha Krishna]]. In the adjoining altars several images have been installed; on the left altar images of [[Jagannath]] (a form of Krishna), [[Balarama]] (Krishna's brother) and [[Subhadra]] (Krishna's sister) are seen; on the right altar idols of Rama, Sita and Lakshman are installed, right across there is a Hanuman idol. Images of Shiva and goddess Durga are also seen within the main temple foyer. The main temple complex also has a small shrine where Krishna was born (said to be the prison where he was born)  depicting images of [[Vasudeva]], [[Devaki]] and four-armed Krishna.<ref name = \"bansal4043\">Bansal p.40-43</ref>\n\nOn the bank of the [[Yamuna River]], at Vishrama ghat [[aarti]] is offered every evening to the river, since it is stated to be the location where Krishna rested after slaying King [[Kamsa]], his maternal uncle. Images of goddess [[Yami|Yamuna]] and her brother [[Yama]], the god of death, are also located here.<ref name = \"bansal4043\"/>\n\nThere are many other temples of importance to pilgrims within Mathura, to name only a few, such as the [[Prem Mandir Vrindavan]], Govindji temple, Madan Mohan temple, Radha Damodar temple, Radha Gopinath temple, Banke Bihari temple, Krishna Balarama temple, Rangaji temple and Seva Kunja. Also, in the nearby [[Vrindavan]] where Krishna spent his childhood days, there is a galaxy of temples (said to be 5000), which is also a very pious place for pilgrims. It is {{convert|12|km|mi}} away from Mathura.<ref name = \"bansal4043\"/>\n\nOther important religious events observed by pilgrims in the precincts of Mathura and Vrindavan are the Vrindavan [[parikrama|Parikrama (religious practice)]] (circumambulation around the temples along a prescribed path) and the Braj Mandal parikrama during October\u2013November, which takes 3 months to complete on foot, as it includes going round the [[Govardhan]] hill, apart from several other shrines.<ref name = \"bansal4043\"/>\n\nIt is located about {{convert|50|km|mi}} north of [[Agra]], and {{convert|150|km|mi}} south of [[Delhi]]; about {{convert|20|km|mi}} from holy [[Vrindavan]].<ref name=Schweig/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Char Dham]]\n*[[Chota Char Dham]]\n* [[Jyotirlinga]]\n\n==Places at a Glance==\n* Haridwar -Hari (Form of Vishnu)\n* Ayodhya- Ayodhyanath, Vijayaraghava Rama (Form of Lord Rama)\n* Kancheepuram- Devi Kamakshi (Form of Goddess Parvati, Shakti)\n* Varanasi(or Kashi)- Kashi Vishwanath (Form of Shiva)\n* Mathura- Shri Gowardhan Krishna (Form of Krishna)\n* Ujjain- Shri Mahakaleshwar (Form of Shiva)\n* Dwarka- Shri Dwarkadheesh (Form of Krishna)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Hindu holy cities}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu holy cities]]\n", "text_old": "A List of Seven Holy Pilgrimage Sites in Hinduism, which bless the Pilgrims with Moksha (Liberation from Cycle of Birth and Death).{{Sapta Puri}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n\nThe '''Sapta Puri''' are seven holy pilgrimage centres in India. The [[Tirtha (Hinduism)|tirtha]]s are: [[Ayodhya]] [Ayodyapuri] ([[Vishnu]] as [[Rama]]), [[Mathura]] [Madurapuri] ([[Vishnu]] as [[Krishna]]), [[Haridwar]] [Mayapuri] ([[Shakti]] as [[Maya Devi Temple, Haridwar|Mayadevi]]), [[Varanasi]] [Kasipuri] ([[Shiva]] as [[Kashi Vishwanath Temple|Vishwanath]]), [[Kanchipuram]] [Kanchipuri] ([[Durga]] as [[Kamakshi]]), [[Ujjain]] [Avantikapuri] ([[Shiva]] as [[Mahakaleshwar]]), [[Dwarka]] [Dwarakapuri] ([[Vishnu]] as [[Krishna]]).<ref name=Bansal>{{Cite book|last=Bansal|first=Sunita Pant| title=Hindu Pilgrimage |work=Teertha|pages=6\u20139 & 34\u201335|accessdate=2009-08-07|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=F303Zb7EC0kC&pg=PT34&dq=panch+prayag&as_brr=3&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=panch%20prayag&f=false|publisher=Pustak Mahal|year=2008|isbn= 9788122309973}}</ref><ref name=Morgan>{{Cite book|last=Morgan|first= Kenneth W|author2=D S Sarma |title= The Religion of the Hindus |work= Sacred Pilgrimage Places|pages=188\u2013191|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ulz9mO9cK54C&pg=PA189&dq=Ujjain&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=Ujjain&f=false|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass Publ|year=1987|isbn= 9788120803879}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://amirdham.com/documents/sri_maha_rudra_yagna.pdf|title=The efficacy of Sri \u2018Maha rudra\u2019 Yagna|last=Guruji Kalyanarama Iyer|first=|date=|website=amirtham.com|page=18|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Sapta Puri are places of birth of religious and spiritual masters, places where gods have descended as [[avatar]]s (incarnations) such as Ayodhya where [[Rama]] was born, and places considered as ''Nitya tirthas'', naturally endowed, with spiritual powers since ages such as Varanasi and Haridwar. Kanchipuram is known for its [[Kamakshi Amman Temple]] dedicated to the mother goddess. Dwarka represents the place where god [[Krishna]], after leaving Mathura spent 100 years before He left for his divine abode from here, according to the epic [[Mahabharata]]. Mathura is the embodiment of events in the life of Krishna during his childhood and young days. Haridwar with shrines of both [[Shiva]] and Vishnu, represents the gateway to [[Uttarakhand]], as the sacred river [[Ganges]] emerges from the hills into the plains at this place. Varanasi is the place of salvation as it is strongly believed that death at this place will bring salvation. [[Varanasi]] is the holiest of all and it is favorite to lord [[Shiva]], thus it is often referred as ''City of Lord Shiva''. In Hinduism, one should visit the major temples in Varanasi in his/her life. Ujjain, also known by the ancient name Avanti, has one of the 12 [[Jyotirlingas]] installed in the [[Mahakaleshwar Temple]]. Each of these cities is also famous for the spectacular melas or fairs held. Haridwar and Ujjain are famous for the [[Kumbh Mela]] held once every 12 years. Marriage festival of [[Kamakshi]] at Kanchipuram is a special occasion. [[Krishna Janmashtami]] ( birth day of Krishna - generally held in August as per Hindu calendar) is a special occasion in Dwarka and Mathura.<ref name=Bansal/><ref name=Morgan/>\nThe seven religious cities are within India's territorial ambit and pilgrimage to these places greatly enhances the unity of the nation, in spite of its linguistic and cultural diversity. The seven sacred urban centers are well connected by road, rail and air transport with the rest of the country.<ref name=Bansal/>\n\n==Haridwar==\n[[File:Clock Tower, at Har-ki-Pauri, Haridwar.jpg|thumb|left|Har-ki-Pauri at Haridwar]]\n\"Haridwar\", also written as \"Hardwar\", literally means \"gateway to god Vishnu (Hari)\" or \"gateway to god Shiva (Har)\". It is the holiest city in the state of [[Uttarakhand]]. It is strategically located ({{coord|29.96|N|78.16|E}}) on the western bank of the river [[Ganges]] as it emerges into the plains at the exact location where the Har-Ki-Pauri ghat has been built to facilitate pilgrims to take a holy bath. It is thus also called the ''Gangadwara'', the place where the Ganges descends to the plains. Every year, thousands of people flock to Haridwar, also called Hardwar, to bathe at the Har-Ki-Pauri ghat (ghat is an embankment structure built out of stone slabs leading to the river edge to facilitate bathing) since it is believed that the feet of Vishnu is imprinted on a rock preserved here. Every evening at sun set time at the ghat, thousands of pilgrims offer [[Arti (Hinduism)|arti]], a Hindu ritual of offering lights of earthen lamps on small floating leaf holders with flowers, as the temple bells reverberate amidst chanting of hymns.<ref name=\"Bansal p.44-47\">Bansal p.44-47</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttp://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/vp/vp043.htm|title=SACRIFICE OF DAKSHA 1 (From the Vayu Purana)|accessdate=2009-08-16|publisher= The Vishnu Purana, translated by [[Horace Hayman Wilson]], 1840. p. 62, 62:2}}</ref><ref name=Hoiberg>{{Cite book|last=Hoiberg|first=Dale|author2=Indu Ramchandani |title=Students' Britannica India|work=Haridwar|pages=248|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AE_LIg9G5CgC&pg=PA248&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=h0h-Svv3BpqUkAT2jpSPCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher=Popular Prakashan|year= 2000|isbn= 9780852297605}}</ref>\n\nLegend from Hindu scriptures state that Haridwar is one among the four sites where drops of [[Amrita]], the elixir of immortality, accidentally spilled over from the pitcher, in which it was being carried away by the celestial bird [[Garuda]], after the [[Samudra manthan]] (churning of the ocean); the other three places are said to be Ujjain, [[Nasik]], and [[Allahabad]].<ref name=Harid>{{Cite web|url=http://sahajaharidwar.tripod.com/About_Haridwar.html|title=About Haridwar|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher=sahajaharidwar.com}}</ref>\n\nAnother legend narrated for this pilgrim place is that sage [[Kapila]] had cursed the ancestors of prince [[Bhagiratha]]. Bhagiratha, therefore, wanted to atone for their sins by performing penance to god Shiva here. Shiva pleased with the prayers of Bhagiratha, allowed the Ganges to trickle through his locks and fall on earth from heaven.<ref name=Davidson>{{Cite book|last=Davidson|first=Linda Kay|author2=David Martin Gitlitz  |title= Pilgrimage |work= Haridwar (Uttar Pradesh, India: Hinduism Seventh century)|pages =228\u2013229|accessdate=2009-08-10|url=\nhttps://books.google.com/books?id=YVYkrNhPMQkC&pg=PT258&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=q1x-SoiED5-qkASVvdiWCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year= 2002|isbn= 9781576070048}}</ref>\n\nIt is from here that the Ganges emerging out of the [[Siwalik Hills|Shivalik]] hills of the Rudra-[[Himalayas]] travels a distance of {{convert|2000|km|mi}} through the fertile Gangetic plains of [[North India]]. It is also the site where the river has been tapped for beneficial uses of irrigation and hydro-power generation by a complex system of barrages (low gated weirs) with large canal systems. Its hoary history, closely spun around the epic [[Mahabharata]] (also substantiated in the travelogues of the Chinese chronicler [[Hiuen Tsang]]), records that [[Timurlane]] had ransacked this town in the year 1399 AD. Apart from the holy ghat, there are a large number of temples in the city dedicated to Shiva, goddess [[Shakti]] or [[Durga]] (a cable car way has been built to approach this temple, apart from the ancient approach by steps over the hills), Vishnu and a galaxy of other deities. It is the pious location where, Hindus from all parts of the country, particularly North India, immerse ashes of the dead and perform last rites.<ref name=Davidson/><ref name=Bradnock>{{Cite book|last=Bradnock|first= Roma|title= Indian Himalaya handbook |work=Haridwar|pages=103\u2013105|accessdate=2009-08-10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TyZGp_YVzb8C&pg=PA109&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=P2B-SqiEA5uOkQTylZStCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher= Footprint Travel Guides|year=2000|isbn= 9781900949798}}</ref>\n\nApart from the regular annual pilgrimage season from April to November, during February\u2013March ''Magh Mela'' ('mela' means \"fair\") is also held on a large scale. Other spectacular events that are held here are the Ardh Kumbha Mela  (half Kumbh Mela) held every six years. The 12 years cycle [[Kumbh Mela]] is held during January or February depending on the Hindu [[Panchanga|Calmanac]]. It is the occasion when lakhs of people congregate here for a holy dip in the Ganges.<ref name=\"Bansal p.44-47\"/><ref name=Davidson/><ref name=Bradnock/><ref name=\"SinghBindloss2007\">{{cite book |last1=Singh |first1=Sarina |last2=Bindloss |first2=Joe |last3=Bainbridge |first3=James |last4=Brown |first4=Lindsay |last5=Elliott |first5=Mark |last6=Butler |first6=Stuart |display-authors=2 |date=2007 |title=India |publisher=Lonely Planet |page=[https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetindi00sari/page/454 454] |isbn=978-1-74104-308-2 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lonelyplanetindi00sari/page/454 }}</ref> The Kumbh Mela (literal meaning is ('festival of pots') is the \"confluence of faith\" since lakhs of people irrespective of their caste affiliations attend it. Astrological combination of planets decide the date for the event; generally when Jupiter, Sun and Moon are in the same zodiacal sign of the Aquarius, but in Haridwar it is fixed when Sun is in Aries and Jupiter in Aquarius, which is called the 'Vaishaki snan' ([[Vaisakha|Vaishakha]] is the second month of Hindu calendar and ''snan'' means bathing).<ref name=Mishra>{{Cite book|last=Mishra|first=J.S.|title=Pilgrimage, purification and piety |work=Mahakumbh, the greatest show on earth|pages=14\u201320|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1pCXqynwwQcC&pg=PA14&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=1GR-SsTHC5PolQT2peCuCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher=Har-Anand Publications|year=2004|isbn= 9788124109939}}</ref>\n\n{{location map+|India|float=right|width=375|caption=Location of Sapta Puri.\n|places=\n{{Location map~|India|label='''Ayodhya'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=bottom|lat=26.80|long=82.20}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Mathura'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=27.29|long=77.40}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Haridwar'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=29.956|long=78.17}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Varanasi'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=25.28|long=82.96}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Kanchipuram'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=12.82|long=79.71}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Ujjain'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=23.18|long=75.77}}\n{{location map~|India|label='''Dwarka'''|mark=Green_pog.svg|position=right|lat=22.23|long=68.97}}\n}}\nA lyrical poetic expression of the place by Mavis Jones, which succinctly describes the environment and the religiosity of the pilgrims is quoted below.<ref name=Jones>{{Cite book|last=Jones|first=Mavis|title=her festival clothes|work =Poem haridwar|page=10|accessdate=2009-08-10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VEz2w6LYxbwC&pg=PA10&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=q1x-SoiED5-qkASVvdiWCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press -MQUP|year=2001|isbn= 9780773519091}}</ref>\n\nA green so light, not jade, not sky.<br>\nIce water rushed out of the Himalayan<br>\nsilence into this wide scarred channel.\n\nAlong the other shore ashrams<br>\nare seashell-coloured, beige,<br>\ncream, coral, sea green.\n\nThe pilgrims who wash on the flooded steps<br>\nemerge new from the sacred waters.<br>\nThey are transfigured in scarlet,\n\nsaffron, emerald. Even the birds<br>\nare blessed with such colour.<br>\nThe kingfisher is as royal\n\nas any prince his ''gazi'' a white-fronted<br>\nwaterhen in grey and russet.<br>\nNow the song rich as honey,\n\nof the black-headed oriole<br>\ncalling pilgrims out of the dry land.<br>\nThis benediction of water, overflowing.\n\nAs many gods are here, as many devotees<br>\nas specks of sun-lit dust rising<br>\nfrom a cremation ghat.\n\nHaridwar is at a road distance of {{convert|214|km|mi}} from Delhi, the capital of the nation, and {{convert|52|km|mi}} from [[Dehradun]], the provincial capital of Uttarakhand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uttaranchalonline.info/Garhwal/Haridwar/Distance_From_Haridwar.html|title=Distances from Haridwar|accessdate=2009-08-13}}</ref>\n\n==Dwarka==\n[[File:Dwarka.jpg|thumb|left|A Painting depicting Krishna's Dwarka made during [[Akbar]]'s reign from the [[Smithsonian Institution]]]]\n[[Krishna]], an incarnation of god Vishnu, is believed to have migrated from Mathura to Dwarka ({{coord|22.23|N|68.97|E}}) 5000 years ago and made Dwarka his capital., as noted in the scripture [[Bhagavata Purana]].<ref name=\"Bansal p.10 & 20\">Bansal p.10 & 20</ref> He established the city on the bank of the [[Gomti River]]. But after the death of Krishna, there was downfall of his dynasty, [[Yadava dynasty|the Yadavas]]. This was further compounded by floods and eventual submergence of Krishna's city in the [[Arabian Sea]]. Presently, Dwarka is a small city located at the western tip of [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] peninsular in [[Gujarat]] state on the shores of the Arabian Sea.<ref name=\"Bansal p.10 & 20\"/><ref name=guju>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=224|title=Dwarka|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher= Gujarat Tourism}}</ref>\n\nChronology of the recorded historic events witnessed at the temple city linked directly to the temple, is dated from 400 B.C. when Vajranabha built an umbrella type temple and deified his grand father Krishna's image there. It has undergone several changes with times under different rulers and in 800 AD, [[Adi Shankara]]charya is said to have got the [[Dwarkadheesh temple, Gujrat|Dwarakadheesh temple]] renovated and also added a shrine of goddess Adya Shakti. Over the next few centuries more renovations took place with grant of additional land till 1261 AD, when the temple was destroyed by Mohamed Shah. In subsequent years also, renovation took place but there was dispute between two groups for the control of the temple. In 1504, [[Vallabhacharya]] established the image of Dwarakadeesh in a well in Ladva village to protect it from Muslim marauders and again it was shifted to [[Dungarpur]] where the temple was renovated. In 1861, Maharaja Khanderao renovated the temple. During British rule, the temple tower was rebuilt. A golden pitcher was fixed on the temple tower by Maharaja [[Gaekwad]] in the year 1903 and further renovations were undertaken by the then Shankarachrya of Dwarka Peet. Since 1960, the conservation of the temple is under the control of the Government of India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dwarkadhish.org/little-history.aspx|title=Events|accessdate=2009-08-13|publisher=Dwarkadhish.org Official Website of Jagad Mandir \u2013 Dwarka}}</ref>\n\nThe present Dwarakhadheesh temple, also called the Jagat Mandir (universal shrine) or ''trilok sundar'' (most beautiful in all three worlds), is a seven storied structure, {{convert|43|m|ft}} in height, appears to be raising above the Arabian sea. It is dated to the 13th century AD on the basis of oceanographic explorations undertaken to trace the ancient temple, which was submerged in the Arabian sea. The elegantly carved temple [[shikara]] (tower) is adorned with a huge flag, which is said to be {{convert|52|yard|ft}} in length with seven colours that can be seen flying from a distance of {{convert|10|km|mi}} (hoisting this flag has a great religious significance). There is an approach to the back side of the temple from the Gomti River end, which is built of 56 steps. The temple built in soft limestone has a sanctum enclosed within a large hall with covered entrance from three sides. While the external carvings depict erotic scenes, the temple sanctum is austere in design but the main image is elaborately ornamented.<ref name =Dwar>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=227&webpartid=872|title= Dwarkadhish Temple|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher=Gujarat Tourism}}</ref><ref name=submerge>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dwarkadhish.org/about-us/dwarka-nagari/submerged-dwarka/|title=Dwarka Nagari - Submerged Dwarka|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher=Dwarkadhish.org Official Website of Jagad Mandir \u2013 Dwarka}}</ref>\n\nA temple dedicated to [[Rukmini]], Krishna's consort, is located in Bet Dwarka, {{convert|2|km|mi}}  away from Dwarka. The temple is said to be 2500 years old but in its present form it is inferred to be of 12th century vintage. It is a richly carved temple decorated with sculptures of gods and goddesses on the exterior with the sanctum housing the main image of Rukmini. Carved ''naratharas'' (human figures) and carved ''gajatharas'' (elephants) are depicted in panels at the base of the tower. An interesting legend is narrated to justify separate dwelling temples, far away from each other, for Rukmini and her husband Krishna. It is said that at the request of sage [[Durvasa]] (who was renowned for his short temper and bestowing curses) Krishna and Rukmini pulled a chariot taking sage Durvasa to their house for dinner. On the way, when Rukmini asked for water to quench her thirst, Krishna drew Ganges water, by prodding the ground with his toe, for her to drink. Rukmini quenched her thirst with the Ganges water. But Durvasa felt insulted since Rukmini did not have the courtesy to offer him water to drink. He, therefore, cursed her that she would live separately from her husband.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gujarattourism.com/showpage.aspx?contentid=227&webpartid=877|title=Rukmini Devi Temple |accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher= Gujarat Tourism}}</ref><ref name=Myths>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dwarkadhish.org/popular-myths.aspx|title=Dwarka Nagari - Popular Myths|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher=Dwarkadhish.org Official Website of Jagad Mandir \u2013 Dwarka}}</ref>\n\nAnother legend states, while Dwarka was the official capital of Krishna where he held his assembly, his residence was at Bet Dwarka.<ref name=Myths/>\n\n==Kanchipuram==\n\nKanchipuram ({{coord|12.82|N|79.71|E}}), the pilgrimage city, in [[tamil nadu]], also known as Canjeevaram during the [[United Kingdom|British]] rule, built during the [[Pallava Dynasty]] between 6th and 8th centuries, located on the bank of the [[Palar_River]], has an architectural legacy of over 1000 years. Before this period, it was the capital of early [[Cholas]] in the 2nd century BC. After the rule of the [[Pallava Dynasty]], the [[Vijayanagara empire]] and the [[Nayak (ethnic group)|Nayaka]] dynasty period followed, in that order. Prior to the Pallava reign, it is conjectured, based on the chronicles of the [[Xuanzang]], the Chinese pilgrim who visited Pallavas court, that the city was under the influence of [[Ashoka]], the [[Mauryan]] emperor in 3rd century BC. Xuanzang had also noted that [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] had visited this place. [[Jain]] and [[Buddhist]] temples and [[stupas]] of the [[Chola Dynasty]] reign have been recorded but mostly do not exist on ground. But South Indian architecture got a fillip only during the Pallava rule, particularly of rock cut temples during Mahendarvarman I's reign after he converted from Jainism to Hinduism . He was considered a man with vision and intelligence, a scholar, musician and a playwright. Kanchipuram was considered second only to Varanasi city in fame and learning. [[Adi Shankara]], the Hindu philosopher saint, who propagated the [[Advaita]] philosophy lived and taught here in the eighth century AD.<ref name=\"Ring p.435-436\">Ring p.435-436</ref><ref name=kanchi>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kanchi.tn.nic.in/dist_profile_history.html |title=Historical Importance of Kanchipuram |accessdate=2009-08-10 |publisher=National Informatic Centre, Kanchi |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090806052722/http://www.kanchi.tn.nic.in/dist_profile_history.html |archivedate=6 August 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe city has 108 [[Shaiva]] and 18 [[Vaishnava]] temples. The Hindu philosopher [[Ramanujacharya]] who propagated the [[Vishishtadvaita]] philosophy studied here. The temples are distributed in three zones of the city namely, the Vishnu temples are in the east zone, the Shiva shrines are on the outskirts of the city in the northern zone and the Jain mandirs are on the east across the Palar River.<ref name=\"Ring p.435-436\"/><ref name=brit>{{Cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/310889/Kanchipuram|title= Kanchipuram|accessdate=2009-08-10}}</ref>\n\nSome of the exquisitely designed and built temples of the Vijayanagar period in [[Vijayanagara architecture]] style are the Ekamabaranath temple tower which is {{convert|192|ft|m}} in height, and the Varadaraja Swamy temple, which has a 1000-pillar hall.<ref name=kanchi/>\n\n[[Kamakshi Amman temple]] is an ancient temple here and the most famous of all the temples in the city. It is associated with Adi Shankara. Legend has it that [[Kamakshi]] offered worship to a [[Lingam|Shivaling]] made out of sand and gained Shiva's hand in marriage. The temple covers an area of about {{convert|5|acre|ha}} and the sanctum is covered with gold plated [[Vimana]]. Kamakshi is enshrined in the temple in a sitting posture called the ''Parabramha Swaroopini'', seated with the trinity of [[Bramha]], Vishnu and Shiva.<ref>Bansal p.149</ref>\n\nIt is located {{convert|75|km|mi}} from [[Chennai]], the provincial capital of [[Tamil Nadu]] and {{convert|277|km|mi}} from [[Bangalore]], the provincial capital of [[Karnataka]]. It has a good net work of roads, rail links and transport services to all parts of the country, and the nearest domestic and international airports are at Chennai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kanchi.tn.nic.in/|title= Kanchipuram|accessdate=2009-08-10}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mustseeindia.com/driving-directions-from-Bangalore-to-Kanchipuram/travel-direction|title=Bangalore to Kanchipuram|accessdate=2009-08-22}}</ref>\n\n==Ujjain==\n[[File:Mahakal Temple Ujjain.JPG|thumb|left|Mahakal temple at Ujjain, [[Madhya Pradesh]] ]] \nUjjain ({{coord|23.182778|N|75.777222|E}}) with an ancient scriptural name of Avantika compliments both rich historical and religious traditions. The history dates its links to the period of [[Vikramaditya]] and [[Ashoka]] (3rd century BC). The religious tradition links it to god Shiva triumphing over the demon king [[Tripurasura]] and then renaming the city as Ujjainyini (meaning 'conquers with pride').<ref name=Ujjain>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ujjain.nic.in/tourist/what_to_see.htm|title=Ujjain|accessdate=2009-08-09|publisher=Ujaajin.nic.in}}</ref>\n\nUjjain, probably, also marks the spread of Hindu religious beliefs to the [[Central Asia]] region. Particular mention could be made to the reign of [[Vima Kadphises]], during the [[Kushan Dynasty]], who considered Shiva as his divine patron. During his reign, apart from the influence of [[Greece|Greek]] religious practices, worship of Shiva, in particular, was also seen as an accepted practice in [[Iran]]. This leaning is attributed to Vima Kadphises's victory over Indian territory. Inscriptions of his times in [[Iran]] establish that he had converted the temple of [[Dioscuri]] (built during Greeko \u2013 [[Bactria]]n period) at Dilberjin into a sanctuary for Shiva by decorating the place with a painting of Shiva and his wife [[Parvati]]. He got the wall painting of Shiva (''Oeso'') done by craftsmen he had taken from Ujjayani (Ujjain), apart from constructing a water conveyance system to the sanctuary of Shiva. Inscriptions further testify that the Kushan king attributed his rise to power to Srava (=Shiva) and Candavira. It is deduced that Candavira may be the same god as Candishvara, the God of Mahakala temple at Ujjain. It is also conjectured that the support of the Indian community (who worshipped Shiva) settled in eastern Iran and the encouragement he got from their priesthood, before and during his Indian campaign, and his relations with Ujjain, contributed to his deep involvement with the cult of Shiva. This devotion was continued by him even after his Indian campaign.<ref name=Harmatta>{{Cite book|last=Harmatta|first=Janos|title= History of civilizations of Central Asia | work=Religious Life under Vima Kaldphises |pages=318\u2013321|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DguGWP0vGY8C&pg=PA319&dq=Ujjain&lr=&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=Ujjain&f=false|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass Publ|year=1999|isbn= 9788120814080}}</ref><ref>Ring p.835-837</ref>\n\nEmperor Ashoka also played a significant role as the Viceroy of Ujjain in enhancing its importance. Ashoka who ruled for three decades between 268 and 233 BC started his career in [[Taxila]] (now in [[Pakistan]]) in the north west by subduing a revolt. Thereafter, his father [[Bindusara]], of the [[Mauryan Dynasty]], transferred Ashoka as his Viceroy to Ujjain, which was the famous capital of the earlier kingdom of Avanti, in [[Central India]].<ref name=Kulkae>{{Cite book|last=Kulkae|first=Hermann|author2=Dietmar Rothermund |title= A History of India |work=Ashoka the beloved to the Gods|pages=62\u201365|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V0GEtXp-GsUC&pg=PA65&dq=Ujjain&lr=&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=Ujjain&f=false|publisher= CRC Press|year=1998|isbn=  9780203443453}}</ref>\n\nIt was once the largest city and capital of [[Malwa]] region. In the ancient city of Ujjain, [[Jai Singh II of Amber|Jai Singh II]] ruled in the 18th century. Jai Singh II built an observatory here, called the [[Jantar Mantar]]. The reason for building the observatory here was that it was the centre of [[Hindu Astronomy]] since ancient times and it was located on the prime or first meridian (of longitude) established on the canons of Hindu astronomy. According to [[Indian astronomy]], the first [[meridian (geography)|meridian]] of longitude passes through Ujjain. The modern calculations have established that the [[Tropic of Cancer]] passes through Ujjain.<ref name=\"Harmatta\"/><ref>Bansal p.50-51</ref><ref name=Sharma>{{Cite book|last=Sharma|first=Virendra Nath|title= Sawai Jai Singh and His Astronomy |work=Ujjain Observatory|pages=212\u2013213|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QRA2mgZnXXMC&pg=PA212&dq=Ujjain&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=Ujjain&f=false|publisher= Motilal Banarsidass Publ.|year=1995|isbn=9788120812567 }}</ref>\n\nUjjain is about {{convert|776|km|mi}} south from [[Delhi]], the capital city of India, and {{convert|183|km|mi}} west of [[Bhopal]], the provincial capital of [[Madhya Pradesh]].<ref name= distance>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mapsofindia.org/distance-chart-india/delhi.html|title=Distances from Delhi to Metro cities in India|accessdate=2009-08-13}}</ref> It is {{convert|402|km|mi}}away from\n[[Ahmedabad]], and {{convert|655|km|mi}} north-west of [[Mumbai]].<ref name=Ujjain/>\n\n==Varanasi==\n[[File:Benares 1890.jpg|thumb|right|Famous Dashashwamedh Ghat]]\n[[File:Ganga Aarti at Varanasi ghats.jpg|right|thumb|Festival of the [[Ganges River]] worship by [[Arti (Hinduism)|arti]] at [[Dashashwamedh Ghat]], [[Utter pradesh]]]]\nVaranasi ({{coord|25.282|N|82.9563|E}}) also called Kashi, Benares, is an ancient city, said to be the oldest inhabited one. The city was known by several names such as ''Avimuktaka'', ''Anandakanana'', ''Mahasmasana'', ''Surandhana'', ''Brahma Vardha'', ''Sudarsana'', and ''Ramya''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.up-tourism.com/destination/varanasi/intro.htm | title=Uttar Pradesh Tourism - Varanasi | publisher=Department of Tourism - Government of UP | accessdate=2009-05-01 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061114082739/http://www.up-tourism.com/destination/varanasi/intro.htm | archivedate=14 November 2006 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn view of its ancient historic, cultural and religious heritage it is considered as \u201cthe most holy of the seven sacred cities of Hinduism\u201d. Its historical and religious legacy dates to the Budhha period (6th Century BC) and has been the centre of religious \u201cBrahminical learning\u201d with sages, philosophers, writers and musicians making it their home in the past several centuries. But much of its temple glory was subject to plundering and destruction by Mohammad Ghauri in the 12th century. The temples and religious institutions seen now in the city are mostly of the 18th century vintage.<ref name=online>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bl.uk/onlinegallery/onlineex/apac/photocoll/r/019pho0000050s2u00064000.html|title=Ramnath [Sumeri] Temple, Benares.|accessdate=2009-08-12|publisher=British Library On Line Gallery}}</ref>\n\nThe temples and the bathing ghats (ghats are embankments made in steps of stone slabs along the river bank where pilgrims perform ritual ablutions) are located on the left west bank of the holy [[Ganges]] river and the count of temples in the city is claimed to be 23,000 and the bathing ghats number 81. The most venerated and frequented ghats for devotional worship by the pilgrims are the Manikarnika Ghat, Harishchandra Ghat, [[Dashashwamedh Ghat]] (pictured), Assi Ghat and Panchganga Ghat. At two of the ghats (Manikarnika and Harishchandra Ghats), Hindus cremate their dead. The rivers 'Varuna' and 'Asi' combined form the name of the city \"Varanasi\". These two rivers flowing on the left bank of the Ganges enclose the old city of Varanasi. The ghats at the confluence sites of these two streams with the Ganges are also held in veneration. All these factors have contributed to the city being called the religious capital of Hinduism.<ref name=\"Bansal p.48-49\">Bansal p.48-49</ref><ref name=Varun>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9074835/Varanasi|title=Varanasi|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online]]|accessdate=2009-08-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Alexander |last=Cunningham |author2=Surendranath Majumdar Sastri  |authorlink=Alexander Cunningham |title=Ancient Geography of India |pages=131\u2013140 |publisher=Munshiram Manoharlal |origyear=1924 |year=2002 |isbn=81-215-1064-3  }}</ref>\n\nVaranasi is also known as the favourite city of the Hindu deity [[Lord Shiva]] as it has been mentioned in the [[Rigveda]] that this city in older times was known as [[Varanasi|Kashi]] or \"Shiv ki Nagri\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9074835/Varanasi |title=Varanasi |publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] |accessdate=30 October 2012}}</ref> The [[Pandavas]] went to Kashi in search of Shiva to atone for their sins of fratricide and bramhanahatya that they had committed during the epic [[Kurukshetra war]] of [[Mahabharata]] epic.<ref name=\"Bansal p.48-49\"/>\n\nAmong the innumerable temples in the city,  most worshipped are: the [[Kashi Vishvanath Temple]] of Shiva; the [[Sankat Mochan Hanuman Temple (Varanasi)|Sankat Mochan Hanuman Temple]]; and the Durga Temple known for the band of monkeys that reside in the large trees nearby. In addition, there are two new temples, the Tulasi Manas and the Vishvanatha temple located in the [[Banaras Hindu University]] campus. Ancient Buddhist monasteries are seen at [[Sarnath]], but they are mostly in ruins. There are also temples built by the [[Maha Bodhi Society]] and by the Chinese, Burmese, and Tibetan Buddhists.<ref name=Varun/>\n\nReligious festivals are held here. On the occasion of the [[Mahashivaratri]] (meaning great night of Shiva) a procession of Shiva is taken from the Mahamrityunjaya Temple to the Kashi Vishvanath Temple. Another popular festival is the Ganges festival held in November or December when the Ganges is venerated by [[Arti (Hinduism)|arti]] offered by thousands of pilgrims who also release lighted lamps to float in the river from the ghats (pictured). The historic event of Rama returning after 14 years of exile, termed vanavas (living in forest) in Sanskrit, and meeting his younger brother [[Bharata (Ramayana)|Bharat]] is celebrated during October or November as ''Bharat Milap'' ('Milap' means \"meeting\") festival. At the Tulsi Ghat, a classical musical soiree, particularly of [[dhrupad]] style, is held during March for 5 days where iconic artists from all parts of India are invited to perform.<ref name=Varun/>\n\nIn one sentence, [[Mark Twain]], the renowned [[Indophile]], has extolled the greatness of Varanasi thus: \"Benares is older than history, older than tradition, older even than legend, and looks twice as old as all of them put together.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Twain |first=Mark | authorlink = Mark Twain |title=Following the Equator: A journey around the world |url=\nhttp://www.literaturecollection.com/a/twain/following-equator/\n|accessdate=2007-02-07 |year=1897 |publisher=Hartford, Connecticut, American Pub. Co. |isbn=0-404-01577-8 | oclc = 577051 |chapter=L | chapterurl = http://www.literaturecollection.com/a/twain/following-equator/51/\n}}</ref>\n\nVaranasi is {{convert|780|km|mi}} from Delhi, the national capital and {{convert|300|km|mi}}  from Lucknow, the provincial capital of Uttar Pradesh.<ref name= distance/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mapsofindia.com/distances/lucknow.html|title=Distance Chart from Lucknow to over Hundreds of Cities & Towns (Highways in km)|accessdate=2009-08-22}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Varanasi panorama.jpg|1800px|alt=Varanasi|[[Varanasi]] or Kashi, the holiest and most ancient of the Sapta Puri.}}\n\n==Ayodhya==\n[[File:A View of Part of the City of Oudh.jpg|thumb|left| A view of [[Ayodhya]] in 1783 then called [[Oudh]], [[Utter pradesh]] ]]\nAyodhya ({{coord|26.8|N|82.2|E}}) is the legendary place where god [[Rama]] was born and it is also sometimes referred to as [[Ram Janmabhoomi]] (\"Rama's birth place\"). The modern town is located on the banks of river [[Sarayu]], also spelt Saryu. There is a surfeit of temples in this town, numbering over 100. Some of the important ones are: Temple of Rama and his wife [[Sita]], called the Kanak Bhavan; [[Hanuman]] temple called the Hanuman Garhi on top of a hill where, apart from a Hanuman statue in a sitting posture, there is also a {{convert|6|in|cm}} tall image of Hanuman always bedecked by flowers; the Kshireshwaranath temple of Sita, established by [[Kausalya]], Rama's mother. In addition, there are several kunds or ponds and ghats (bathing steps to approach river or tank water level) with linkage to mythological characters; such as the [[Brahma]] kund built in honour of Brahma's visit here, Sita kund, [[Bharat (Ramyana)|Bharat]] kund, [[Lakshman]] ghat where Lakshman, Rama's brother took bath, Rama ghat (also called Swargadwar meaning gateway to heaven).<ref name=Bansal/><ref name=\"SinghBindloss2007\" /><ref name=Ring>{{Cite book |last1=Ring |first1=Trudy |last2=Salkin |first2=Robert M. |last3=Schellinger |first3=Paul E. |last4=La Boda |first4=Sharon |title= International Dictionary of Historic Places: Asia and Oceania |work=Ayodhya|pages=47\u201350|accessdate=2009-08-10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vWLRxJEU49EC&pg=PA435&dq=Kanchipuram#v=onepage&q=Kanchipuram&f=false|publisher= Taylor & Francis|year= 1996|isbn= 9781884964046}}</ref>\n\nThere is a legend related to [[Kusha (Ramayana)|Kusha]], son of Rama, in support of the Nageshwaranath temple here. The armlet, which Kusha had lost in the Sarayu river was found by a nag-kanya (a damsel of the serpent family), a devotee of god Shiva, who fell in love with Kusha. A temple was built by Kusha in her honour and is stated to be the only surviving ancient temple dated to the reign of [[Vikramaditya]].<ref>Bansal p.39</ref>\n\nThe historic legacy of this place is traced to sixth century BC, as established by archaeological and literary references. Ramayana epic is traced to late centuries of BC of the [[Ikshvaku Dynasty]] and early centuries of AD. [[Dasaratha]], father of Rama belonged to this dynasty.<ref name=Ring/>\n\nIt is also the place where the [[Babri Masjid]] was built by the [[Mughals]] in the 16th century (since destroyed in 1992),<ref name=Bansal/> which has been described in the [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]] 1986 edition as: \"Rama\u2019s birthplace, is marked by a mosque, erected by the Moghul emperor Babar in 1528 on the site of an earlier temple\".<ref>15th edition of the Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica, 1986, entry \"Ayodhya\", Chicago: Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Inc.</ref> This is an issue under intense debate and the matter is subjudice since a special Ayodhya Bench of the [[Lucknow]] [[High Court]] is addressing the dispute.<ref name=\"Ring\"/>\n\nRoad distances from Ayodhya to Delhi is {{convert|799|km|mi}}, to Lucknow {{convert|134|km|mi}} and to Varanasi {{convert|209|km|mi}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oktatabyebye.com/travel-directions/driving-directions-from-New_Delhi-to-Ayodhya.html|title=How to reach Ayodhya from New Delhi|accessdate=2009-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.whereincity.com/india/uttar-pradesh/ayodhya.php|title=India Information|accessdate=2009-08-22}}</ref>\n\n==Mathura==\n[[File:Krishna Killing King Kamsa and Balarama Slaying a Wrestler LACMA AC1995.163.1.jpg|thumb|200px|Krishna kills his uncle [[Kamsa|Kansa]], the evil king of Mathura, at Mathura.]]\nMathura ({{coord|27.45|N|77.72|E}}), [[Utter pradesh]] located on the right bank of the [[Yamuna River]] in the district headquarters of Mathura district, also called Mathura Mandala or [[Braj Bhoomi]], is considered the heart of Indian culture. Krishna was born here and hence it is also popularly known as 'Krishnajanmabhoomi' (\"Krishna's birth place\").<ref name=Schweig>{{cite book|last=Schweig|first=G.M.|title=Dance of divine love: The Rasa Lila of Krishna from the Bhagavata Purana, India's classic sacred love story.|publisher=Princeton University Press, Princeton, NJ; Oxford|year=2005|isbn=0-691-11446-3}}p. 2</ref><ref name=Singh>{{Cite book|last=Singh|first=Surendra|title=Urbanization in Garhwal Himalaya: a geographical interpretation |work=Growth patern in haridwar|pages=160\u2013162|accessdate=2009-08-09|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X4FsjWPEeM4C&pg=PA160&dq=Haridwar&lr=&ei=h0h-Svv3BpqUkAT2jpSPCg#v=onepage&q=Haridwar&f=false|publisher=M.D. Publications Pvt. Ltd.|year=1995|isbn= 9788185880693}}</ref>\n\nMathura is replete with several historic events. Based on archeological findings of ancient pottery, tools and tackles, Mathura's ancient history has been traced to about 1200 BC. [[Vedic period|Vedic]] and [[Puranas|Puranic]] literature also link founding of Mathura by [[Shatrughna]] (youngest brother of Rama). The Puranas also mention about two clans namely, Andhaka and Vrsni, the later clan was more organized under Krishna, attesting to historic linkage to the period between sixth century and fifth century BC. Mauryan empire's influence from the fourth century BC, when there was domination of Jain and Buddhist religious culture, have been noted from the sculptures recorded in Mathura. From this period, it has been inferred that \"the city had a significant impact on the development of figurative sculpture elsewhere in the country\". It was also a commercial hub during this period, imbibing composite culture and religious ethos, apart from establishing a prospering commerce both within and across the borders of the region. Following the [[Maurya]]n rule, the [[Kushans]] ruled till 3rd century AD when the sacred and secular life styles coalesced. Then a number of rulers followed, with the [[Gupta empire]] under [[Samudra Gupta]] ruling between 330 AD and 380 AD. During the Gupta empire, which lasted till sixth century AD, there was decline in the prosperity of Mathura. The [[Huns]] sacked the city in the sixth century. Thereafter, the city was controlled by [[Maukhari Dynasty]] of [[Kanauj]] when the Krishna cult evolved from the 7th century onwards to make the city a hub of Krishna worship in the country. Then [[Mahmud of Ghazni]] invaded and ransacked Mathura and decamped with all religious treasures made of gold and silver. This was followed by ushering in the rule of [[Slave Dynasty]] or [[Delhi Sultanate]] from 1193 AD and subsequently by the [[Mughal Dynasty]] rule, which lasted till the [[United Kingdom|British]] took over.  The Mughal rule, in particular of [[Aurangzeb]] saw the highest level of persecution, when in 1669 the Keshava temple was demolished and in its place a mosque was built. Even though the [[jat]] community of the region tried unsuccessfully to restore some of the temples but repeated Muslim depredation continued and it was not until the [[British Raj]] came into effect, after the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857|Sepoy Mutiny]] in 1857, that Krishna worship in Mathura got a reprieve. British archeologists were successful in recreating the ancient historicity of the city and providing insight to Indian culture. Krishna temples and ancient history are now both major attractions of the city.<ref>Ring p.572-57</ref>\n\nThe present [[Keshav Dev Temple]] has been built at the same location where several major temples had been built in the 5000 years of hoary past, which is traced to the Vajranabha, the great grandson of Krishna. A grand temple was rebuilt during the reign of [[Chandragupta II|Chandra Gupta]] [[Vikramaditya]] in the 5th century that was sacked by Mahmud of Ghazni. Thereafter, at the same location Raja Veer Singh Deva Bundela had built a {{convert|250|ft|m}} high temple during [[Jahangir]]'s reign, which was also destroyed by [[Aurangzeb]] in 1669 and a mosque built in its place, which can be seen adjoining the present temple. The present temple (see picture in infobox) was completed in 1958 with installation of images of [[Radha Krishna]]. In the adjoining altars several images have been installed; on the left altar images of [[Jagannath]] (a form of Krishna), [[Balarama]] (Krishna's brother) and [[Subhadra]] (Krishna's sister) are seen; on the right altar idols of Rama, Sita and Lakshman are installed, right across there is a Hanuman idol. Images of Shiva and goddess Durga are also seen within the main temple foyer. The main temple complex also has a small shrine where Krishna was born (said to be the prison where he was born)  depicting images of [[Vasudeva]], [[Devaki]] and four-armed Krishna.<ref name = \"bansal4043\">Bansal p.40-43</ref>\n\nOn the bank of the [[Yamuna River]], at Vishrama ghat [[aarti]] is offered every evening to the river, since it is stated to be the location where Krishna rested after slaying King [[Kamsa]], his maternal uncle. Images of goddess [[Yami|Yamuna]] and her brother [[Yama]], the god of death, are also located here.<ref name = \"bansal4043\"/>\n\nThere are many other temples of importance to pilgrims within Mathura, to name only a few, such as the [[Prem Mandir Vrindavan]], Govindji temple, Madan Mohan temple, Radha Damodar temple, Radha Gopinath temple, Banke Bihari temple, Krishna Balarama temple, Rangaji temple and Seva Kunja. Also, in the nearby [[Vrindavan]] where Krishna spent his childhood days, there is a galaxy of temples (said to be 5000), which is also a very pious place for pilgrims. It is {{convert|12|km|mi}} away from Mathura.<ref name = \"bansal4043\"/>\n\nOther important religious events observed by pilgrims in the precincts of Mathura and Vrindavan are the Vrindavan [[parikrama|Parikrama (religious practice)]] (circumambulation around the temples along a prescribed path) and the Braj Mandal parikrama during October\u2013November, which takes 3 months to complete on foot, as it includes going round the [[Govardhan]] hill, apart from several other shrines.<ref name = \"bansal4043\"/>\n\nIt is located about {{convert|50|km|mi}} north of [[Agra]], and {{convert|150|km|mi}} south of [[Delhi]]; about {{convert|20|km|mi}} from holy [[Vrindavan]].<ref name=Schweig/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Char Dham]]\n*[[Chota Char Dham]]\n* [[Jyotirlinga]]\n\n==Places at a Glance==\n* Haridwar -Hari (Form of Vishnu)\n* Ayodhya- Ayodhyanath, Vijayaraghava Rama (Form of Lord Rama)\n* Kancheepuram- Devi Kamakshi (Form of Goddess Parvati, Shakti)\n* Varanasi(or Kashi)- Kashi Vishwanath (Form of Shiva)\n* Mathura- Shri Gowardhan Krishna (Form of Krishna)\n* Ujjain- Shri Mahakaleshwar (Form of Shiva)\n* Dwarka- Shri Dwarkadheesh (Form of Krishna)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Hindu holy cities}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu holy cities]]\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sapta_Puri"}
{"title_page": "Via Giulia", "text_new": "{{Infobox street\n| name = Via Giulia\n| image = 948RomaViaGiulia.JPG\n| image_size = 230px\n| image_alt = \n| caption = Arco Farnese across Via Giulia\n| map_type = \n| map_size =\n| location= Rome\n| quarter = [[Regola]], [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]]\n| coordinates =\n| terminus_a = Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti\n| terminus_b = Piazza dell'Oro\n| length = {{convert|950|m|abbr=on}}\n| width = \n| completion_date = 1512\n| designer = [[Donato Bramante]]\n| inauguration_label = Denomination\n| inauguration_date = \n}}\n'''Via Giulia''' is a street in [[Rome]], Italy, that is of historical and architectural importance. The road was one of the first important urban planning projects in papal Rome and became one of the main centers of the [[Roman Renaissance|Renaissance]]. Up until the 1850s it was one of the favorite streets of the Roman nobility and it was enriched with feasts and games. After a two-century decline, from the 1950s onwards the road's fame was renewed to be one of the city's most prestigious locations.\n\n==Location==\nVia Giulia runs along the left (east) bank of the [[Tiber]] from ''Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti'', near [[Ponte Sisto]], to ''Piazza dell'Oro''. It is about 1 kilometre long and connects the [[Regola]] and [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]] [[rioni of Rome|Rioni]].\n\n==Denominations==\nThe road was named after its patron, [[Pope Julius II]] [[della Rovere]] (r. 1503-1513), who ordered its construction in 1508.<ref name=bramanteDbi/><ref name=del472>Delli (1988), p. 472</ref> It had been also called {{Lang|la|Via Magistralis}} (lit. \"master road\") because of its importance,<ref name=del472/> and {{Lang|la|Via Recta}} (lit. \"straight road\") because of its layout.<ref name=del473/>\n\n==History==\nThe area of the ancient {{Lang|la|[[Campus Martius]]}} developed into one of the most densely populated districts (''abitato'') of Rome since the early [[Middle Ages]]. The maze of narrow alleys was criss-crossed by three narrow thoroughfares: the {{Lang|la|Via Papalis}} (lit. \"papal road\"),<ref>Today's ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi'' - ''via del Governo Vecchio'' - ''piazza di Pasquino'' - ''piazza di S.Pantaleo''  - ''piazza d'Aracoeli'' - ''Campidoglio'' - ''Stradone di S.Giovanni''</ref> the {{Lang|la|Via Peregrinorum}} (lit. \"pilgrims' road\") <ref>Today's ''Via dei Banchi Vecchi'' - ''Via del Pellegrino'' - ''via dei Giubbonari''</ref> and the {{Lang|la|Via Recta}} (lit. \"straight road\").<ref>Today's ''[[via dei Coronari]]''</ref><ref name=tem57>Temple(2011), p. 57</ref> [[Procession]]s travelled through these streets almost daily during the [[Middle Ages]] to the [[Ponte Sant'Angelo|Angels' Bridge]]. As [[Dante Alighieri]] described in the [[Divine Comedy]], in 1300, [[Pope Boniface VIII]] (r. 1294-1303) ordered a two-way traffic system to be set up to avoid traffic jams or panic as a response to the dense crowds on Angels' Bridge.<ref>Dante Aligheri: Inferno, canto XVIII, vv. 28\u20133\u20133</ref> After [[Pope Martin V]] (r. 1417-1431) [[Western_Schism#Resolution|returned]] to Rome in 1420, the influx of pilgrims increased significantly again, especially in the [[Jubilee]] years. On 29 December 1450, the last day of the Holy Year, a [[stampede]] broke out on the bridge that killed more than 300 people.<ref name=gi9038>Gigli (1990) p. 38</ref><ref name=gi9040>Gigli (1990) p. 40</ref>\nAs a result of the catastrophe, [[Pope Nicholas V]] (r. 1447-1455) ordered the Angels' Bridge to be cleared of stalls and shops and the first urban planning measures in the area were initiated. In 1475, [[Pope Sixtus IV]] (r. 1471-1484) ordered the [[Ponte Sisto]], named after him, to be built across the [[Tiber]] [[:File:Ponte Sisto Bauinschrift 1475.jpg|(inscription)]] in order to relieve the pilgrimage route across the Angels' Bridge and to connect the ''rioni'' of [[Regola]] and [[Trastevere]].<ref name=pie7982>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 82</ref> At the same time he ordered the restoration of ''Via Pelegrinorum'' and the area around the ''[[Campo de' Fiori]]'' [[:File:Via Florea Stadterneuerung.jpg|(inscription)]]. According to the chronicler [[Stefano Infessura]], however, strategic reasons aside from reducing traffic were also important for these projects.<ref>Stefano Infessura: ''Diario Rerum Romanorum''; Roma 1890 p. 79 f.: February 1475</ref> In 1497 [[Pope Alexander VI]] (r. 1492-1503) ordered the widening of ''Via Peregrinorum'' <ref>Inscription at the entrance to the Via del Pellegrino: ALEX VI PONT MAX POST INSTAURATAM ADRIANI MOLEM ANGUSTAS VRBIS VIAS AMMPLIARI IVSSIT MCCCCLXXXXVII (''Alexander VI. Pont. Max. ordered to widen the narrow streets of the town after the restoration of the Castel Sant'Angelo'')</ref> [[:File:Via del Pellegrino Inschrift Alexander VI.jpg|(Fig.)]] and the restoration of ''[[Via della Lungara]]'' on the right bank of the [[Tiber]] from [[Ponte Sisto]] to [[Old St. Peter's Basilica|St. Peter's Basilica]].\n\n===The project of Pope Julius II===\n[[File:Inschrift Julius II. Via Curato-Banchi.jpg|thumb|Inscription by Julius II, 1512]]\nIn addition to reconstructing [[St. Peter's Basilica]], Julius II implemented multiple projects in the framework of Rome's [[urban renewal]] (''Renovatio Romae'') in the [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]], [[Parione]], [[Sant'Eustachio (rione of Rome)|Sant'Eustachio]] and [[Colonna (rione of Rome)|Colonna]] ''[[Rioni of Rome|rioni]]'', a task which was started forty years before by his uncle, [[Pope Sixtus IV]] (r. 1471-1484).<ref name=cast378>Castagnoli (1958), pp.378</ref> One of the most important projects was the creation of two new straight streets on the left and right banks of the Tiber: the Via Giulia on the left bank, a new grand avenue through the most densely populated quarter of Rome, from the [[Ponte Sisto]] to the Florentine merchant quarter on the [[Tiber]] bend,<ref name=pie798>Pietrangeli(1979) p. 8</ref> and a straight road along the right bank of the Tiber from the [[Porta Settimiana]] in [[Trastevere]] to the [[Ospedale di Santo Spirito in Sassia|Hospital of Santo Spirito]] in the [[Borgo (rione of Rome)|Borgo]], the ''Via della Lungara''.<ref name=cast38081>Castagnoli (1958), pp.380-381</ref>\nBoth roads flanked the Tiber and were closely connected to it.<ref name=\"po19\"/> The Lungara had the dual aim to relieve the pilgrimage route to Saint Peter<ref name=cast38081/> and transport goods coming from the [[Via Aurelia]] and the [[Via Portuensis|via Portuense]] roads towards the centre of the city.  The Pope intended for it to reach Piazza di [[Santa Maria in Trastevere]] and the [[Port of Ripa Grande and Papal Arsenal|port of Ripa Grande]].<ref name=\"po19\"/>\n\nThe main goal behind these plans was to superimpose a regular road network with the focus given to the Tiber by medieval Rome's disorderly buildings; together with the new [[Borgo Nuovo (Rome)|Via Alessandrina]] that Alexander VI opened in the Borgo, the ''Via dei Pettinari'' that connected the [[Trastevere]] on one side and the [[Campidoglio]] on the other, the Lungara and Via Giulia created a quadrilateral network of modern roads in the city's maze of alleys.<ref name=\"po19\"/> In the original project Via Giulia was supposed to reach the Hospital of Santo Spirito in [[Borgo (rione of Rome)|Borgo]] via the rebuilt ''[[Pons Neronianus]]''.<ref name=del472/><ref name=cast380>Castagnoli (1958), pp.380</ref> The center of the city shifted towards the Vatican and [[Trastevere]] and away from the [[Palazzo Senatorio]] on the [[Capitoline Hill]], which was the symbol of the Roman nobility's power;<ref name=tem124/><ref name=\"po19\"/> the plan was intended to separate the papacy from the city's powerful noble families, particularly the [[Orsini family|Orsini]] and [[Colonna family|Colonna]] families.<ref name=tem124>Temple (2011), pp. 124</ref>\n\nThese projects had a secondary, celebrative goal to promote the [[Pontiff]] as the unifier of Italy and the renewer of Rome; in 1506, after the end of the [[Plague (disease)|plague]], the Pope overthrew the powerful [[Baglioni (family)|Baglioni]] and [[Bentivoglio family|Bentivoglio]] families and conquered [[Perugia]] and [[Bologna]],<ref name=\"po19\">Portoghesi, p. 19</ref> as testified in an inscription along the ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi''.<ref>IVLIO.II.PONT:OPT:MAX:QVOD FINIB:DITIONIS.S.R.E.PROLATIS ITALIAQ:LIBERATA VRBEM ROMAM OCCVPATE SIMILIOREM QVAM DIVISE PATEFACTIS DIMENSIS Q: VIIS PRO MAIESTATE IMPERII ORNAVIT (''Julius II p.o.m. who extended the power of the Holy Roman Church and freed Italy. The city of Rome, which resembled a conquered rather than a properly planned one, he embellished for the glory of the Empire'')</ref>\n\nAside from serving as a means of communication and representation for the Church, the road was supposed to host the city's new layman's administrative center.<ref name=\"po19\"/> [[Luitpold Frommel]] discovered a drawing by [[Donato Bramante]] in the Uffizi which showed a new huge administrative complex, the ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'', facing a representative square (the ''Foro Iulio'') that opened along the new street.<ref name=\"po19\"/> This forum was thought to lie between the ''Palazzo'' and the old ''[[Chancery (medieval office)|Cancelleria]]'' (today's Palazzo Sforza-Cesarini).<ref name=tem6768/> The centre was not far from the [[Apostolic Camera]] (the Pope's treasury) in [[Palazzo della Cancelleria|Palazzo Riario]] and the new ''Palazzo della Zecca'' (lit. \"papal mint\") erected by Bramante at the edge of ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi'' (also named ''Canale di Ponte'').<ref name=tem6768>Temple (2011), pp. 67-68</ref> By this road lay the merchants' and bankers' houses and offices, like the [[House of Altoviti|Altoviti]], Ghinucci, [[Acciaioli family|Acciaiuoli]], [[Chigi Family|Chigi]] and [[Fugger]].<ref name=cast378/> Close economic ties with Tuscan bankers like [[Agostino Chigi]] were sought and promoted.<ref name=chigiDbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/agostino-chigi_(Dizionario-Biografico)|title=Agostino Chigi|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Francesco|last=Dante|volume=24|year=1980|language=it}}</ref>\n\nAround 1508 Bramante was asked by the Pope to start [[expropriating]] and demolishing properties in the densely populated ''[[Campus Martius|Campo Marzio]]'' to create the new street.<ref name=bramanteDbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/donato-bramante_(Dizionario-Biografico)/|title=Donato Bramante|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Arnaldo|last=Bruschi|volume=13|year=1971|language=it}}</ref>\n\n[[Giorgio Vasari]] writes:\n{{quote|''Si risolv\u00e9 il Papa di mettere in strada Giulia, da Bramante indrizzata, tutti gli uffici e le ragioni di Roma in un luogo, per la commodit\u00e0 ch\u2019a i negoziatori averia recato nelle faccende, essendo continuamente fino allora state molto scomode.''}}\n{{quote|The Pope decided to consolidate all the offices and financial centers of Rome in one place in the Via Giulia designed by Bramante. This would have made it easier for businessmen to conduct their business, which until then had been a cumbersome process.}} <ref name=vasBra>Giorgio Vasari: Vita di Donato Bramante \u2013 1568</ref>\n\nHowever, in 1511, an agreement (known as the ''Pax Romana'') between the feuding [[Orsini family|Orsini]] and [[Colonna family|Colonna]] families was formed, which caused the ''Via Giulia'' and the ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'' projects to be suspended.<ref name=tem124/> Apart from a few [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] blocks between the Via del Gonfalone and the Vicolo del Cefalo, nothing remained of the palace.<ref name=pie52/>\n\n===Via Giulia in the 16th and 17th century===\n[[File:G.Vasi - Collegio Ecclesiastico a Ponte Sisto.jpg|thumb|Fontana di Ponte Sisto by the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' in an [[etching]] by [[Giuseppe Vasi]] (1759)]]\nAfter the death of [[Julius II]] in 1513, his successor, [[Pope Leo X]] (r. 1513-1521) from the [[House of Medici]], continued the work.<ref name=cas382>Castagnoli (1958), p. 382</ref> Further construction was done mainly in the northern part of the road between the unfinished ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'' and the banking district, which supported the Florentine merchant community.<ref name=cas382/> In this area, important artists, such as [[Raphael]] and [[Antonio da Sangallo the Younger]], acquired plots of land or built palaces.<ref name=pie40/><ref name=pie36/> \n\nThe area south of the [[San Biagio della Pagnotta|church of San Biagio]] changed radically: the central part of the Via Giulia around ''Monte dei Planca Incoronati'' became a slum filled with inns, brothels, and infamous locations like ''Piazza Padella'', a venue known for duels and stabbings up to the end of 19th century and demolished in the 1930s.<ref name=del504>Delli (1988), p. 504</ref> The area between ''Via del Gonfalone'', ''Via delle Carceri'', ''Via di Monserrato'', and the Tiber was a major district of ill-repute since the Middle Ages; a manuscript from 1556 reports about the quarter around the eventually demolished church of ''San Niccol\u00f2 degli Incoronati'' hosted \"... 150 houses of very simple people, whores and dubious persons ...\".<ref name=arm424>Armellini (1891), p. 424</ref>\nThe quarter starting from the church of Santa Aurea, today [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]], was called ''Castrum Senense'' in the [[Middle Ages]] because it was mainly inhabited by people from Siena.<ref name=del473>Delli (1988), p. 473</ref>  At this end of the Via Giulia, a well-defined architectural development plan was drawn up, which started with building the [[palazzo Farnese|Farnese residence]]. In 1586, the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' (lit. \"Beggar's Hospice\") was built by the architect [[Domenico Fontana]] on the orders of [[Pope Sixtus V]] (r. 1585-1590) and marked the end of the ''Via Giulia''.<ref name=pie7976/> It was built to solve the begging problem in the city and was given a yearly endowment of 150,000 ''[[roman scudo|scudi]]'' which could employ 2,000 people.<ref name=cas415>Castagnoli (1988), p. 415</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the 16th century it had become fashionable for the various nations and city-states to have their own churches built in Rome known as the ''chiese nazionali''.<ref name=cas392/> The ''rioni'' of [[Regola]] and [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]], along the [[procession]]al and pilgrim roads, were the preferred locations. The Florentines,  the Sienese, and the Neapolitans had their churches built in Via Giulia (the [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini|San Giovanni]], the [[Santa Caterina da Siena a Via Giulia|Santa Caterina]], and the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani|Santo Spirito]] respectively),<ref name=del473/><ref name=pie16/> while the Bolognese ([[Santi Giovanni Evangelista e Petronio|San Giovanni e Petronio]]), Spanish ([[Santa Maria in Monserrato degli Spagnoli|Santa Maria in Monserrato]]), English ([[San Tommaso di Canterbury]]) and Swedish ([[Santa Brigida, Rome|Santa Brigida]]) churches were built in the Regola ''rione''.<ref name=cas392>Castagnoli (1958), p. 392</ref>\n\nIn order to supply the quarter with sufficient drinking water, [[Pope Paul V]] (r. 1605-1621) had the [[Aqua Paola]] extend over the Tiber. In 1613, the ''Fontanone di Ponte Sisto'' (lit. \"The Big Fountain of the Sistine Bridge\") was built on the [[fa\u00e7ade]] of the beggars' hospice on Via Giulia.<ref name=pie7978/> It was demolished in 1879 and rebuilt in 1898 on the opposite side of the [[Ponte Sisto]] in what is now ''Piazza Trilussa''.[[:File:Fontana di Ponte Sisto.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7978/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"300\" heights=\"300\">\n 1645 Antonio Tempesta Via Giulia marked.svg|Via Giulia; Particular from ''Almae urbis Romae prospectus'' by [[Antonio Tempesta]] (1645)\n</gallery>\nAt the end of the 16th century Via Giulia's path was fixed; it ended by the Florentine quarter to the north and the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' to the south. It became less of a major commercial street and more a busy promenade and a place for celebrations, processions (such as that of the ''ammantate'', poor girls which were dowried by the goldsmiths of [[Sant'Eligio degli Orefici]]) and races.<ref name=pie799>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 9</ref><ref name=pie7910/> \n\nIn 1603 Tiberio Ceuli held a [[Tournament (medieval)|tournament]] at Palazzo Sacchetti,<ref name=doc>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/ldpd_7219594_000/ldpd_7219594_000_djvu.txt|title=Documenti del Barocco Romano|p=58 [c440] (1)|language=it|access-date=5 March 2020|publisher=Miscellanea della R. Societ\u00e0 Romana di Storia Patria|editor=J. A. F. Orbaan|year=1920|location=Roma}}</ref> while in 1617 [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Odoardo Farnese]] organized a [[Saracen]] tournament at the ''Oratorio della Compagnia della Morte'', to which he invited eight cardinals.<ref name=gig118>Gigli (1958), p. 118</ref> During the summer months the street was sometimes flooded for the pleasure of the common people and the nobility.<ref name=pie7910>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 10</ref> One of the most glamorous celebrations was held by the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]] in 1638 to celebrate the birth of the French [[Dauphin of France|dauphin]], the future king [[Louis XIV]].<ref name=pie7910/> Via Giulia hosted [[Water buffalo|buffalo]] races, parades of carnival [[Float (parade)|floats]], and in 1663 the organisation of a horse race with naked hunchbacks during [[Carnival]] is handed down.<ref name=pie798/> During the carnival, Via Giulia hosted several feasts promoted by the Florentines.<ref name=pie7910/>\nIn the [[baroque]] period, other important building projects contributed to the later appearance of the street: the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]],<ref name=pie16/> the ''Carceri Nuove'' (lit. \"New Prisons\"),<ref name=pie7913/> the [[Palazzo Falconieri]] <ref name=pie7944/>, and the churches of Sant'Anna dei Bresciani and [[Santa Maria del Suffragio, Rome|Santa Maria del Suffragio]].<ref name=pie56>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 56</ref> The street's character changed little despite the addition of these buildings. Via Giulia was rather left out in Rome's general [[urban development]] plan.\n\n===Development in the 18th and 19th centuries===\nIn the 18th century the Via Giulia remained primarily a place to organise feasts: in 1720 the Sienese held a festival to celebrate the promotion of [[Marc'Antonio Zondadari]] to Grand Master of the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Order of Malta]].<ref name=pie798/> [[Fireworks]] was set off near the ''Fontanone di Ponte Sisto'';<ref name=pie7910/> two triumphal arches were raised above the street: one in Santo Spirito and the other near Palazzo Farnese;<ref name=pie798/><ref name=pie7910/> and the Fountain of the Mascherone poured wine for the people instead of water.<ref name=pie7910/>\n\nUnder [[Pope Clement XI]]'s (r. 1720-1721) rule, the beggars housed in the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' were transferred to the [[San Michele a Ripa]].<ref name=pie7980>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 80</ref> The building was occupied by both poor unmarried girls (''zitelle'' in the [[Romanesco dialect]]) and a congregation made up of 100 priests and 20 clerics; the latter prayed for the souls of deceased priests;<ref name=pie7980/> as such, the building was nicknamed the ''Ospizio dei cento preti'' (\"Hospice of the Hundred Priests\").<ref name=pie7980/>  \n\nIn the 19th century only a few new buildings or restoration projects were realised: among them were the youth prison (Palazzo del Gonfalone) (1825-27), the renovation of the Armenian Hospice next to the [[San Biagio della Pagnotta|church of San Biagio]] (1830), the new fa\u00e7ade of the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]] (1853), and the [[Collegio Spagnuolo]] (1853). However, this did not stop the general decline of the street that started in the middle of the 18th century.<ref name=del474>Delli (1988), p. 474</ref> The nobility abandoned the palaces on the street to move to the new center of urban life in the [[Campo Marzio (rione of Rome)|Campo Marzio]], and in their place the road hosted artisans and became less of a centre for festivities.<ref name=ber332>Bertarelli (1925), p. 332</ref>\n\n===Via Giulia since 1870===\nAfter Rome [[Capture of Rome|became the capital]] of the [[Kingdom of Italy]] in 1870, the Tiber (known for flooding, particularly in ''[[Campus Martius]]'') had its banks worked on in 1873 by constructing [[Lungotevere]]s, which since 1888 were erected along the road and required the church of Sant'Anna dei Bresciani to be torn down.<ref name=pie8110>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 10</ref> The Lungoteveres completely cut off Via Giulia from the Tiber and prevented the [[loggia]]s and gardens of the palaces facing the river, such as the Palazzi Medici-Clarelli, Sacchetti, Varese, and [[Palazzo Falconieri|Falconieri]] from having a view of the river.\nSignificant building demolitions during the fascist period left a large gap between ''Via della Barchetta'' and the ''Vicolo delle Prigioni'', which to this day has only been partially filled by the new building of the ''Liceo Classico Virgilio''.<ref name=pie791822>Pietrangeli (1979), pp. 18-22</ref> The street has regained its status as one of the most prestigious streets in the city.<ref name=nyt/><ref name=pie7910/>\nNumerous events took place in 2008 during its 500th anniversary; some churches and palaces were restored and opened to visitors.<ref name=nyt>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/29/travel/29globe.html|title=A Stroll in Rome With a Papal Pedigree-Via Giulia celebrates its 500th birthday this year|author=Elisabeth Rosenthal|date=29 June 2008|access-date=8 March 2020|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks on Via Giulia==\nVia Giulia extends northwest for about one kilometre from the Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti on the [[Ponte Sisto]] to the Piazza dell'Oro in front of the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]. From 1586, the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' (\"Beggars' Hospice\") marked the southern end of the street.<ref name=pie7976>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 76</ref> Under Paul V's decree in 1613, a fountain that brought the [[Aqua Paola]] to the [[Regola]] ''rione''  was built against its fa\u00e7ade (see engraving by [[Giuseppe Vasi]] above).<ref name=pie7978>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 78</ref> This fountain was demolished together with the hospice in 1879 and rebuilt in 1898 on the opposite side of the Ponte Sisto in what is now Piazza Trilussa [[:File:Fontana di Ponte Sisto.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7978/>\n[[File:Via Giulia Roma.svg|400px|center|Map of via Giulia]]\n===1 Palazzina Pateras Pescara (Via Giulia 251)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Pal Pateras Pescara (Consulat de France).jpg|thumb|100px|1 Palazzo Pateras Pescara]]\nThis last building in Via Giulia was built in 1924 by [[Marcello Piacentini]] on behalf of the Avvocato Pateras.<ref name=pie7962>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 62</ref> Today it houses the Consulate of the French Republic in Rome.<ref name=pie7962/>\n===2 Fontana del Mascherone===\n[[File:Fontana del Mascherone Via Giulia.jpg|thumb|100px|2 Fontana del Mascherone]]\nThe fountain diagonally opposite [[Palazzo Farnese]] was built around 1626 by [[Carlo Rainaldi]] and paid for by the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]].<ref name=pie7956>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 56</ref> It was planned in 1570 to be a public fountain fed by the ''[[Aqua Virgo]]'' [[Aqueduct (water supply)|aqueduct]] to supply people with clean drinking water.<ref name=pie7956/> However, installation was only possible after Paul V ordered the water pipe to be extended over the [[Ponte Sisto]] in 1612.<ref name=pie7956/><ref name=pie7958>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 58</ref> The fountain consists of an ancient large marble mask (\"Mascherone\") on a background with [[volute]]s in marble, crowned by the symbol of the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]], a metal [[Fleur-de-lis]].<ref name=pie7956/> The fountain was moved against the wall in 1903, losing most of its charm.<ref name=pie7956/> The poet [[Wilhelm Waiblinger]] died in 1830 in the house opposite to it [[:File:Via Giulia Sterbehaus Wilhelm Waiblinger.jpg|(Fig.)]].\n\n===3 Palazzo Farnese (Via Giulia 186)===\n{{Main|Palazzo Farnese}}\n[[File:Palazzo Farnese Gartenseite.jpg|thumb|100px|3 Palazzo Farnese]]\nThe garden fa\u00e7ade of this palace building is oriented towards the Via Giulia. In 1549 it was designed according to [[Vignola]]'s drawings and completed by [[Giacomo della Porta]] in 1589.<ref name=cal213>Callari (1932), p. 213</ref> The garden between the fa\u00e7ade and the Via Giulia was once adorned by the [[Toro Farnese|Farnese bull]] (now in the [[National Archaeological Museum, Naples|National Archaeological Museum]] in [[Naples]]) [[:File:Farnese Bull MAN Napoli Inv6002 n01.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7956/> The palace is now the French Embassy in Italy.\n===3a Camerini Farnesiani (Via Giulia 253-260)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Camerini Farnesiani.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nBehind the row of lower buildings (\"Camerini Farnesiani\") [[:File:Via Giulia 253-260 Palazzetto Farnese.jpg|(Fig.)]], which today belong to the French Embassy, lay a small palace with garden, the Palazzetto Farnese, built around 1603 by [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Odoardo Farnese]] as his [[Hermitage (religious retreat)|hermitage]],<ref name=pie7954/> also known as ''Eremo del Cardinale'' (\"Cardinal's hermitage\"). This private retreat of the Cardinal, decorated with murals by [[Giovanni Lanfranco]], was accessible from Palazzo Farnese via a terrace and the Arco Farnese.<ref name=pie7954/> The building and garden was destroyed in the Tiber regulation after 1870.\n\n===4 Arco Farnese===\n[[File:Via Giulia Farnesebogen.jpg|thumb|100px|4 Arco Farnese]]\nThe bridge connects Via Giulia to the [[Palazzo Farnese]]. It was erected in 1603,<ref name=pie7954>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 54</ref> and was used to observe festive processions, games, and horse races in Via Giulia, particularly during [[Carnival]].\n===5 Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte===\n{{Main|Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte}}\nThe church, built in 1575-76, is located in the immediate vicinity of [[Palazzo Farnese]] and belonged to the ''Compagnia della Morte'' (\"Death's Brotherhood\") founded in 1538.<ref name=pie7948>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 48</ref> The fraternity was tasked with burying the dead that were recovered from the river or found in the [[Roman Campagna|area surrounding Rome]]. The building was demolished in 1733 and rebuilt by [[Ferdinando Fuga]] in 1737.<ref name=pie7950>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 50</ref> Its cemetery on the banks of the Tiber was demolished when the river was regulated in 1886.<ref name=pie7948/>\n===6 Palazzo Falconieri also Palazzo Odescalchi Falconieri (Via Giulia 1)===\n{{Main|Palazzo Falconieri}}\n[[File:Regola - via Giulia palazzo Falconieri facciata 1180066.JPG|thumb|100px|6 Palazzo Falconieri]]\nThe original building was built in the 16th century for the Roman noble family of the Ceci and directly adjoins the church of [[Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte]]. It was sold by the Ceci in 1574 to the [[Odescalchi family]] before being passed to the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]] in 1606. Eventually the Florentine nobleman [[Orazio Falconieri]] bought it in 1638 for 16,000 scudi.<ref name=pie7944>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 44</ref> From 1646 to 1649 he commissioned the architect [[Francesco Borromini]] to extend the palace.<ref name=pie7944/> The sides of the fa\u00e7ade on Via Giulia are decorated with two [[pilaster]]s in the shape of large [[herma]]s with female breasts and falcon heads.<ref name=pie7946>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 46</ref> The fa\u00e7ade on the [[Tiber]] side features a three-arched [[loggia]] <ref name=pie7946/> dating back to 1646. From 1814 Cardinal [[Joseph Fesch]], uncle of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] lived there, and from 1815 to 1818 he hosted his stepsister [[Laetitia Ramolino]], the emperor's mother.<ref name=pie7946/> In 1927 the Kingdom of Italy ceded the palace to the [[Hungary|Hungarian State]], which established it as the seat of the Hungarian Academy (Accademia d'ungheria). Today, in addition to the Academy, the palace is home to the Hungarian Embassy and the ''Pontificium Institutum Ecclesiasticum Hungaricum in Urbe''.\n\n===7 Palazzo Baldoca-Muccioli (Via Giulia 167)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Baldoca Muccioli.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe history of the palace is closely linked to the neighbouring Palazzo Cisterna.<ref name=pie7940/> Both properties were acquired by the sculptor [[Guglielmo della Porta]].<ref name=pie7940/> In 1540 [[Pope Paul III]] (r. 1534-1549) appointed him as his court artist and entrusted him with the interior decoration of Palazzo Farnese. The sculptor gave the building to the Baldoca family and then to the Muccioli. At the beginning of the 20th century the palace served as the residence of the English ambassador in Rome, Lord Rennel of Rodd, who bought and had it restored in 1928.<ref name=pie7940/>\n===8 Palazzo Cisterna (Via Giulia 163)===\n[[:File:Palazzo Cisterna (Rom).jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe Palazzo Cisterna was built by [[Guglielmo della Porta]] and served as his residence.<ref name=pie7940/> Above the [[architrave]] of the windows on the first floor the inscription '''FRANCISCVS TANCREDA ET GVILELMVS D(ella) P(orta) ME(ediolanensis) - S(culptor) CI(vis) RO(manus)''' can be read [[:File:Palazzo Cisterna (Roma).jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7940/> From a letter to a friend, it appears that the palace was completed in 1575. In 1600 Spanish missionaries acquired the palace and sold it to the Cisterna family at the beginning of the 20th century.<ref name=pie7940/> It was sold to the Ducci family in the middle of the 20th century.\n===9 Santa Caterina da Siena in Via Giulia===\n{{Main|Santa Caterina da Siena a Via Giulia}}\n[[File:Regola - S. Caterina da Siena.JPG|thumb|100px|9 Santa Caterina]]\nThe history of this church is closely linked to the [[republic of Siena|Sienese]] Brotherhood.<ref name=pie7936>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 36</ref> A community of merchants, bankers and craftsmen from Siena had been living in what was to be Via Giulia, where at that time stood the ''castrum Senense'' since the 14th century.<ref name=pie7936/> In 1519 the Brotherhood was canonically erected by Leo X.<ref name=pie7936/> In 1526 they commissioned [[Baldassare Peruzzi]] to build the church in honour of their saints, an [[Oratory (worship)|oratory]], and a house for the clerics.<ref name=pie7936/> The funds were provided by the Sienese nobility in Rome, particularly by Cardinal [[Giovanni Piccolomini]] and the banker [[Agostino Chigi]]. Since it was in a dilapidated state, it was rebuilt between 1766 and 1768 according to [[Paolo Posi]]'s designs,<ref name=pie7938>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 38</ref> while the interior decor was completed in 1775.<ref name=pie7938/> The [[Archconfraternity]] of the Sienese still owns the building today.<ref name=pie7940>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 40</ref> During Via Giulia's 500th anniversary of the street in 2008 the altarpiece was restored by Girolamo Genga.\n===10 Palazzo Varese (Via Giulia 14-21)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Varese (1).jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe palace opposite Santa Caterina da Siena was built between 1617 and 1618 by [[Carlo Maderno]] on behalf of Monsignor Diomede Varese.<ref name=pie7934>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 34</ref> In 1788 Monsignor Giuseppe degli Atti Varese gave the building to the [[Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith|Congregation ''Propaganda Fide'']] when his family line died out.<ref name=pie7934/> After exchanging owners several times the palace finally came into the possession of the [[Mancini family]].<ref name=pie7936>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 36</ref>\nThe front consists of two upper floors and a [[mezzanine]]. On the ground floor is the main [[portal (architecture)|portal]] and above it is a balcony on [[console (architecture)|console]]s, flanked by three windows each. A portal opens into the yard with three [[arcade (architecture)|arcade]]s stacked on one another [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Varese (2).jpg|(Fig.)]]. The yard originally opened to a garden by the river.\n===11 Sant'Eligio degli Orefici (Via di Sant'Eligio 9)===\n{{Main|Sant'Eligio degli Orefici}}\n[[File:Sant' Eligio degli Orefici - Au\u00dfenansicht.jpg|thumb|100px|11 Sant\u2019Eligio]]\nThe small church is off the Via Giulia and serves as the guild church of the Roman gold- and silversmiths.<ref name=pie7930>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 30</ref> Its construction is attributed to [[Raphael]], although it is possible that after the death of the artist it was finished by [[Baldassare Peruzzi]].<ref name=pie7932>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 32</ref>\n===12 Palazzo del Collegio Spagnolo (Via Giulia 151)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Collegio Spagnolo.jpg|thumb|100px|12 Collegio Spagnolo]]\nThe ''Palacio de Monserrat'' by [[Pietro Camporese the Younger|Pietro Camporese]] and [[Antonio Sarti]] was built between 1848 and 1862 and is the Spanish Centre for Higher Ecclesiastical Studies today. The Centre is attached to the Spanish National Church of [[Santa Maria di Monserrato]] on Via di Monserrato behind it. Construction on Via Giulia stopped with the completion of this building complex in the 19th century.\n===13 Liceo Statale Virgilio (Via Giulia No 35 ff.)===\nOne of the most important state school complexes in Rome was built between 1936 and 1939 <ref name=pie7922>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 22</ref> by [[Marcello Piacentini]]. The building complex between Via Giulia and the [[Lungotevere dei Tebaldi]] includes the fa\u00e7ade of [[Palazzo Ghislieri]] [[:File:Via Giulia Collegio Ghisleri.jpg|(Fig.)]], designed by [[Carlo Maderno]] (16th century), and the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani|church of the Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]].\n===14 Palazzo Ricci (Via Giulia 146)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Ricci.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe present building was originally a cluster of unconnected buildings, built at different times, opposite the Collegio Ghislieri.<ref name=pie7928>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 28</ref> The building complex was merged in 1634 and 1683. The main fa\u00e7ade facing Piazza de'Ricci shows strongly faded remains of a ''[[Graffito (drawing technique)|graffito]]'' by [[Polidoro da Caravaggio]] (16th century). On the side facing Via Giulia, a continuous fa\u00e7ade gave the complex its present uniform appearance [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Ricci.jpg|(Fig.)]].\n\n===15 Santo Spirito dei Napoletani===\n{{Main|Santo Spirito dei Napoletani}}\n[[File:Via Giulia Santo Spirito dei Napoletani 1.jpg|thumb|100px|15 Sto. Spirito dei Napoletani]]\nIn the [[Pius V]] catalogue this church is listed under the name of ''Santa Aura in strada Iulia''.<ref name=arm423>Armellini (1891), p. 423</ref> It was dedicated to [[Aurea of Ostia|Saint Aurea]], the patron saint of [[Ostia (Rome)|Ostia]].<ref name=arm423/> A nunnery was attached to the church.<ref name=arm423/> In 1439 the church was restored at the expense of Cardinal [[Guillaume d'Estouteville]].<ref name=arm423/> In 1572 Cardinal Inigo d'Avalos founded in the dilapidated building the ''Confraternita dello Spirito Santo dei Napoletani'' (\"Brotherhood of the Holy Spirit of the Neapolitans\"), who bought it from the nuns in 1574.<ref name=pie7924>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 24</ref> Between 1619 and 1650 a new building was erected, with a project of [[Ottavio Mascherino]] and a fa\u00e7ade by [[Cosimo Fanzago]].<ref name=pie7924/> It was dedicated to the Holy Spirit.<ref name=pie7924/> In the following centuries it was renovated several times, at the beginning of the 18th century by [[Carlo Fontana]] <ref name=pie7924/> and in the middle of the 19th century the fa\u00e7ade was renovated by Antonio Cipolla (1853).<ref name=pie7926>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 26</ref> It was the National Church of the [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]. The last [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies|King of Naples]] [[Francis II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]] and his wife [[Maria Sophie of Bavaria|Marie Sophie Amalie, Duchess in Bavaria]], were buried in the church in 1942.<ref name=pie7926/><ref name=del475>Delli (1988), p. 475</ref> After a long period of restoration, the church is open to the public again since 1986. [[:File:Santo Spirito dei Napoletani (Inneres).jpg|(Fig.)]]\n===16 San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia===\n[:File:Via Giulia Oratorio San Filippo Neri.jpg|(Fig.)]]\n{{Main|San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia}}\nConstruction of the small church opposite the Carceri Nuove was sponsored by Rutilio Brandi, a glove-maker from Florence, and given to the Compagnia delle santissime piaghe around 1600. The church was originally dedicated to [[Saint Trophimus]].<ref name=pie7916>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 16</ref> It was connected to a residence for unmarried girls (''zitelle'') and a hospital for sick priests.<ref name=pie7918>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 18</ref> The church was dedicated to [[San Filippo Neri]] after the saint's death.<ref name=pie7916/> In 1728 [[Filippo Raguzzini]] restored the church on behalf of [[Pope Benedict XIII]] (r. 1724-1730).<ref name=pie7918/> The church barely escaped destruction in the early 1940s due to the construction of a large road that should have joined [[Ponte Mazzini]] and the [[Santa Maria in Vallicella|Chiesa Nuova]].<ref name=pie7918/> This road was never built due to the [[World War II]].<ref name=pie7918/> It was abandoned after the war before being restored for non-religious purposes.\n===17 Carceri Nuove (Via Giulia 52)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Carceri Nuove 1.jpg|thumb|100px|17 Carceri Nuove]]\nSince 1430 the [[Savelli family]] had a monopoly on prisons in the city, especially Corte Savella at 42 Via di Monserrato. The inhumane penal system in the Corte Savella caused [[Pope Innocent X]] (r. 1644-1655)) to withdraw the Savelli's monopoly on the penal system in Rome. As a sign of new ''Justitia Papalis'', he had the new penal institution, the ''Carceri Nuove'', built in Via Giulia.<ref name=pie7913>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 13</ref> This new prison was built between 1652 and 1655 by the architect Antonio del Grande.<ref name=pie7913/><ref>Inscription above the portal: IUSTITIAE ET CLEMENTIAE SECURIORI AC MITlORI REORUM CUSTODIAE NOVUM CARCEREM INNOCENTIUS X PONT. MAX. POSUIT ANNO DOMINI MDCLV (''Innocent X. P.M. built the new prison in the year of the Lord 1655, for justice, leniency for the safe and humane custody of convicts'')</ref> The Carceri Nuove were considered a model of a humane penitentiary system in their time. The building and its purpose had a rather negative influence on the image of the magnificent street, which led to the suspension of construction in the following years and the [[Italian Renaissance|Renaissance]] character of the street being preserved. The building acted as a prison until the opening of [[Regina Coeli]] in [[Trastevere]] <ref name=pie7914>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 14</ref> in 1883, further on until 1931 as a youth prison.<ref name=pie7914/> From 1931 the palace housed the headquarters of the ''Centro di Studi Penitenziari'' (\"Research Institute for Criminal Justice\") and a specialized library.<ref name=pie7914/> Today the building houses the ''Direzione Nazionale Antimafia e Antiterrorismo'' (\"National Directorate for Anti-Mafia and Anti-Terrorism\").\n===17a Palazzo del Gonfalone===\n[[File:Via Giulia Carceri Nuove Museo Criminologico.jpg|thumb|100px|17a Palazzo del Gonfalone]]\nThe building between the Vicolo della Scimia and Via del Gonfalone has no entrance from Via Giulia.<ref name=pie64/> It was built between 1825 and 1827 under [[Pope Leo XII]] (r. 1823-1829) according to plans by [[Giuseppe Valadier]] as a prison for the youth.<ref name=pie64>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 64</ref> Today the building houses the ''Museo Criminologico'' (lit. \"Criminological Museum\").<ref name=pie66>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 66</ref>\n===18 Santa Maria del Suffragio===\n{{Main|Santa Maria del Suffragio, Rome}}\n[[File:Via Giulia Santa Maria del Suffragio.jpg|thumb|100px|18 S.M. del Suffragio]]\nIn 1592 the ''Confraternita del Suffragio'' (\"Brotherhood of Intercession\") was founded next to the church of [[San Biagio della Pagnotta]] to implore the intercession for the souls of the purgatory.<ref name=pie56/> The Brotherhood was approved by [[Pope Clement VIII]] (r. 1592-1605) in 1594 <ref name=pie56/> and was elevated to the status of ''Arciconfaternita'' (\"Archbishopric Brotherhood\") by [[Paul V]] in 1620. Thanks to several donations, in 1662 the erection of the church began as a project of architect [[Carlo Rainaldi]].<ref name=pie56/> The building was consecrated in 1669, and the fa\u00e7ade was finished in 1680.<ref name=pie56/> The church's interior was renovated in 1869; the frescoes inside the church are by [[Cesare Mariani]] (''[[Coronation of the Virgin]]'') and [[Giuseppe Chiari]] (''[[Nativity of Mary]]'' and ''[[Adoration of the Magi]]'').<ref name=pie58>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 58</ref>\n===19 Palazzo dei Tribunali===\n[[File:Via Giulia Sof\u00e0 (Palazzo dei Tribunali) 1.jpg|thumb|100px|19 Sof\u00e0]]\n[[Julius II]]'s most important planned project in the new street was a central administration building, in which a large part of the city's important offices and courts (\"tribunali\") were to be grouped together.<ref name=pie50/> The Pope's commission to [[Donato Bramante]]<ref name=pie50/> was issued around 1506, and construction in the area between ''Vicolo del Cefalo'' and ''Via del Gonfalone'' began before 1508,<ref name=pie50/> but was interrupted as in 1511 by the ''Pax Romana''.<ref name=tem124/> With the [[Julius II]]'s death in 1513, construction completely stopped. [[Giorgio Vasari]] wrote:\n{{quote|''Onde Bramante diede principio al palazzo ch'a San Biagio su 'l Tevere si vede, nel quale \u00e8 ancora un tempio corinzio non finito, cosa molto rara, et il resto del principio di opera rustica bellissimo che \u00e8 stato gran danno che una s\u00ec onorata et utile e magnifica opra non si sia finita, ch\u00e9 da quelli della professione \u00e8 tenuto il pi\u00f9 bello ordine che si sia visto mai in quel genere.''}}\n{{quote|Bramante therefore began the construction of the palace, which can be seen near San Biagio on the Tiber. In it there is still an unfinished [[corinthian order|Corinthian]] temple, something very rare and the remains of the beginning in beautiful ''[[Rustication (architecture)|Opera Rustica]]''. It is a great pity that such an important, useful and great project has remained unfinished. Experts considered it to be the most beautiful building of its kind ever seen.}} <ref name=vasBra/><ref name=pie50>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 50</ref><ref name=pie52/>\nSome remains of the mighty [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] walls, called ''sof\u00e0'' by the Roman population, between Via del Gonfalone and Vicolo del Cefalo along Via Giulia, can be seen today.<ref name=pie52/>\n===20 San Biagio della Pagnotta (San Biagio degli Armeni)===\n{{Main|San Biagio della Pagnotta}}\n[[File:Via Giulia San Biagio della Pagnotta.jpg|thumb|100px|20 San Biagio]]\nThis church was dedicated to [[Saint Blaise]] of [[Sivas|Sebaste]] and is mentioned in the church catalogues of the Middle Ages under the name of ''San Biagio de Cantu Secuta''.<ref name=pie52>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 52</ref> The name \"della pagnotta\" is derived from the Roman word ''pagnotta'' (\"bread roll\"), which was distributed to the faithful on the 3 February (feast of St. Blaise) and thought to protect against throat illnesses.<ref name=pie54>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 54</ref> The church was attached to one of the first abbeys in Rome.<ref name=pie52/> An inscription on the interior commemorates the construction of the church by an abbot Dominicus in 1072.<ref name=arm356>Armellini (1891), p. 356</ref> According to the Bramante's plans, this church was to be included in the construction of the Palazzo dei Tribunali. From 1539 to 1835 it was a [[parish]] church.<ref name=pie54/> In 1826 [[Pope Gregory XVI]] (r. 1831-1846) assigned the church to the [[Armenian people|Armenian]] community of Santa Maria Egiziaca.<ref name=pie54/> Since then it has been called officially ''San Biagio degli Armeni''.<ref name=pie52/>\n===21 Palazzo Ricci-Donarelli (Via Giulia no. 99-105)===\nThe palace is opposite to the Palazzo Sacchetti and was originally a group of residential buildings that first belonged to the [[Ricci family|Ricci]] and later to the Donarelli family.<ref name=pie48>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 48</ref>  The complex was restructured in 1663, possibly by [[Carlo Rainaldi]].<ref name=pie50>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 50</ref>\n===22 Palazzo Sacchetti (Via Giulia 66)===\n[[File:Palazzo Sacchetti Via Giulia (Rom).jpg|thumb|100px|22 Palazzo Sacchetti]]\n[[Antonio da Sangallo the Younger]] built the palace on land bought in 1542 by the Vatican Chapter.<ref name=pie40>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 40</ref> The fa\u00e7ade still bears the chipped [[coat of arms]] of Paul III.<ref name=pie40/> His son Orazio inherited the building and sold it in 1552 to Cardinal [[Giovanni Ricci (bishop)|Giovanni Ricci]] di [[Montepulciano]], who had the palace extended to its current dimensions by the architect [[Nanni di Baccio Bigio]].<ref name=pie40/> An inscription<ref>Inscription [[:File:Ponte - via Giulia palazzo Sacchetti - domus Antonii Sangalli architecti 1160658.JPG|(Fig.)]] on the fa\u00e7ade: DOMVS/ANTONII/SANGALLI/ARCHITECTI/MDLIII (house of the architect Antonio Sangallo 1553)</ref> in the Vicolo del Cefalo's side wall states that the palace was exempted from paying the census tax in 1555.[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Sacchetti Zensus 1555.jpg|(Fig.)]]<ref name=pie46/> The building changed hands several times.<ref name=pie40/><ref name=pie42>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 42</ref> In 1649 it was bought by the Florentine [[Sacchetti family]], whose name it still bears.<ref name=pie42/> The entrance to Via Giulia is made of marble and flanked on both sides by three large windows with grilles, thresholds, and cornices.<ref name=pie44>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 44</ref> In the left corner of the palace there is a small fountain [[:File:Palazzo Sacchetti Delfinbrunnen.jpg|(Fig.)]] flanked by [[caryatid]]es with two dolphins embedded in the wall;<ref name=pie44/> this refers to the later owners, the Ceuli family, whose coat of arms was chipped.<ref name=pie44/> Notable features inside include the ''Salone dei Mappamondi'' (\"Hall of World Maps\"), designed by [[Francesco de' Rossi (Il Salviati)|Francesco Salviati]],<ref name=pie46>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 46</ref> and the dining room with two [[fresco]]es designed by [[Pietro da Cortona]].<ref name=pie46/> The writer [[Ingeborg Bachmann]] lived in this palazzo in 1973 and died on 17 October 1973.\n===23 Palace with the Farnese coat of arms (Via Giulia 93)===\n[[File:Via Giulia (Rom);Palast mit den Farnese Wappen.jpg|thumb|100px|23 Palazzo with the Farnese coat of arms]]\nThe building is attributed to [[Giacomo della Porta]]. The palazzo takes its name from the three coats of arms of the [[Farnese family]], which were added to the fa\u00e7ade under Paul III. In the centre of the upper floor there is the coat of arms of [[Paul III]] with the papal [[tiara]] and the keys between two [[unicorn]]s. On the left is the coat of arms of Cardinal [[Alessandro Farnese (cardinal)|Alessandro Farnese]] and on the right the [[coat of arms]] of the [[Duchy of Parma|Duke of Parma and Piacenza]] [[Ranuccio I Farnese]].\n===24 Palazzo Medici Clarelli (Via Giulia 79)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Palazzo Medici Clarelli.jpg|thumb|100px|24 Palazzo Medici Clarelli]]\nAntonio da Sangallo the Younger built this palace as a private residence around 1535-1536.<ref name=pie34>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 34</ref> After Sangallo's death in 1546 the building was owned by the Florentine Migliore Cresci.<ref name=pie34/> An inscription above the main portal [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Medici Clarelli (Inschrift).jpg|(Fig.)]] immortalizes Duke [[Cosimo I de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany|Cosimo I de' Medici]].<ref name=pie34/> The palace for some time belonged to the Tuscan Consulate in Rome.<ref name=pie34/> At the end of the 17th century it was acquired by the Marini Clarelli family. In the 19th century it was used as barracks before being sold to the city of Rome in 1870. The fa\u00e7ade and the portal are lined with rusticated [[ashlar]]s.<ref name=pie36>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 36</ref> On the sides of the portal there are badly rebuilt large windows on [[Console (architecture)|consoles]].<ref name=pie36/>\n===25 Casa di Raffaello (via Giulia 85)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Casa di Raffaello.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThis palace, erroneously called the House of [[Raphael]], was built after 1525 for the [[Vatican Hill|Vatican]] [[Chapter (religion)|Chapter]] according to a design by the architect Bartolomeo de Ramponibus.<ref name=pie36>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 36</ref> Raphael originally acquired several plots of land here.<ref name=pie36/> However, he died before the building's construction began. The designs were created by Rafael and Antonio da Sangallo the Younger.<ref name=pie36/> An inscription above the windows of the first floor is dedicated to Raphael: '''POSSEDEVA RAF SANZIO NEL MDXX'''.<ref name=pie36/>\n===26 Quarter of the Florentines===\nIn 1448 Florentine merchants who resided in Rome founded the ''Compagnia della Piet\u00e0'', akin to the Florentine \"Misericordia\".<ref name=pie14>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 14</ref> Both Popes from the [[Medici family]], Leo X and [[Pope Clement VII|Clement VII]] (r. 1523-1534), promoted the influx of Florentines. Since 1515 the Commune of Florence had its own consulate in a palace on ''Via del Consolato''  that was erected in 1541 and demolished in 1888 to build [[Corso Vittorio Emanuele]].<ref name=pie26>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 26</ref> It had its own laws, its own court, and its own prison. Some of the buildings erected towards the end of the 15th century that once belonged to Florentines [[:File:Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (0).jpg|(Fig.)]] are still preserved across from the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]:<ref name=pie24>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 24</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\" \"=\"\">\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (1).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (2).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (4).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n</gallery>\n===27 San Giovanni dei Fiorentini===\n{{Main|San Giovanni dei Fiorentini}}\n[[File:San Giovanni dei Fiorentini (Roma).jpg|thumb|200px|San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]\nIn 1519 the \"nation\" of the Florentines received the privilege to build a parish church in honour of [[John the Baptist]] from Leo X .<ref name=pie16>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 16</ref> The church stands at the northern end of ''Via Giulia'' in the Florentine quarter.<ref name=pie16/> The church reflects the grandeur and the political self-image of the [[Medici family]], who owned a palazzo right next to the church. It is the largest church on Via Giulia.<ref name=pie16/> It combined the efforts of three of Rome's master builders: [[Giacomo della Porta]], [[Carlo Maderno]], and [[Francesco Borromini]].<ref name=pie16/> The last two artists [[burial|interred]] in the same tomb at the church.<ref name=pie20>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 20</ref> The altarpiece, started by [[Pietro da Cortona]], was continued by Borromini and finished by [[Ciro Ferri]].<ref name=pie20/>\n\n==Trivia==\n[[\u00c9mile Zola]], who visited Rome from 1894 to 1896, gave a description of Via Giulia and Palazzo Sacchetti (Palazzo Boccanera) in his [[travel literature|travelogue]].<ref>\u00c9mile Zola: ''Les trois villes \u2013 Rome''; Volume I, Cap. 3,II; Parigi 1896</ref>\n==References==\n<references/>\n== Sources==\n*{{cite book\n | author=Giorgio Vasari\n | authorlink=Giorgio Vasari\n | title=Le vite de\u2019 pi\u00f9 eccellenti architetti, pittori, et scultori italiani, da Cimabue insino a' tempi nostri\n | publisher=Giunti\n | location=Firenze\n | year=1568\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Giacinto Gigli\n | title = Diario romano, 1608-1670\n | location= Roma\n | publisher= Staderini\n | year= 1958\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Mariano Armellini\n | title = Le chiese di Roma dal secolo IV al XIX\n | year = 1891\n | url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/I/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/churches/_Texts/Armellini/ARMCHI*/home.html\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Luigi Vittorio Bertarelli\n | publisher=Touring Club Italiano\n | location=Milano\n | year=1925\n | title=Roma e dintorni\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Luigi Callari\n | title=I Palazzi di Roma\n | publisher=Ugo Sofia-Moretti\n | location=Roma\n | year=1932\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Ferdinando Castagnoli|authorlink1=Ferdinando Castagnoli|author2=Carlo Cecchelli|author3=Gustavo Giovannoni|author4=Mario Zocca| title=Topografia e urbanistica di Roma|publisher=Cappelli|location=Bologna|year=1958|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Paolo Portoghesi\n | authorlink=Paolo Portoghesi\n | title=Roma del Rinascimento\n | publisher=Electa\n | location = Milano\n | ISSN=\n | year=1970\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Carlo Pietrangeli\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Regola (III)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | edition=2\n | year=1979\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Carlo Pietrangeli\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Ponte (IV)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | edition=3\n | year=1981\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n |author=Sergio Delli\n |title=Le strade di Roma\n |publisher=Newton & Compton\n |location=Roma\n |year=1988\n |language=it\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Laura Gigli\n | title=Guide rionali di Roma\n | volume=Borgo (I)\n | publisher=Fratelli Palombi Editori\n | location=Roma\n | year=1990\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Nicholas Temple\n | title=Renovatio Urbis; Architecture, urbanism and ceremony in the Rome of Julius II\n | publisher=Routledge\n | location=New York\n | year=2011\n | ISBN=978-0-203-81848-0\n}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author=Luigi Salerno|author-link=Luigi Salerno |author2=Luigi Spezzaferro |author3=Manfredo Tafuri|title=Via Giulia: una utopia urbanistica del 500|location=Rome|publisher=Staderini|year=1973}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Via Giulia (Roma)|Via Giulia}}\n*[http://www.morelli.it/foglio/giulia/index.html#sommario Vincenzo Morelli, ''Omaggio a Via Giulia'']\n*[http://www.morelli.it/foglio/giulia/storia.html ''La storia di Via Giulia'']\n\n{{coord|41.8942|N|12.4701|E|source:kolossus-ruwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in Rome|Giulia]]\n[[Category:1508 establishments in the Papal States]]\n[[Category:Renaissance architecture in Rome]]\n[[Category:Rome R. VII Regola]]\n[[Category:Rome R. V Ponte]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox street\n| name = Via Giulia\n| image = 948RomaViaGiulia.JPG\n| image_size = 230px\n| image_alt = \n| caption = Arco Farnese across Via Giulia\n| map_type = \n| map_size =\n| location= Rome\n| quarter = [[Regola]], [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]]\n| coordinates =\n| terminus_a = Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti\n| terminus_b = Piazza dell'Oro\n| length = {{convert|950|m|abbr=on}}\n| width = \n| completion_date = 1512\n| designer = [[Donato Bramante]]\n| inauguration_label = Denomination\n| inauguration_date = \n}}\n'''Via Giulia''' is a street in [[Rome]], Italy, that is of historical and architectural importance. The road was one of the first important urban planning projects in papal Rome and became one of the main centers of the [[Roman Renaissance|Renaissance]]. Up until the 1850s it was one of the favorite streets of the Roman nobility and it was enriched with feasts and games. After a two-century decline, from the 1950s onwards the road's fame was renewed to be one of the city's most prestigious locations.\n\n==Location==\nVia Giulia runs along the left (east) bank of the [[Tiber]] from ''Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti'', near [[Ponte Sisto]], to ''Piazza dell'Oro''. It is about 1 kilometre long and connects the [[Regola]] and [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]] [[rioni of Rome|Rioni]].\n\n==Denominations==\nThe road was named after its patron, [[Pope Julius II]] [[della Rovere]] (r. 1503-1513), who ordered its construction in 1508.<ref name=bramanteDbi/><ref name=del472>Delli (1988), p. 472</ref> It had been also called {{Lang|la|Via Magistralis}} (lit. \"master road\") because of its importance,<ref name=del472/> and {{Lang|la|Via Recta}} (lit. \"straight road\") because of its layout.<ref name=del473/>\n\n==History==\nThe area of the ancient {{Lang|la|[[Campus Martius]]}} developed into one of the most densely populated districts (''abitato'') of Rome since the early [[Middle Ages]]. The maze of narrow alleys was criss-crossed by three narrow thoroughfares: the {{Lang|la|Via Papalis}} (lit. \"papal road\"),<ref>Today's ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi'' - ''via del Governo Vecchio'' - ''piazza di Pasquino'' - ''piazza di S.Pantaleo''  - ''piazza d'Aracoeli'' - ''Campidoglio'' - ''Stradone di S.Giovanni''</ref> the {{Lang|la|Via Peregrinorum}} (lit. \"pilgrims' road\") <ref>Today's ''Via dei Banchi Vecchi'' - ''Via del Pellegrino'' - ''via dei Giubbonari''</ref> and the {{Lang|la|Via Recta}} (lit. \"straight road\").<ref>Today's ''[[via dei Coronari]]''</ref><ref name=tem57>Temple(2011), p. 57</ref> [[Procession]]s travelled through these streets almost daily during the [[Middle Ages]] to the [[Ponte Sant'Angelo|Angels' Bridge]]. As [[Dante Alighieri]] described in the [[Divine Comedy]], in 1300, [[Pope Boniface VIII]] (r. 1294-1303) ordered a two-way traffic system to be set up to avoid traffic jams or panic as a response to the dense crowds on Angels' Bridge.<ref>Dante Aligheri: Inferno, canto XVIII, vv. 28\u20133\u20133</ref> After [[Pope Martin V]] (r. 1417-1431) [[Western_Schism#Resolution|returned]] to Rome in 1420, the influx of pilgrims increased significantly again, especially in the [[Jubilee]] years. On 29 December 1450, the last day of the Holy Year, a [[stampede]] broke out on the bridge that killed more than 300 people.<ref name=gi9038>Gigli (1990) p. 38</ref><ref name=gi9040>Gigli (1990) p. 40</ref>\nAs a result of the catastrophe, [[Pope Nicholas V]] (r. 1447-1455) ordered the Angels' Bridge to be cleared of stalls and shops and the first urban planning measures in the area were initiated. In 1475, [[Pope Sixtus IV]] (r. 1471-1484) ordered the [[Ponte Sisto]], named after him, to be built across the [[Tiber]] [[:File:Ponte Sisto Bauinschrift 1475.jpg|(inscription)]] in order to relieve the pilgrimage route across the Angels' Bridge and to connect the ''rioni'' of [[Regola]] and [[Trastevere]].<ref name=pie7982>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 82</ref> At the same time he ordered the restoration of ''Via Pelegrinorum'' and the area around the ''[[Campo de' Fiori]]'' [[:File:Via Florea Stadterneuerung.jpg|(inscription)]]. According to the chronicler [[Stefano Infessura]], however, strategic reasons aside from reducing traffic were also important for these projects.<ref>Stefano Infessura: ''Diario Rerum Romanorum''; Roma 1890 p. 79 f.: February 1475</ref> In 1497 [[Pope Alexander VI]] (r. 1492-1503) ordered the widening of ''Via Peregrinorum'' <ref>Inscription at the entrance to the Via del Pellegrino: ALEX VI PONT MAX POST INSTAURATAM ADRIANI MOLEM ANGUSTAS VRBIS VIAS AMMPLIARI IVSSIT MCCCCLXXXXVII (''Alexander VI. Pont. Max. ordered to widen the narrow streets of the town after the restoration of the Castel Sant'Angelo'')</ref> [[:File:Via del Pellegrino Inschrift Alexander VI.jpg|(Fig.)]] and the restoration of ''[[Via della Lungara]]'' on the right bank of the [[Tiber]] from [[Ponte Sisto]] to [[Old St. Peter's Basilica|St. Peter's Basilica]].\n\n===The project of Pope Julius II===\n[[File:Inschrift Julius II. Via Curato-Banchi.jpg|thumb|Inscription by Julius II, 1512]]\nIn addition to reconstructing [[St. Peter's Basilica]], Julius II implemented multiple projects in the framework of Rome's [[urban renewal]] (''Renovatio Romae'') in the [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]], [[Parione]], [[Sant'Eustachio (rione of Rome)|Sant'Eustachio]] and [[Colonna (rione of Rome)|Colonna]] ''[[Rioni of Rome|rioni]]'', a task which was started forty years before by his uncle, [[Pope Sixtus IV]] (r. 1471-1484).<ref name=cast378>Castagnoli (1958), pp.378</ref> One of the most important projects was the creation of two new straight streets on the left and right banks of the Tiber: the Via Giulia on the left bank, a new grand avenue through the most densely populated quarter of Rome, from the [[Ponte Sisto]] to the Florentine merchant quarter on the [[Tiber]] bend,<ref name=pie798>Pietrangeli(1979) p. 8</ref> and a straight road along the right bank of the Tiber from the [[Porta Settimiana]] in [[Trastevere]] to the [[Ospedale di Santo Spirito in Sassia|Hospital of Santo Spirito]] in the [[Borgo (rione of Rome)|Borgo]], the ''Via della Lungara''.<ref name=cast38081>Castagnoli (1958), pp.380-381</ref>\nBoth roads flanked the Tiber and were closely connected to it.<ref name=\"po19\"/> The Lungara had the dual aim to relieve the pilgrimage route to Saint Peter<ref name=cast38081/> and transport goods coming from the [[Via Aurelia]] and the [[Via Portuensis|via Portuense]] roads towards the centre of the city.  The Pope intended for it to reach Piazza di [[Santa Maria in Trastevere]] and the [[Port of Ripa Grande and Papal Arsenal|port of Ripa Grande]].<ref name=\"po19\"/>\n\nThe main goal behind these plans was to superimpose a regular road network with the focus given to the Tiber by medieval Rome's disorderly buildings; together with the new [[Borgo Nuovo (Rome)|Via Alessandrina]] that Alexander VI opened in the Borgo, the ''Via dei Pettinari'' that connected the [[Trastevere]] on one side and the [[Campidoglio]] on the other, the Lungara and Via Giulia created a quadrilateral network of modern roads in the city's maze of alleys.<ref name=\"po19\"/> In the original project Via Giulia was supposed to reach the Hospital of Santo Spirito in [[Borgo (rione of Rome)|Borgo]] via the rebuilt ''[[Pons Neronianus]]''.<ref name=del472/><ref name=cast380>Castagnoli (1958), pp.380</ref> The center of the city shifted towards the Vatican and [[Trastevere]] and away from the [[Palazzo Senatorio]] on the [[Capitoline Hill]], which was the symbol of the Roman nobility's power;<ref name=tem124/><ref name=\"po19\"/> the plan was intended to separate the papacy from the city's powerful noble families, particularly the [[Orsini family|Orsini]] and [[Colonna family|Colonna]] families.<ref name=tem124>Temple (2011), pp. 124</ref>\n\nThese projects had a secondary, celebrative goal to promote the [[Pontiff]] as the unifier of Italy and the renewer of Rome; in 1506, after the end of the [[Plague (disease)|plague]], the Pope overthrew the powerful [[Baglioni (family)|Baglioni]] and [[Bentivoglio family|Bentivoglio]] families and conquered [[Perugia]] and [[Bologna]],<ref name=\"po19\">Portoghesi, p. 19</ref> as testified in an inscription along the ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi''.<ref>IVLIO.II.PONT:OPT:MAX:QVOD FINIB:DITIONIS.S.R.E.PROLATIS ITALIAQ:LIBERATA VRBEM ROMAM OCCVPATE SIMILIOREM QVAM DIVISE PATEFACTIS DIMENSIS Q: VIIS PRO MAIESTATE IMPERII ORNAVIT (''Julius II p.o.m. who extended the power of the Holy Roman Church and freed Italy. The city of Rome, which resembled a conquered rather than a properly planned one, he embellished for the glory of the Empire'')</ref>\n\nAside from serving as a means of communication and representation for the Church, the road was supposed to host the city's new layman's administrative center.<ref name=\"po19\"/> [[Luitpold Frommel]] discovered a drawing by [[Donato Bramante]] in the Uffizi which showed a new huge administrative complex, the ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'', facing a representative square (the ''Foro Iulio'') that opened along the new street.<ref name=\"po19\"/> This forum was thought to lie between the ''Palazzo'' and the old ''[[Chancery (medieval office)|Cancelleria]]'' (today's Palazzo Sforza-Cesarini).<ref name=tem6768/> The centre was not far from the [[Apostolic Camera]] (the Pope's treasury) in [[Palazzo della Cancelleria|Palazzo Riario]] and the new ''Palazzo della Zecca'' (lit. \"papal mint\") erected by Bramante at the edge of ''Via dei Banchi Nuovi'' (also named ''Canale di Ponte'').<ref name=tem6768>Temple (2011), pp. 67-68</ref> By this road lay the merchants' and bankers' houses and offices, like the [[House of Altoviti|Altoviti]], Ghinucci, [[Acciaioli family|Acciaiuoli]], [[Chigi Family|Chigi]] and [[Fugger]].<ref name=cast378/> Close economic ties with Tuscan bankers like [[Agostino Chigi]] were sought and promoted.<ref name=chigiDbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/agostino-chigi_(Dizionario-Biografico)|title=Agostino Chigi|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Francesco|last=Dante|volume=24|year=1980|language=it}}</ref>\n\nAround 1508 Bramante was asked by the Pope to start [[expropriating]] and demolishing properties in the densely populated ''[[Campus Martius|Campo Marzio]]'' to create the new street.<ref name=bramanteDbi>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/donato-bramante_(Dizionario-Biografico)/|title=Donato Bramante|encyclopedia=Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani |first=Arnaldo|last=Bruschi|volume=13|year=1971|language=it}}</ref>\n\n[[Giorgio Vasari]] writes:\n{{quote|''Si risolv\u00e9 il Papa di mettere in strada Giulia, da Bramante indrizzata, tutti gli uffici e le ragioni di Roma in un luogo, per la commodit\u00e0 ch\u2019a i negoziatori averia recato nelle faccende, essendo continuamente fino allora state molto scomode.''}}\n{{quote|The Pope decided to consolidate all the offices and financial centers of Rome in one place in the Via Giulia designed by Bramante. This would have made it easier for businessmen to conduct their business, which until then had been a cumbersome process.}} <ref name=vasBra>Giorgio Vasari: Vita di Donato Bramante \u2013 1568</ref>\n\nHowever, in 1511, an agreement (known as the ''Pax Romana'') between the feuding [[Orsini family|Orsini]] and [[Colonna family|Colonna]] families was formed, which caused the ''Via Giulia'' and the ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'' projects to be suspended.<ref name=tem124/> Apart from a few [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] blocks between the Via del Gonfalone and the Vicolo del Cefalo, nothing remained of the palace.<ref name=pie52/>\n\n===Via Giulia in the 16th and 17th century===\n[[File:G.Vasi - Collegio Ecclesiastico a Ponte Sisto.jpg|thumb|Fontana di Ponte Sisto by the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' in an [[etching]] by [[Giuseppe Vasi]] (1759)]]\nAfter the death of [[Julius II]] in 1513, his successor, [[Pope Leo X]] (r. 1513-1521) from the [[House of Medici]], continued the work.<ref name=cas382>Castagnoli (1958), p. 382</ref> Further construction was done mainly in the northern part of the road between the unfinished ''Palazzo dei Tribunali'' and the banking district, which supported the Florentine merchant community.<ref name=cas382/> In this area, important artists, such as [[Raphael]] and [[Antonio da Sangallo the Younger]], acquired plots of land or built palaces.<ref name=pie40/><ref name=pie36/> \n\nThe area south of the [[San Biagio della Pagnotta|church of San Biagio]] changed radically: the central part of the Via Giulia around ''Monte dei Planca Incoronati'' became a slum filled with inns, brothels, and infamous locations like ''Piazza Padella'', a venue known for duels and stabbings up to the end of 19th century and demolished in the 1930s.<ref name=del504>Delli (1988), p. 504</ref> The area between ''Via del Gonfalone'', ''Via delle Carceri'', ''Via di Monserrato'', and the Tiber was a major district of ill-repute since the Middle Ages; a manuscript from 1556 reports about the quarter around the eventually demolished church of ''San Niccol\u00f2 degli Incoronati'' hosted \"... 150 houses of very simple people, whores and dubious persons ...\".<ref name=arm424>Armellini (1891), p. 424</ref>\nThe quarter starting from the church of Santa Aurea, today [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]], was called ''Castrum Senense'' in the [[Middle Ages]] because it was mainly inhabited by people from Siena.<ref name=del473>Delli (1988), p. 473</ref>  At this end of the Via Giulia, a well-defined architectural development plan was drawn up, which started with building the [[palazzo Farnese|Farnese residence]]. In 1586, the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' (lit. \"Beggar's Hospice\") was built by the architect [[Domenico Fontana]] on the orders of [[Pope Sixtus V]] (r. 1585-1590) and marked the end of the ''Via Giulia''.<ref name=pie7976/> It was built to solve the begging problem in the city and was given a yearly endowment of 150,000 ''[[roman scudo|scudi]]'' which could employ 2,000 people.<ref name=cas415>Castagnoli (1988), p. 415</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of the 16th century it had become fashionable for the various nations and city-states to have their own churches built in Rome known as the ''chiese nazionali''.<ref name=cas392/> The ''rioni'' of [[Regola]] and [[Ponte (rione of Rome)|Ponte]], along the [[procession]]al and pilgrim roads, were the preferred locations. The Florentines,  the Sienese, and the Neapolitans had their churches built in Via Giulia (the [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini|San Giovanni]], the [[Santa Caterina da Siena a Via Giulia|Santa Caterina]], and the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani|Santo Spirito]] respectively),<ref name=del473/><ref name=pie16/> while the Bolognese ([[Santi Giovanni Evangelista e Petronio|San Giovanni e Petronio]]), Spanish ([[Santa Maria in Monserrato degli Spagnoli|Santa Maria in Monserrato]]), English ([[San Tommaso di Canterbury]]) and Swedish ([[Santa Brigida, Rome|Santa Brigida]]) churches were built in the Regola ''rione''.<ref name=cas392>Castagnoli (1958), p. 392</ref>\n\nIn order to supply the quarter with sufficient drinking water, [[Pope Paul V]] (r. 1605-1621) had the [[Aqua Paola]] extend over the Tiber. In 1613, the ''Fontanone di Ponte Sisto'' (lit. \"The Big Fountain of the Sistine Bridge\") was built on the [[fa\u00e7ade]] of the beggars' hospice on Via Giulia.<ref name=pie7978/> It was demolished in 1879 and rebuilt in 1898 on the opposite side of the [[Ponte Sisto]] in what is now ''Piazza Trilussa''.[[:File:Fontana di Ponte Sisto.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7978/>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"300\" heights=\"300\">\n 1645 Antonio Tempesta Via Giulia marked.svg|Via Giulia; Particular from ''Almae urbis Romae prospectus'' by [[Antonio Tempesta]] (1645)\n</gallery>\nAt the end of the 16th century Via Giulia's path was fixed; it ended by the Florentine quarter to the north and the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' to the south. It became less of a major commercial street and more a busy promenade and a place for celebrations, processions (such as that of the ''ammantate'', poor girls which were dowried by the goldsmiths of [[Sant'Eligio degli Orefici]]) and races.<ref name=pie799>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 9</ref><ref name=pie7910/> \n\nIn 1603 Tiberio Ceuli held a [[Tournament (medieval)|tournament]] at Palazzo Sacchetti,<ref name=doc>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/ldpd_7219594_000/ldpd_7219594_000_djvu.txt|title=Documenti del Barocco Romano|p=58 [c440] (1)|language=it|access-date=5 March 2020|publisher=Miscellanea della R. Societ\u00e0 Romana di Storia Patria|editor=J. A. F. Orbaan|year=1920|location=Roma}}</ref> while in 1617 [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Odoardo Farnese]] organized a [[Saracen]] tournament at the ''Oratorio della Compagnia della Morte'', to which he invited eight cardinals.<ref name=gig118>Gigli (1958), p. 118</ref> During the summer months the street was sometimes flooded for the pleasure of the common people and the nobility.<ref name=pie7910>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 10</ref> One of the most glamorous celebrations was held by the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]] in 1638 to celebrate the birth of the French [[Dauphin of France|dauphin]], the future king [[Louis XIV]].<ref name=pie7910/> Via Giulia hosted [[Water buffalo|buffalo]] races, parades of carnival [[Float (parade)|floats]], and in 1663 the organisation of a horse race with naked hunchbacks during [[Carnival]] is handed down.<ref name=pie798/> During the carnival, Via Giulia hosted several feasts promoted by the Florentines.<ref name=pie7910/>\nIn the [[baroque]] period, other important building projects contributed to the later appearance of the street: the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]],<ref name=pie16/> the ''Carceri Nuove'' (lit. \"New Prisons\"),<ref name=pie7913/> the [[Palazzo Falconieri]] <ref name=pie7944/>, and the churches of Sant'Anna dei Bresciani and [[Santa Maria del Suffragio, Rome|Santa Maria del Suffragio]].<ref name=pie56>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 56</ref> The street's character changed little despite the addition of these buildings. Via Giulia was rather left out in Rome's general [[urban development]] plan.\n\n===Development in the 18th and 19th centuries===\nIn the 18th century the Via Giulia remained primarily a place to organise feasts: in 1720 the Sienese held a festival to celebrate the promotion of [[Marc'Antonio Zondadari]] to Grand Master of the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Order of Malta]].<ref name=pie798/> [[Fireworks]] was set off near the ''Fontanone di Ponte Sisto'';<ref name=pie7910/> two triumphal arches were raised above the street: one in Santo Spirito and the other near Palazzo Farnese;<ref name=pie798/><ref name=pie7910/> and the Fountain of the Mascherone poured wine for the people instead of water.<ref name=pie7910/>\n\nUnder [[Pope Clement XI]]'s (r. 1720-1721) rule, the beggars housed in the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' were transferred to the [[San Michele a Ripa]].<ref name=pie7980>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 80</ref> The building was occupied by both poor unmarried girls (''zitelle'' in the [[Romanesco dialect]]) and a congregation made up of 100 priests and 20 clerics; the latter prayed for the souls of deceased priests;<ref name=pie7980/> as such, the building was nicknamed the ''Ospizio dei cento preti'' (\"Hospice of the Hundred Priests\").<ref name=pie7980/>  \n\nIn the 19th century only a few new buildings or restoration projects were realised: among them were the youth prison (Palazzo del Gonfalone) (1825-27), the renovation of the Armenian Hospice next to the [[San Biagio della Pagnotta|church of San Biagio]] (1830), the new fa\u00e7ade of the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]] (1853), and the [[Collegio Spagnuolo]] (1853). However, this did not stop the general decline of the street that started in the middle of the 18th century.<ref name=del474>Delli (1988), p. 474</ref> The nobility abandoned the palaces on the street to move to the new center of urban life in the [[Campo Marzio (rione of Rome)|Campo Marzio]], and in their place the road hosted artisans and became less of a centre for festivities.<ref name=ber332>Bertarelli (1925), p. 332</ref>\n\n===Via Giulia since 1870===\nAfter Rome [[Capture of Rome|became the capital]] of the [[Kingdom of Italy]] in 1870, the Tiber (known for flooding, particularly in ''[[Campus Martius]]'') had its banks worked on in 1873 by constructing [[Lungotevere]]s, which since 1888 were erected along the road and required the church of Sant'Anna dei Bresciani to be torn down.<ref name=pie8110>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 10</ref> The Lungoteveres completely cut off Via Giulia from the Tiber and prevented the [[loggia]]s and gardens of the palaces facing the river, such as the Palazzi Medici-Clarelli, Sacchetti, Varese, and [[Palazzo Falconieri|Falconieri]] from having a view of the river.\nSignificant building demolitions during the fascist period left a large gap between ''Via della Barchetta'' and the ''Vicolo delle Prigioni'', which to this day has only been partially filled by the new building of the ''Liceo Classico Virgilio''.<ref name=pie791822>Pietrangeli (1979), pp. 18-22</ref> The street has regained its status as one of the most prestigious streets in the city.<ref name=nyt/><ref name=pie7910/>\nNumerous events took place in 2008 during its 500th anniversary; some churches and palaces were restored and opened to visitors.<ref name=nyt>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/29/travel/29globe.html|title=A Stroll in Rome With a Papal Pedigree-Via Giulia celebrates its 500th birthday this year|author=Elisabeth Rosenthal|date=29 June 2008|access-date=8 March 2020|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks on Via Giulia==\nVia Giulia extends northwest for about one kilometre from the Piazza San Vincenzo Pallotti on the [[Ponte Sisto]] to the Piazza dell'Oro in front of the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]. From 1586, the ''Ospizio dei Mendicanti'' (\"Beggars' Hospice\") marked the southern end of the street.<ref name=pie7976>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 76</ref> Under Paul V's decree in 1613, a fountain that brought the [[Aqua Paola]] to the [[Regola]] ''rione''  was built against its fa\u00e7ade (see engraving by [[Giuseppe Vasi]] above).<ref name=pie7978>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 78</ref> This fountain was demolished together with the hospice in 1879 and rebuilt in 1898 on the opposite side of the Ponte Sisto in what is now Piazza Trilussa [[:File:Fontana di Ponte Sisto.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7978/>\n[[File:Via Giulia Roma.svg|400px|center|Map of via Giulia]]\n===1 Palazzina Pateras Pescara (Via Giulia 251)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Pal Pateras Pescara (Consulat de France).jpg|thumb|100px|1 Palazzo Pateras Pescara]]\nThis last building in Via Giulia was built in 1924 by [[Marcello Piacentini]] on behalf of the Avvocato Pateras.<ref name=pie7962>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 62</ref> Today it houses the Consulate of the French Republic in Rome.<ref name=pie7962/>\n===2 Fontana del Mascherone===\n[[File:Fontana del Mascherone Via Giulia.jpg|thumb|100px|2 Fontana del Mascherone]]\nThe fountain diagonally opposite [[Palazzo Farnese]] was built around 1626 by [[Carlo Rainaldi]] and paid for by the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]].<ref name=pie7956>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 56</ref> It was planned in 1570 to be a public fountain fed by the ''[[Aqua Virgo]]'' [[Aqueduct (water supply)|aqueduct]] to supply people with clean drinking water.<ref name=pie7956/> However, installation was only possible after Paul V ordered the water pipe to be extended over the [[Ponte Sisto]] in 1612.<ref name=pie7956/><ref name=pie7958>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 58</ref> The fountain consists of an ancient large marble mask (\"Mascherone\") on a background with [[volute]]s in marble, crowned by the symbol of the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]], a metal [[Fleur-de-lis]].<ref name=pie7956/> The fountain was moved against the wall in 1903, losing most of its charm.<ref name=pie7956/> The poet [[Wilhelm Waiblinger]] died in 1830 in the house opposite to it [[:File:Via Giulia Sterbehaus Wilhelm Waiblinger.jpg|(Fig.)]].\n\n===3 Palazzo Farnese (Via Giulia 186)===\n{{Main|Palazzo Farnese}}\n[[File:Palazzo Farnese Gartenseite.jpg|thumb|100px|3 Palazzo Farnese]]\nThe garden fa\u00e7ade of this palace building is oriented towards the Via Giulia. In 1549 it was designed according to [[Vignola]]'s drawings and completed by [[Giacomo della Porta]] in 1589.<ref name=cal213>Callari (1932), p. 213</ref> The garden between the fa\u00e7ade and the Via Giulia was once adorned by the [[Toro Farnese|Farnese bull]] (now in the [[National Archaeological Museum, Naples|National Archaeological Museum]] in [[Naples]]) [[:File:Farnese Bull MAN Napoli Inv6002 n01.jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7956/> The palace is now the French Embassy in Italy.\n===3a Camerini Farnesiani (Via Giulia 253-260)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Camerini Farnesiani.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nBehind the row of lower buildings (\"Camerini Farnesiani\") [[:File:Via Giulia 253-260 Palazzetto Farnese.jpg|(Fig.)]], which today belong to the French Embassy, lay a small palace with garden, the Palazzetto Farnese, built around 1603 by [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Odoardo Farnese]] as his [[Hermitage (religious retreat)|hermitage]],<ref name=pie7954/> also known as ''Eremo del Cardinale'' (\"Cardinal's hermitage\"). This private retreat of the Cardinal, decorated with murals by [[Giovanni Lanfranco]], was accessible from Palazzo Farnese via a terrace and the Arco Farnese.<ref name=pie7954/> The building and garden was destroyed in the Tiber regulation after 1870.\n\n===4 Arco Farnese===\n[[File:Via Giulia Farnesebogen.jpg|thumb|100px|4 Arco Farnese]]\nThe bridge connects Via Giulia to the [[Palazzo Farnese]]. It was erected in 1603,<ref name=pie7954>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 54</ref> and was used to observe festive processions, games, and horse races in Via Giulia, particularly during [[Carnival]].\n===5 Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte===\n{{Main|Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte}}\nThe church, built in 1575-76, is located in the immediate vicinity of [[Palazzo Farnese]] and belonged to the ''Compagnia della Morte'' (\"Death's Brotherhood\") founded in 1538.<ref name=pie7948>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 48</ref> The fraternity was tasked with burying the dead that were recovered from the river or found in the [[Roman Campagna|area surrounding Rome]]. The building was demolished in 1733 and rebuilt by [[Ferdinando Fuga]] in 1737.<ref name=pie7950>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 50</ref> Its cemetery on the banks of the Tiber was demolished when the river was regulated in 1886.<ref name=pie7948/>\n===6 Palazzo Falconieri also Palazzo Odescalchi Falconieri (Via Giulia 1)===\n{{Main|Palazzo Falconieri}}\n[[File:Regola - via Giulia palazzo Falconieri facciata 1180066.JPG|thumb|100px|6 Palazzo Falconieri]]\nThe original building was built in the 16th century for the Roman noble family of the Ceci and directly adjoins the church of [[Santa Maria dell'Orazione e Morte]]. It was sold by the Ceci in 1574 to the [[Odescalchi family]] before being passed to the [[Farnese Family|Farnese]] in 1606. Eventually the Florentine nobleman [[Orazio Falconieri]] bought it in 1638 for 16,000 scudi.<ref name=pie7944>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 44</ref> From 1646 to 1649 he commissioned the architect [[Francesco Borromini]] to extend the palace.<ref name=pie7944/> The sides of the fa\u00e7ade on Via Giulia are decorated with two [[pilaster]]s in the shape of large [[herma]]s with female breasts and falcon heads.<ref name=pie7946>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 46</ref> The fa\u00e7ade on the [[Tiber]] side features a three-arched [[loggia]] <ref name=pie7946/> dating back to 1646. From 1814 Cardinal [[Joseph Fesch]], uncle of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] lived there, and from 1815 to 1818 he hosted his stepsister [[Laetitia Ramolino]], the emperor's mother.<ref name=pie7946/> In 1927 the Kingdom of Italy ceded the palace to the [[Hungary|Hungarian State]], which established it as the seat of the Hungarian Academy (Accademia d'ungheria). Today, in addition to the Academy, the palace is home to the Hungarian Embassy and the ''Pontificium Institutum Ecclesiasticum Hungaricum in Urbe''.\n\n===7 Palazzo Baldoca-Muccioli (Via Giulia 167)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Baldoca Muccioli.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe history of the palace is closely linked to the neighbouring Palazzo Cisterna.<ref name=pie7940/> Both properties were acquired by the sculptor [[Guglielmo della Porta]].<ref name=pie7940/> In 1540 [[Pope Paul III]] (r. 1534-1549) appointed him as his court artist and entrusted him with the interior decoration of Palazzo Farnese. The sculptor gave the building to the Baldoca family and then to the Muccioli. At the beginning of the 20th century the palace served as the residence of the English ambassador in Rome, Lord Rennel of Rodd, who bought and had it restored in 1928.<ref name=pie7940/>\n===8 Palazzo Cisterna (Via Giulia 163)===\n[[:File:Palazzo Cisterna (Rom).jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe Palazzo Cisterna was built by [[Guglielmo della Porta]] and served as his residence.<ref name=pie7940/> Above the [[architrave]] of the windows on the first floor the inscription '''FRANCISCVS TANCREDA ET GVILELMVS D(ella) P(orta) ME(ediolanensis) - S(culptor) CI(vis) RO(manus)''' can be read [[:File:Palazzo Cisterna (Roma).jpg|(Fig.)]].<ref name=pie7940/> From a letter to a friend, it appears that the palace was completed in 1575. In 1600 Spanish missionaries acquired the palace and sold it to the Cisterna family at the beginning of the 20th century.<ref name=pie7940/> It was sold to the Ducci family in the middle of the 20th century.\n===9 Santa Caterina da Siena in Via Giulia===\n{{Main|Santa Caterina da Siena a Via Giulia}}\n[[File:Regola - S. Caterina da Siena.JPG|thumb|100px|9 Santa Caterina]]\nThe history of this church is closely linked to the [[republic of Siena|Sienese]] Brotherhood.<ref name=pie7936>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 36</ref> A community of merchants, bankers and craftsmen from Siena had been living in what was to be Via Giulia, where at that time stood the ''castrum Senense'' since the 14th century.<ref name=pie7936/> In 1519 the Brotherhood was canonically erected by Leo X.<ref name=pie7936/> In 1526 they commissioned [[Baldassare Peruzzi]] to build the church in honour of their saints, an [[Oratory (worship)|oratory]], and a house for the clerics.<ref name=pie7936/> The funds were provided by the Sienese nobility in Rome, particularly by Cardinal [[Giovanni Piccolomini]] and the banker [[Agostino Chigi]]. Since it was in a dilapidated state, it was rebuilt between 1766 and 1768 according to [[Paolo Posi]]'s designs,<ref name=pie7938>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 38</ref> while the interior decor was completed in 1775.<ref name=pie7938/> The [[Archconfraternity]] of the Sienese still owns the building today.<ref name=pie7940>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 40</ref> During Via Giulia's 500th anniversary of the street in 2008 the altarpiece was restored by Girolamo Genga.\n===10 Palazzo Varese (Via Giulia 14-21)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Varese (1).jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe palace opposite Santa Caterina da Siena was built between 1617 and 1618 by [[Carlo Maderno]] on behalf of Monsignor Diomede Varese.<ref name=pie7934>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 34</ref> In 1788 Monsignor Giuseppe degli Atti Varese gave the building to the [[Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith|Congregation ''Propaganda Fide'']] when his family line died out.<ref name=pie7934/> After exchanging owners several times the palace finally came into the possession of the [[Mancini family]].<ref name=pie7936>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 36</ref>\nThe front consists of two upper floors and a [[mezzanine]]. On the ground floor is the main [[portal (architecture)|portal]] and above it is a balcony on [[console (architecture)|console]]s, flanked by three windows each. A portal opens into the yard with three [[arcade (architecture)|arcade]]s stacked on one another [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Varese (2).jpg|(Fig.)]]. The yard originally opened to a garden by the river.\n===11 Sant'Eligio degli Orefici (Via di Sant'Eligio 9)===\n{{Main|Sant'Eligio degli Orefici}}\n[[File:Sant' Eligio degli Orefici - Au\u00dfenansicht.jpg|thumb|100px|11 Sant\u2019Eligio]]\nThe small church is off the Via Giulia and serves as the guild church of the Roman gold- and silversmiths.<ref name=pie7930>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 30</ref> Its construction is attributed to [[Raphael]], although it is possible that after the death of the artist it was finished by [[Baldassare Peruzzi]].<ref name=pie7932>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 32</ref>\n===12 Palazzo del Collegio Spagnolo (Via Giulia 151)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Collegio Spagnolo.jpg|thumb|100px|12 Collegio Spagnolo]]\nThe ''Palacio de Monserrat'' by [[Pietro Camporese the Younger|Pietro Camporese]] and [[Antonio Sarti]] was built between 1848 and 1862 and is the Spanish Centre for Higher Ecclesiastical Studies today. The Centre is attached to the Spanish National Church of [[Santa Maria di Monserrato]] on Via di Monserrato behind it. Construction on Via Giulia stopped with the completion of this building complex in the 19th century.\n===13 Liceo Statale Virgilio (Via Giulia No 35 ff.)===\nOne of the most important state school complexes in Rome was built between 1936 and 1939 <ref name=pie7922>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 22</ref> by [[Marcello Piacentini]]. The building complex between Via Giulia and the [[Lungotevere dei Tebaldi]] includes the fa\u00e7ade of [[Palazzo Ghislieri]] [[:File:Via Giulia Collegio Ghisleri.jpg|(Fig.)]], designed by [[Carlo Maderno]] (16th century), and the [[Santo Spirito dei Napoletani|church of the Santo Spirito dei Napoletani]].\n===14 Palazzo Ricci (Via Giulia 146)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Ricci.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThe present building was originally a cluster of unconnected buildings, built at different times, opposite the Collegio Ghislieri.<ref name=pie7928>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 28</ref> The building complex was merged in 1634 and 1683. The main fa\u00e7ade facing Piazza de'Ricci shows strongly faded remains of a painting by [[Polidoro da Caravaggio]] (16th century). On the side facing Via Giulia, a continuous fa\u00e7ade gave the complex its present uniform appearance [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Ricci.jpg|(Fig.)]].\n===15 Santo Spirito dei Napoletani===\n{{Main|Santo Spirito dei Napoletani}}\n[[File:Via Giulia Santo Spirito dei Napoletani 1.jpg|thumb|100px|15 Sto. Spirito dei Napoletani]]\nIn the [[Pius V]] catalogue this church is listed under the name of ''Santa Aura in strada Iulia''.<ref name=arm423>Armellini (1891), p. 423</ref> It was dedicated to [[Aurea of Ostia|Saint Aurea]], the patron saint of [[Ostia (Rome)|Ostia]].<ref name=arm423/> A nunnery was attached to the church.<ref name=arm423/> In 1439 the church was restored at the expense of Cardinal [[Guillaume d'Estouteville]].<ref name=arm423/> In 1572 Cardinal Inigo d'Avalos founded in the dilapidated building the ''Confraternita dello Spirito Santo dei Napoletani'' (\"Brotherhood of the Holy Spirit of the Neapolitans\"), who bought it from the nuns in 1574.<ref name=pie7924>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 24</ref> Between 1619 and 1650 a new building was erected, with a project of [[Ottavio Mascherino]] and a fa\u00e7ade by [[Cosimo Fanzago]].<ref name=pie7924/> It was dedicated to the Holy Spirit.<ref name=pie7924/> In the following centuries it was renovated several times, at the beginning of the 18th century by [[Carlo Fontana]] <ref name=pie7924/> and in the middle of the 19th century the fa\u00e7ade was renovated by Antonio Cipolla (1853).<ref name=pie7926>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 26</ref> It was the National Church of the [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]. The last [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies|King of Naples]] [[Francis II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]] and his wife [[Maria Sophie of Bavaria|Marie Sophie Amalie, Duchess in Bavaria]], were buried in the church in 1942.<ref name=pie7926/><ref name=del475>Delli (1988), p. 475</ref> After a long period of restoration, the church is open to the public again since 1986. [[:File:Santo Spirito dei Napoletani (Inneres).jpg|(Fig.)]]\n===16 San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia===\n[:File:Via Giulia Oratorio San Filippo Neri.jpg|(Fig.)]]\n{{Main|San Filippo Neri in Via Giulia}}\nConstruction of the small church opposite the Carceri Nuove was sponsored by Rutilio Brandi, a glove-maker from Florence, and given to the Compagnia delle santissime piaghe around 1600. The church was originally dedicated to [[Saint Trophimus]].<ref name=pie7916>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 16</ref> It was connected to a residence for unmarried girls (''zitelle'') and a hospital for sick priests.<ref name=pie7918>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 18</ref> The church was dedicated to [[San Filippo Neri]] after the saint's death.<ref name=pie7916/> In 1728 [[Filippo Raguzzini]] restored the church on behalf of [[Pope Benedict XIII]] (r. 1724-1730).<ref name=pie7918/> The church barely escaped destruction in the early 1940s due to the construction of a large road that should have joined [[Ponte Mazzini]] and the [[Santa Maria in Vallicella|Chiesa Nuova]].<ref name=pie7918/> This road was never built due to the [[World War II]].<ref name=pie7918/> It was abandoned after the war before being restored for non-religious purposes.\n===17 Carceri Nuove (Via Giulia 52)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Carceri Nuove 1.jpg|thumb|100px|17 Carceri Nuove]]\nSince 1430 the [[Savelli family]] had a monopoly on prisons in the city, especially Corte Savella at 42 Via di Monserrato. The inhumane penal system in the Corte Savella caused [[Pope Innocent X]] (r. 1644-1655)) to withdraw the Savelli's monopoly on the penal system in Rome. As a sign of new ''Justitia Papalis'', he had the new penal institution, the ''Carceri Nuove'', built in Via Giulia.<ref name=pie7913>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 13</ref> This new prison was built between 1652 and 1655 by the architect Antonio del Grande.<ref name=pie7913/><ref>Inscription above the portal: IUSTITIAE ET CLEMENTIAE SECURIORI AC MITlORI REORUM CUSTODIAE NOVUM CARCEREM INNOCENTIUS X PONT. MAX. POSUIT ANNO DOMINI MDCLV (''Innocent X. P.M. built the new prison in the year of the Lord 1655, for justice, leniency for the safe and humane custody of convicts'')</ref> The Carceri Nuove were considered a model of a humane penitentiary system in their time. The building and its purpose had a rather negative influence on the image of the magnificent street, which led to the suspension of construction in the following years and the [[Italian Renaissance|Renaissance]] character of the street being preserved. The building acted as a prison until the opening of [[Regina Coeli]] in [[Trastevere]] <ref name=pie7914>Pietrangeli (1979), p. 14</ref> in 1883, further on until 1931 as a youth prison.<ref name=pie7914/> From 1931 the palace housed the headquarters of the ''Centro di Studi Penitenziari'' (\"Research Institute for Criminal Justice\") and a specialized library.<ref name=pie7914/> Today the building houses the ''Direzione Nazionale Antimafia e Antiterrorismo'' (\"National Directorate for Anti-Mafia and Anti-Terrorism\").\n===17a Palazzo del Gonfalone===\n[[File:Via Giulia Carceri Nuove Museo Criminologico.jpg|thumb|100px|17a Palazzo del Gonfalone]]\nThe building between the Vicolo della Scimia and Via del Gonfalone has no entrance from Via Giulia.<ref name=pie64/> It was built between 1825 and 1827 under [[Pope Leo XII]] (r. 1823-1829) according to plans by [[Giuseppe Valadier]] as a prison for the youth.<ref name=pie64>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 64</ref> Today the building houses the ''Museo Criminologico'' (lit. \"Criminological Museum\").<ref name=pie66>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 66</ref>\n===18 Santa Maria del Suffragio===\n{{Main|Santa Maria del Suffragio, Rome}}\n[[File:Via Giulia Santa Maria del Suffragio.jpg|thumb|100px|18 S.M. del Suffragio]]\nIn 1592 the ''Confraternita del Suffragio'' (\"Brotherhood of Intercession\") was founded next to the church of [[San Biagio della Pagnotta]] to implore the intercession for the souls of the purgatory.<ref name=pie56/> The Brotherhood was approved by [[Pope Clement VIII]] (r. 1592-1605) in 1594 <ref name=pie56/> and was elevated to the status of ''Arciconfaternita'' (\"Archbishopric Brotherhood\") by [[Paul V]] in 1620. Thanks to several donations, in 1662 the erection of the church began as a project of architect [[Carlo Rainaldi]].<ref name=pie56/> The building was consecrated in 1669, and the fa\u00e7ade was finished in 1680.<ref name=pie56/> The church's interior was renovated in 1869; the frescoes inside the church are by [[Cesare Mariani]] (''[[Coronation of the Virgin]]'') and [[Giuseppe Chiari]] (''[[Nativity of Mary]]'' and ''[[Adoration of the Magi]]'').<ref name=pie58>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 58</ref>\n===19 Palazzo dei Tribunali===\n[[File:Via Giulia Sof\u00e0 (Palazzo dei Tribunali) 1.jpg|thumb|100px|19 Sof\u00e0]]\n[[Julius II]]'s most important planned project in the new street was a central administration building, in which a large part of the city's important offices and courts (\"tribunali\") were to be grouped together.<ref name=pie50/> The Pope's commission to [[Donato Bramante]]<ref name=pie50/> was issued around 1506, and construction in the area between ''Vicolo del Cefalo'' and ''Via del Gonfalone'' began before 1508,<ref name=pie50/> but was interrupted as in 1511 by the ''Pax Romana''.<ref name=tem124/> With the [[Julius II]]'s death in 1513, construction completely stopped. [[Giorgio Vasari]] wrote:\n{{quote|''Onde Bramante diede principio al palazzo ch'a San Biagio su 'l Tevere si vede, nel quale \u00e8 ancora un tempio corinzio non finito, cosa molto rara, et il resto del principio di opera rustica bellissimo che \u00e8 stato gran danno che una s\u00ec onorata et utile e magnifica opra non si sia finita, ch\u00e9 da quelli della professione \u00e8 tenuto il pi\u00f9 bello ordine che si sia visto mai in quel genere.''}}\n{{quote|Bramante therefore began the construction of the palace, which can be seen near San Biagio on the Tiber. In it there is still an unfinished [[corinthian order|Corinthian]] temple, something very rare and the remains of the beginning in beautiful ''[[Rustication (architecture)|Opera Rustica]]''. It is a great pity that such an important, useful and great project has remained unfinished. Experts considered it to be the most beautiful building of its kind ever seen.}} <ref name=vasBra/><ref name=pie50>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 50</ref><ref name=pie52/>\nSome remains of the mighty [[Rustication (architecture)|rusticated]] walls, called ''sof\u00e0'' by the Roman population, between Via del Gonfalone and Vicolo del Cefalo along Via Giulia, can be seen today.<ref name=pie52/>\n===20 San Biagio della Pagnotta (San Biagio degli Armeni)===\n{{Main|San Biagio della Pagnotta}}\n[[File:Via Giulia San Biagio della Pagnotta.jpg|thumb|100px|20 San Biagio]]\nThis church was dedicated to [[Saint Blaise]] of [[Sivas|Sebaste]] and is mentioned in the church catalogues of the Middle Ages under the name of ''San Biagio de Cantu Secuta''.<ref name=pie52>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 52</ref> The name \"della pagnotta\" is derived from the Roman word ''pagnotta'' (\"bread roll\"), which was distributed to the faithful on the 3 February (feast of St. Blaise) and thought to protect against throat illnesses.<ref name=pie54>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 54</ref> The church was attached to one of the first abbeys in Rome.<ref name=pie52/> An inscription on the interior commemorates the construction of the church by an abbot Dominicus in 1072.<ref name=arm356>Armellini (1891), p. 356</ref> According to the Bramante's plans, this church was to be included in the construction of the Palazzo dei Tribunali. From 1539 to 1835 it was a [[parish]] church.<ref name=pie54/> In 1826 [[Pope Gregory XVI]] (r. 1831-1846) assigned the church to the [[Armenian people|Armenian]] community of Santa Maria Egiziaca.<ref name=pie54/> Since then it has been called officially ''San Biagio degli Armeni''.<ref name=pie52/>\n===21 Palazzo Ricci-Donarelli (Via Giulia no. 99-105)===\nThe palace is opposite to the Palazzo Sacchetti and was originally a group of residential buildings that first belonged to the [[Ricci family|Ricci]] and later to the Donarelli family.<ref name=pie48>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 48</ref>  The complex was restructured in 1663, possibly by [[Carlo Rainaldi]].<ref name=pie50>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 50</ref>\n===22 Palazzo Sacchetti (Via Giulia 66)===\n[[File:Palazzo Sacchetti Via Giulia (Rom).jpg|thumb|100px|22 Palazzo Sacchetti]]\n[[Antonio da Sangallo the Younger]] built the palace on land bought in 1542 by the Vatican Chapter.<ref name=pie40>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 40</ref> The fa\u00e7ade still bears the chipped [[coat of arms]] of Paul III.<ref name=pie40/> His son Orazio inherited the building and sold it in 1552 to Cardinal [[Giovanni Ricci (bishop)|Giovanni Ricci]] di [[Montepulciano]], who had the palace extended to its current dimensions by the architect [[Nanni di Baccio Bigio]].<ref name=pie40/> An inscription<ref>Inscription [[:File:Ponte - via Giulia palazzo Sacchetti - domus Antonii Sangalli architecti 1160658.JPG|(Fig.)]] on the fa\u00e7ade: DOMVS/ANTONII/SANGALLI/ARCHITECTI/MDLIII (house of the architect Antonio Sangallo 1553)</ref> in the Vicolo del Cefalo's side wall states that the palace was exempted from paying the census tax in 1555.[[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Sacchetti Zensus 1555.jpg|(Fig.)]]<ref name=pie46/> The building changed hands several times.<ref name=pie40/><ref name=pie42>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 42</ref> In 1649 it was bought by the Florentine [[Sacchetti family]], whose name it still bears.<ref name=pie42/> The entrance to Via Giulia is made of marble and flanked on both sides by three large windows with grilles, thresholds, and cornices.<ref name=pie44>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 44</ref> In the left corner of the palace there is a small fountain [[:File:Palazzo Sacchetti Delfinbrunnen.jpg|(Fig.)]] flanked by [[caryatid]]es with two dolphins embedded in the wall;<ref name=pie44/> this refers to the later owners, the Ceuli family, whose coat of arms was chipped.<ref name=pie44/> Notable features inside include the ''Salone dei Mappamondi'' (\"Hall of World Maps\"), designed by [[Francesco de' Rossi (Il Salviati)|Francesco Salviati]],<ref name=pie46>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 46</ref> and the dining room with two [[fresco]]es designed by [[Pietro da Cortona]].<ref name=pie46/> The writer [[Ingeborg Bachmann]] lived in this palazzo in 1973 and died on 17 October 1973.\n===23 Palace with the Farnese coat of arms (Via Giulia 93)===\n[[File:Via Giulia (Rom);Palast mit den Farnese Wappen.jpg|thumb|100px|23 Palazzo with the Farnese coat of arms]]\nThe building is attributed to [[Giacomo della Porta]]. The palazzo takes its name from the three coats of arms of the [[Farnese family]], which were added to the fa\u00e7ade under Paul III. In the centre of the upper floor there is the coat of arms of [[Paul III]] with the papal [[tiara]] and the keys between two [[unicorn]]s. On the left is the coat of arms of Cardinal [[Alessandro Farnese (cardinal)|Alessandro Farnese]] and on the right the [[coat of arms]] of the [[Duchy of Parma|Duke of Parma and Piacenza]] [[Ranuccio I Farnese]].\n===24 Palazzo Medici Clarelli (Via Giulia 79)===\n[[File:Via Giulia Palazzo Medici Clarelli.jpg|thumb|100px|24 Palazzo Medici Clarelli]]\nAntonio da Sangallo the Younger built this palace as a private residence around 1535-1536.<ref name=pie34>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 34</ref> After Sangallo's death in 1546 the building was owned by the Florentine Migliore Cresci.<ref name=pie34/> An inscription above the main portal [[:File:Via Giulia Palazzo Medici Clarelli (Inschrift).jpg|(Fig.)]] immortalizes Duke [[Cosimo I de' Medici, Grand Duke of Tuscany|Cosimo I de' Medici]].<ref name=pie34/> The palace for some time belonged to the Tuscan Consulate in Rome.<ref name=pie34/> At the end of the 17th century it was acquired by the Marini Clarelli family. In the 19th century it was used as barracks before being sold to the city of Rome in 1870. The fa\u00e7ade and the portal are lined with rusticated [[ashlar]]s.<ref name=pie36>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 36</ref> On the sides of the portal there are badly rebuilt large windows on [[Console (architecture)|consoles]].<ref name=pie36/>\n===25 Casa di Raffaello (via Giulia 85)===\n[[:File:Via Giulia Casa di Raffaello.jpg|(Fig.)]]\nThis palace, erroneously called the House of [[Raphael]], was built after 1525 for the [[Vatican Hill|Vatican]] [[Chapter (religion)|Chapter]] according to a design by the architect Bartolomeo de Ramponibus.<ref name=pie36>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 36</ref> Raphael originally acquired several plots of land here.<ref name=pie36/> However, he died before the building's construction began. The designs were created by Rafael and Antonio da Sangallo the Younger.<ref name=pie36/> An inscription above the windows of the first floor is dedicated to Raphael: '''POSSEDEVA RAF SANZIO NEL MDXX'''.<ref name=pie36/>\n===26 Quarter of the Florentines===\nIn 1448 Florentine merchants who resided in Rome founded the ''Compagnia della Piet\u00e0'', akin to the Florentine \"Misericordia\".<ref name=pie14>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 14</ref> Both Popes from the [[Medici family]], Leo X and [[Pope Clement VII|Clement VII]] (r. 1523-1534), promoted the influx of Florentines. Since 1515 the Commune of Florence had its own consulate in a palace on ''Via del Consolato''  that was erected in 1541 and demolished in 1888 to build [[Corso Vittorio Emanuele]].<ref name=pie26>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 26</ref> It had its own laws, its own court, and its own prison. Some of the buildings erected towards the end of the 15th century that once belonged to Florentines [[:File:Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (0).jpg|(Fig.)]] are still preserved across from the church of [[San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]:<ref name=pie24>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 24</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" widths=\"200\" heights=\"200\" \"=\"\">\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (1).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (2).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n Via Giulia Case dei Fiorentini (4).jpg|Quarter of the Florentines\n</gallery>\n===27 San Giovanni dei Fiorentini===\n{{Main|San Giovanni dei Fiorentini}}\n[[File:San Giovanni dei Fiorentini (Roma).jpg|thumb|200px|San Giovanni dei Fiorentini]]\nIn 1519 the \"nation\" of the Florentines received the privilege to build a parish church in honour of [[John the Baptist]] from Leo X .<ref name=pie16>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 16</ref> The church stands at the northern end of ''Via Giulia'' in the Florentine quarter.<ref name=pie16/> The church reflects the grandeur and the political self-image of the [[Medici family]], who owned a palazzo right next to the church. It is the largest church on Via Giulia.<ref name=pie16/> It combined the efforts of three of Rome's master builders: [[Giacomo della Porta]], [[Carlo Maderno]], and [[Francesco Borromini]].<ref name=pie16/> The last two artists [[burial|interred]] in the same tomb at the church.<ref name=pie20>Pietrangeli (1981), p. 20</ref> The altarpiece, started by [[Pietro da Cortona]], was continued by Borromini and finished by [[Ciro Ferri]].<ref name=pie20/>\n\n==Trivia==\n[[\u00c9mile Zola]], who visited Rome from 1894 to 1896, gave a description of Via Giulia and Palazzo Sacchetti (Palazzo Boccanera) in his [[travel literature|travelogue]].<ref>\u00c9mile Zola: ''Les trois villes \u2013 Rome''; Volume I, Cap. 3,II; Parigi 1896</ref>\n==References==\n<references/>\n== Sources==\n*{{cite book\n | author=Giorgio Vasari\n | authorlink=Giorgio Vasari\n | title=Le vite de\u2019 pi\u00f9 eccellenti architetti, pittori, et scultori italiani, da Cimabue insino a' tempi nostri\n | publisher=Giunti\n | location=Firenze\n | year=1568\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Giacinto Gigli\n | title = Diario romano, 1608-1670\n | location= Roma\n | publisher= Staderini\n | year= 1958\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Mariano Armellini\n | title = Le chiese di Roma dal secolo IV al XIX\n | year = 1891\n | url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/I/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/churches/_Texts/Armellini/ARMCHI*/home.html\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Luigi Vittorio Bertarelli\n | publisher=Touring Club Italiano\n | location=Milano\n | year=1925\n | title=Roma e dintorni\n | language=Italian\n}}\n*{{cite book\n | author=Luigi Callari\n | title=I Palazzi di Roma\n | publisher=Ugo Sofia-Moretti\n | location=Roma\n | year=1932\n | lan