{"title_page": "2019 Kansas City Chiefs season", "text_new": "{{short description|60th season in franchise history; third Super Bowl appearance}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL team season\n| logo            = Kansas City Chiefs 60th season logo.svg\n| team            = Kansas City Chiefs \n| year            = 2019\n| record          = 12\u20134\n| division_place  = 1st [[AFC West]]\n| coach           = [[Andy Reid]]\n| owner           = [[Lamar Hunt#Personal life|The Hunt family]]\n| general manager = [[Brett Veach]] \n| stadium         = [[Arrowhead Stadium]]\n| playoffs        = {{Unbulleted list|'''Won [[2019\u201320 NFL playoffs|Divisional Playoffs]]'''|(vs. [[2019 Houston Texans season|Texans]]) 51\u201331|'''Won [[2019-20 NFL playoffs|AFC Championship]]'''|(vs. [[2019 Tennessee Titans season|Titans]]) 35\u201324|'''Won [[Super Bowl LIV]]'''|(vs. [[2019 San Francisco 49ers season|49ers]]) 31\u201320}}\n| pro bowlers     = {{Collapsible list\n| title           = 6\n| 1 =               {{small|Selected but did not participate due to participation in Super Bowl LIV:}}               \n| 2 = DE [[Frank Clark (American football)|Frank Clark]]\n| 3 = PR [[Mecole Hardman]]\n| 4 = WR [[Tyreek Hill]]\n| 5 = DT [[Chris Jones (defensive tackle, born 1994)|Chris Jones]]\n| 6 = TE [[Travis Kelce]]\n| 7 = QB [[Patrick Mahomes]]\n}}\n| AP All-pros     = {{Collapsible list\n|title = 4\n|1 = KR [[Mecole Hardman]] ''(2nd team)''\n|2 = TE [[Travis Kelce]] ''(2nd team)''\n|3 = DB [[Tyrann Mathieu]] ''(1st team)''\n|4 = S Tyrann Mathieu ''(2nd team)''\n|5 = OT [[Mitchell Schwartz]] ''(2nd team)''\n}}\n| MVP             = [[Tyrann Mathieu]]\n| ROY             = [[Mecole Hardman]] \n| uniform         = File:kc chiefs uniforms.png\n| shortnavlink    = Chiefs seasons\n}}\nThe '''2019 Kansas City Chiefs season''' was the [[Kansas City Chiefs]]' 50th in the [[National Football League]], their 60th overall, their seventh under [[List of Kansas City Chiefs head coaches|head coach]] [[Andy Reid]], and third under general manager [[Brett Veach]].\n\nIn the offseason, the Chiefs released two of their longest-tenured players: [[Justin Houston]] and [[Eric Berry]]. The Chiefs started the season with a 1\u20133 record at home, their worst record after four home games since [[2012 Kansas City Chiefs season|2012]]. However, they began the season 4\u20130 on the road, their best road record after four road games since [[2013 Kansas City Chiefs season|2013]]. With a Week 14 [[2019 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]] loss and a win over the [[2019 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], the Chiefs clinched the [[American Football Conference|AFC]] [[AFC West|West]], extending their team record division title streak to four consecutive. They also clinched the franchise's fifth consecutive playoff appearance, one short of the franchise record of six consecutive from 1990\u20131995. The Chiefs also finished undefeated in the AFC West for the second time under Andy Reid, extending their record within the AFC West since 2015 to 27\u20133. They clinched their second straight bye to the Divisional round of the AFC playoffs due to a Week 17 win against the [[2019 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]] combined with a Patriots loss to the [[2019 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]]. \n\nIn the Divisional round, the Chiefs defeated the [[2019 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] 51\u201331 despite falling behind 24\u20130 in the second quarter to give the Chiefs playoff wins in back-to-back seasons for the first time in franchise history. The 51 points they scored was a franchise record for a postseason game. The win, along with the [[2019 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens']] loss the previous night, allowed the Chiefs to host the AFC Championship for the second time in franchise history. They defeated the [[2019 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]] 35\u201324 in the AFC Championship advancing to [[Super Bowl LIV]], where they defeated the [[San Francisco 49ers]] 31\u201320 to win their first championship since [[Super Bowl IV]] in [[1969 Kansas City Chiefs season|1970]].\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==NFL Top 100==\n{{main article|NFL Top 100 Players of 2019}}\n\nThe Chiefs had six players ranked on [[NFL Network]]'s annual Top 100 players countdown, which was tied for second most in the league. Reigning NFL MVP Patrick Mahomes was ranked 4th, the highest ranking ever by a Chiefs player. Additionally, he was the highest ranked player on the countdown that was not ranked in 2018 and was the second highest player ever that was unranked the previous season.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|year=2018|border=2}}\"| Rank\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|year=2018|border=2}}\"| Player\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|year=2018|border=2}}\"| Position\n!style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|year=2018|border=2}}\"| Change\n|-\n| 4 || [[Patrick Mahomes]] || QB || NR\n|-\n| 19 || [[Tyreek Hill]] || WR || {{increase}} 21\n|-\n| 21 || [[Travis Kelce]] || TE || {{increase}} 3\n|-\n| 36 || [[Chris Jones (defensive tackle, born 1994)|Chris Jones]] || DT || NR\n|-\n| 85 || [[Frank Clark (American football)|Frank Clark]] || DE || NR\n|-\n| 94 || [[Mitchell Schwartz]] || T || NR\n|}\n\n==Staff==\n===Coaching changes===\n<!-- Only include major position changes and not support staff such as trainers etc. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ style=\"{{NFLPrimaryStyle|Kansas City Chiefs|year=2019|border=2}}\"| 2019 Kansas City Chiefs Staff Changes\n|-\n! Coach !! Position !! Reason left !! Replacement\n|-\n| [[Bob Sutton (American football)|Bob Sutton]] || Defensive Coordinator || Fired || [[Steve Spagnuolo]]\n|-\n| Britt Reid || Defensive Line || Promoted || [[Brendan Daly (American football)|Brendan Daly]]\n|-\n| [[Mike Smith (linebacker)|Mike Smith]] || Outside Linebackers || Accepted job with<br