ke Pereira]]\n|reference=[https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2020020200/2019/POST22/49ers@chiefs Recap], [https://nflcdns.nfl.com/liveupdate/gamecenter/58167/KC_Gamebook.pdf Game Book]\n|scoring=\n'''First quarter'''\n*SF \u2013 [[Robbie Gould]] 38-yard field goal, 7:57. ''49ers 3\u20130. '''Drive: 10 plays, 62 yards, 5:58.'''''\n*KC \u2013 [[Patrick Mahomes]] 1-yard run ([[Harrison Butker]] kick), 0:31. ''Chiefs 7\u20133. '''Drive: 15 plays, 75 yards, 7:26.'''''\n'''Second quarter'''\n*KC \u2013 Harrison Butker 31-yard field goal, 9:32. ''Chiefs 10\u20133. '''Drive: 9 plays, 43 yards, 4:36.'''''\n*SF \u2013 [[Kyle Juszczyk]] 15-yard pass from [[Jimmy Garoppolo]] (Robbie Gould kick), 5:05. ''Tied 10\u201310. '''Drive: 7 plays, 80 yards, 4:27.'''''\n'''Third quarter'''\n*SF \u2013 Robbie Gould 42-yard field goal, 9:29. ''49ers 13\u201310. '''Drive: 9 plays, 60 yards, 5:31.''''''\n*SF \u2013 [[Raheem Mostert]] 1-yard run (Robbie Gould kick), 2:35. ''49ers 20\u201310. '''Drive: 5 plays, 55 yards, 2:48.'''''\n'''Fourth quarter'''\n*KC \u2013 [[Travis Kelce]] 1-yard pass from Patrick Mahomes (Harrison Butker kick), 6:13. ''49ers 20\u201317. '''Drive: 10 plays, 83 yards, 2:40.'''''\n*KC \u2013 [[Damien Williams]] 5-yard pass from Patrick Mahomes (Harrison Butker kick), 2:44. ''Chiefs 24\u201320. '''Drive: 5 plays, 55 yards, 2:48.'''''\n*KC \u2013 Damien Williams 38-yard run (Harrison Butker kick), 1:12. ''Chiefs 31\u201320. '''Drive: 2 plays, 42 yards, 0:13.'''''\n|stats=\n'''Top passers'''\n*SF \u2013 Jimmy Garoppolo \u2013 20/31, 219 yards, TD, 2 INT\n*KC \u2013 Patrick Mahomes \u2013 26/42, 286 yards, 2 TD, 2 INT\n'''Top rushers'''\n*SF \u2013 Raheem Mostert \u2013 12 rushes, 58 yards, TD\n*KC \u2013 Damien Williams \u2013 17 rushes, 104 yards, TD\n'''Top receivers'''\n*SF \u2013 [[Deebo Samuel]] \u2013 5 receptions, 39 yards\n*KC \u2013 [[Tyreek Hill]] \u2013 9 receptions, 105 yards\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.chiefs.com}}\n\n<!--The following is a series produced by the Kansas City Chiefs, published by the team via YouTube through the verified account of the Kansas City Chiefs. Do not remove these links for copyright reasons, they are clear!-->\n*''The Franchise,'' Kansas City Chiefs, May 29, 2019-Feb. 19, 2020 (video). <small>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P1UNviaUeNA&t=37s 1: Be Great] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iKlcgiEjgow&t=16s 2: It Starts Here] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hP--KJNPy6A 3: Clear the Way] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oVFfCtGVO10 4: The Non-Season] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m3GAeOKb-8o 5: A Best Of] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B_am0oaoPNw 6: Start Your Engines] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=luf3wNd4k94 7: A Long Time Coming] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9My9AsS13tQ 8: A Seat at the Table] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=StqmuDpybJw 9: Kick It Off] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PMzvy-w1POs 10: Play to the Whistle] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZDehKd2EQ3c 11: Adversity] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t8rYi-tfCk0 12: Next Man Up] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y0N63OwqeWM 13: Attack Every Day] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HdvLBMiWsls 14: Recharge and Reload] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7LfYp7LK4LA 15: The Playoff Push] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9vh4i_bSG3g 16: Championship Swagger] | [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S4R8rKNO1wA 17: Super Bowl]</small>\n\n{{Super Bowl champions}}\n{{Kansas City Chiefs}}\n{{Kansas City Chiefs seasons}}\n{{Super Bowl LIV}}\n{{2019 NFL season by team}}\n\n[[Category:2019 National Football League season by team|Kansas City]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs seasons]]\n[[Category:2019 in sports in Missouri|Kansas City Chiefs]]\n[[Category:NFL International Series participants]]\n[[Category:AFC West championship seasons]]\n[[Category:American Football Conference championship seasons]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champion seasons]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRestricted free agents:Typo fixing, replaced: can chose \u2192 can choose", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Kansas_City_Chiefs_season"}
{"title_page": "Rani Sati Temple", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox Hindu temple \n| name               = Rani Sati Dadi Temple<br> \u0930\u093e\u0923\u0940 \u0938\u0924\u0940 \u0926\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u092e\u0902\u0926\u093f\u0930\n| image              = File:( Side view of Rani Sati temple Jhunjhunu ).JPG.jpeg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Main entrance of temple\n| map_type           = India Rajasthan#India \n| map_caption        = Location of Rani Sati Temple in [[Jhunjhunu]], [[Rajasthan]]\n| coordinates        = {{coord|28|8|7|N|75|24|13|E|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| native_name        =  \u0930\u093e\u0923\u0940 \u0938\u0924\u0940 \u092e\u0902\u0926\u093f\u0930 \u091d\u0941\u0902\u091d\u0941\u0928\u0942\n| country            = [[India]] \n| state              = [[Rajasthan]] \n| district           = [[Jhunjhunu district|Jhunjhunu]] \n|locale              = \n| elevation_m        = \n| deity  =\n| festivals= Varshika [[Puja (Hinduism)|Puja]]\n| architecture       = \n| temple_quantity  = \n| monument_quantity= \n| inscriptions       = \n| established        = \n| creator            =  \n| website            = {{url| http://www.dadisati.in}} \n}}\n\n'''Rani Sati Temple''' (\u0930\u093e\u0923\u0940 \u0938\u0924\u0940 \u0926\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u092e\u0902\u0926\u093f\u0930) is a temple located in [[Jhunjhunu]], [[Jhunjhunu district]], in the state of [[Rajasthan]], India. It is the largest temple in [[India]] devoted to [[Rani Sati]], a [[Rajasthan]]i lady who lived sometime between the 13th and the 17th century and committed [[sati (practice)|sati]] (self-immolation) on her husband's death. Various temples in Rajasthan and elsewhere are devoted to her worship and to commemorate her act. Rani Sati is also called Narayani Devi and referred to as Dadiji (grandmother).\n\n==Story==\nThe story of Rani Sati Dadi Maa starts from the time of Mahabharata. Narayani's wish of being married to Abhimanyu and her desire to be sati in her next life.{{clarify|date=February 2016}}\n\nAs granted by [[Lord Krishna]], in her next life she was born as the daughter of Gursamal Birmewal in the village of Dokwa in Rajasthan and was named Narayani. Abhimanyu was born in Hissar as a son of Jaliram Jalan and named Tandhan Jalan. Tandan and Narayani got married and were leading a peaceful life. He was in possession of a beautiful horse which was being eyed by the son of king of Hissar for quite some time. Tandhan refused to hand over his precious horse to the king's son.\n\nThe king's son then decides to forcefully acquire the horse and thus challenges Tandan to a duel. Tandan fights the battle bravely and kills the king's son. The enraged king thus kills Tandan in front of Narayani in the battle. Narayani, symbolic of female bravery and power, fights with the king and kills him. She then commanded Ranaji (the caretaker of the horse) to make immediate arrangements for her to be set ablaze along with her husband's cremation.<ref name=\"History of Temple\">{{cite web|title=Shree Rani Sati Dadi Ji Mandir, Jhunjhunu. Rajasthan, India :: Know About temple of Rani Sati Dadi maa  Jhunjhunu|url=http://www.dadisati.in/about-dadi.php|website=www.dadisati.in|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=1}}</ref>\n\nRanaji, playing a vital role in fulfilling her wish to be sati with her husband, is then blessed by Narayani that his name will be taken and worshiped along with her name and since then she is known as Rani Sati.\n\n==Temple==\n[[File:Rani Sati Temple Jhunjhunu a Gallery.jpg|thumb|A gallery within the temple]]\nThe temple is notable for not holding any paintings or statues of either female or male gods. Instead a trishul depicting power and force is worshipped religiously by the followers. A portrait of Rani Sati dadiji is located in the pradhan mand. The temple is constructed from white marble and has colorful wall paintings.<ref name=\"About Temple\">{{cite web|title=Visti Temple of Shri Rani Sati Dadi Maa Jhunjhunu Temple in Rajasthan|url=http://www.dadisati.in/temple.php|website=www.dadisati.in|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=2}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rani Sati Main Temple.png|thumb]]\nIn the complex of Rani Sati temple there is also the [[Lord Hanuman]] Temple, Sita Temple, Thakur Ji temple,[[Lord Ganesha]] Temple and [[Shiva]] Temple. A regular 'Prasad' distribution takes place after every 'aarti'.<ref>{{cite web|title=My Yatra Diary...: The Rani Sati Dadi Temple, Jhunjhunu|url=http://www.myyatradiary.com/2010/08/rani-sati-dadi-temple-jhunjhunu.html?m=1|website=www.myyatradiary.com|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=3}}</ref> As well as the main temple there are twelve smaller sati temples.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Page 1|url=http://myjhunjhunu.com/jhunjhunu/tourism/jhunjhnutourism.htm|website=myjhunjhunu.com|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref> A huge statue of Lord Shiva is located in the centre of the complex and is surrounded by green gardens.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rani Sati Temple in Jhunjhunu, Temple of Dadisa Rani Sati|url=http://m.jhunjhunuonline.in/city-guide/rani-sati-temple-in-jhunjhunu|website=m.jhunjhunuonline.in|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=4}}</ref> Inside the temple, the interiors are adorned with exquisite murals and glass mosaics depicting the entire history of the place.\n\n==Observances and festivals==\n[[File:Rani Sati Temple Aarti.jpg|thumb|[[Aarti]] at Rani Sati Temple Jhunjhunu]]\nHundreds of devotees visit the temple every day. An elaborate [[aarti]] is performed at the temple two times a day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shri Rani Sati Dadi Ma Temple Aarti|url=http://www.dadisati.in/aarti.php|website=www.dadisati.in|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=5}}</ref> These are:\n* ''Mangala Aarti'': performed in the early morning, when the temple is opened.\n* ''Sandhya Aarti'': performed in the evening, at sunset.\n\nA special Poojan utsav is held on the occasion of [[Bhadra (Hindu calendar)|Bhadra]] [[Amavasya]]: The 15th day of the dark half of [[Bhadra (Hindu calendar)|Bhadra]] month in the [[Hindu calendar]] is of special significance to the temple.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rajasthan Tourism, Travel Rajasthan, Jhunjhunu Tourism, Jhunjhunu Travel|url=http://jhunjhunu.info/Tourism.html|website=jhunjhunu.info|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=5}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Rani Sati Temple}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.dadisati.in}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Jhunjhunu district]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani culture]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox Hindu temple \n| name               = Rani Sati Dadi Temple<br> \u0930\u093e\u0923\u0940 \u0938\u0924\u0940 \u0926\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u092e\u0902\u0926\u093f\u0930\n| image              = File:( Side view of Rani Sati temple Jhunjhunu ).JPG.jpeg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Main entrance of temple\n| map_type           = India Rajasthan#India \n| map_caption        = Location of Rani Sati Temple in [[Jhunjhunu]], [[Rajasthan]]\n| coordinates        = {{coord|28|8|7|N|75|24|13|E|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| native_name        =  \u0930\u093e\u0923\u0940 \u0938\u0924\u0940 \u092e\u0902\u0926\u093f\u0930 \u091d\u0941\u0902\u091d\u0941\u0928\u0942\n| country            = [[India]] \n| state              = [[Rajasthan]] \n| district           = [[Jhunjhunu district|Jhunjhunu]] \n|locale              = \n| elevation_m        = \n| deity  =\n| festivals= Varshika [[Puja (Hinduism)|Puja]]\n| architecture       = \n| temple_quantity  = \n| monument_quantity= \n| inscriptions       = \n| established        = \n| creator            =  \n| website            = {{url| http://www.dadisati.in}} \n}}\n\n'''Rani Sati Temple''' (\u0930\u093e\u0923\u0940 \u0938\u0924\u0940 \u0926\u093e\u0926\u0940 \u092e\u0902\u0926\u093f\u0930) is a temple located in [[Jhunjhunu]], [[Jhunjhunu district]], in the state of [[Rajasthan]], India. It is the largest temple in [[India]] devoted to [[Rani Sati]], a [[Rajasthan]]i lady who lived sometime between the 13th and the 17th century and committed [[sati (practice)|sati]] (self-immolation) on her husband's death. Various temples in Rajasthan and elsewhere are devoted to her worship and to commemorate her act. Rani Sati is also called Narayani Devi and referred to as Dadiji (grandmother).\n\n==Story==\nThe story of Rani Sati Dadi Maa starts from the time of Mahabharata. Narayani's wish of being married to Abhimanyu and her desire to be sati in her next life.{{clarify|date=February 2016}}\n\nAs granted by [[Lord Krishna]], in her next life she was born as the daughter of Gursamal Birmewal in the village of Dokwa in Rajasthan and was named Narayani. Abhimanyu was born in Hissar as a son of Jaliram Jalan and named Tandhan Jalan. Tandan and Narayani got married and were leading a peaceful life. He was in possession of a beautiful horse which was being eyed by the son of king of Hissar for quite some time. Tandhan refused to hand over his precious horse to the king\u2019s son.\n\nThe king\u2019s son then decides to forcefully acquire the horse and thus challenges Tandan to a duel. Tandan fights the battle bravely and kills the king\u2019s son. The enraged king thus kills Tandan in front of Narayani in the battle. Narayani, symbolic of female bravery and power, fights with the king and kills him. She then commanded Ranaji (the caretaker of the horse) to make immediate arrangements for her to be set ablaze along with her husband\u2019s cremation.<ref name=\"History of Temple\">{{cite web|title=Shree Rani Sati Dadi Ji Mandir, Jhunjhunu. Rajasthan, India :: Know About temple of Rani Sati Dadi maa  Jhunjhunu|url=http://www.dadisati.in/about-dadi.php|website=www.dadisati.in|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=1}}</ref>\n\nRanaji, playing a vital role in fulfilling her wish to be sati with her husband, is then blessed by Narayani that his name will be taken and worshiped along with her name and since then she is known as Rani Sati.\n\n==Temple==\n[[File:Rani Sati Temple Jhunjhunu a Gallery.jpg|thumb|A gallery within the temple]]\nThe temple is notable for not holding any paintings or statues of either female or male gods. Instead a trishul depicting power and force is worshipped religiously by the followers. A portrait of Rani Sati dadiji is located in the pradhan mand. The temple is constructed from white marble and has colorful wall paintings.<ref name=\"About Temple\">{{cite web|title=Visti Temple of Shri Rani Sati Dadi Maa Jhunjhunu Temple in Rajasthan|url=http://www.dadisati.in/temple.php|website=www.dadisati.in|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=2}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rani Sati Main Temple.png|thumb]]\nIn the complex of Rani Sati temple there is also the [[Lord Hanuman]] Temple, Sita Temple, Thakur Ji temple,[[Lord Ganesha]] Temple and [[Lord Shiva]] Temple. A regular 'Prasad' distribution takes place after every 'aarti'.<ref>{{cite web|title=My Yatra Diary...: The Rani Sati Dadi Temple, Jhunjhunu|url=http://www.myyatradiary.com/2010/08/rani-sati-dadi-temple-jhunjhunu.html?m=1|website=www.myyatradiary.com|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=3}}</ref> As well as the main temple there are twelve smaller sati temples.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Page 1|url=http://myjhunjhunu.com/jhunjhunu/tourism/jhunjhnutourism.htm|website=myjhunjhunu.com|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref> A huge statue of Lord Shiva is located in the centre of the complex and is surrounded by green gardens.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rani Sati Temple in Jhunjhunu, Temple of Dadisa Rani Sati|url=http://m.jhunjhunuonline.in/city-guide/rani-sati-temple-in-jhunjhunu|website=m.jhunjhunuonline.in|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=4}}</ref> Inside the temple, the interiors are adorned with exquisite murals and glass mosaics depicting the entire history of the place.\n\n==Observances and festivals==\n[[File:Rani Sati Temple Aarti.jpg|thumb|[[Aarti]] at Rani Sati Temple Jhunjhunu]]\nHundreds of devotees visit the temple every day. An elaborate [[aarti]] is performed at the temple two times a day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shri Rani Sati Dadi Ma Temple Aarti|url=http://www.dadisati.in/aarti.php|website=www.dadisati.in|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=5}}</ref> These are:\n* ''Mangala Aarti'': performed in the early morning, when the temple is opened.\n* ''Sandhya Aarti'': performed in the evening, at sunset.\n\nA special Poojan utsav is held on the occasion of [[Bhadra (Hindu calendar)|Bhadra]] [[Amavasya]]: The 15th day of the dark half of [[Bhadra (Hindu calendar)|Bhadra]] month in the [[Hindu calendar]] is of special significance to the temple.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rajasthan Tourism, Travel Rajasthan, Jhunjhunu Tourism, Jhunjhunu Travel|url=http://jhunjhunu.info/Tourism.html|website=jhunjhunu.info|accessdate=23 December 2015|ref=5}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Rani Sati Temple}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.dadisati.in}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Jhunjhunu district]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani culture]]\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rani_Sati_Temple"}
{"title_page": "Licence to Grill", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=March 2008}}\n\n'''''Licence to Grill''''' is a show hosted by [[Rob Rainford]] and can be seen on [[Food Network Canada]],  [[Asian Food Channel]] and downloaded at [[MoboVivo]].  The show is produced by [[Knight Enterprises]]. The show was formerly carried in the United States on the [[Discovery Networks]] channel Discovery Home, but was dropped from the schedule when the channel was flipped to the ecology-themed [[Planet Green]]. The episode \"Bike Ride BBQ\" was the last one to air in the USA.\n\n''Licence to Grill'' is a series that explores the enjoyment of backyard cooking, entertaining, and the [[barbecue]].  Each episode takes place over a day or two, but mainly on Saturdays.  The host and chef Rob Rainford prepares a meal for the evening when guests will arrive.\n\nThe central theme is barbecue and with that, Rainford shows us tips and tricks for cooking on a barbecue.  The recipes range from the typical barbecue fare, such as [[hamburgers]], [[steak]]s, [[kebab]]s, to more ambitious meals such as [[Lamb and mutton|leg of lamb]], hot smoking sides of [[fish]], grilled [[dessert]]s.\n\nRainford has a philosophy when it comes to the barbecue: \"It's pretty simple. Just start with the freshest ingredients you can find and then you've got two choices: long slow cooking over low indirect heat, or red hot and smokin' for fast grilling. If you cook low and slow then you can use all sorts of rubs and smoking agents to infuse the food with a depth of flavour you just can\u2019t get out of an oven. As for high heat grilling, your barbecue puts out way more heat than your stovetop so you can get that wonderful charring and searing, just like in a restaurant.\" <ref>Quoted on FoodTV.Ca at http://www.foodtv.ca/ontv/hostdetails.aspx?hostid=37086</ref>\n\n==Episode list==\n'''Season 1''':\n\n*1001- Martini Birthday Barbecue\n*1002- The Barbecue For No Reason\n*1003- Parents Night Out\n*1004- Baseball Pulled Pork\n*1005- Nothing But Chicken\n*1006- Garage Sale Brunch\n*1007- Blind Date With Garlic\n*1008- Toga Party\n*1009- The Mediterranean Feast\n*1010- Karaoke Slow Ribs\n*1011- The Engagement\n*1012- Total Eclipse\n*1013- Block Party\n*1014- Mexican Fiesta\n*1015- Full Moon - Summer Solstice\n*1016- Surprise Guest For Dinner\n*1017- Da Boys\n*1018- The Soccer Team Fundraiser\n*1019- The Superstar Celebration\n*1020- The Hole In One\n*1021- Saucy Contest\n*1022- The Girls' Championship Game\n*1023- Burgs and Dogs - Paint the Fence\n*1024- Bocce Ball Tournament\n*1025- Taste of the Sea\n*1026- Pool Party\n\n'''Season 2''':\n\n*2027- Hawaiian Luau\n*2028- Mardi Gras\n*2029- International Beer Day Celebration\n*2030- Airband Concert Pre-Party\n*2031- Japanese Farewell Dinner\n*2032- Godfather Italian Feast\n*2033- Caribbean Bon Voyage\n*2034- Wine and Cheese\n*2035- Aerobic Marathon\n*2036- 40th Birthday Bash\n*2037- Blackout\n*2038- Poker Night with the Boys\n*2039- Sunday Afternoon BBQ\n\n'''Season 3''':\n\n*3040- Vegas Night\n*3041- Pajama Party\n*3042- Fancy Pants Dinner\n*3043- Taste of India Celebration\n*3044- Volleyball Dinner\n*3045- Volunteer Dinner\n*3046- Poetry Club BBQ\n*3047- Rodeo BBQ\n*3048- Successful Jump\n*3049- The Non-Engagement\n*3050- 80's Night\n*3051- Hot Tub Night\n*3052- Boys Gone Fishing\n\n'''Season 4''':\n\n*4053- Costume Party BBQ\n*4054- Pool Party\n*4055- Horsehoe Tournament\n*4056- Motorcycle Parade Tournament\n*4057- Olympic BBQ\n*4058- Surf and Turf BBQ\n*4059- Silent Auction Dinner\n*4060- Live Band Party\n*4061- Tapas Dinner\n*4062- Carnival Day BBQ\n*4063- Bike Ride BBQ\n*4064- Boozey BBQ\n*4065- Games Night\n*4066- Dog Walkers' Breakfast\n*4067- Big Promotion BBQ\n*4068- Just Because BBQ\n*4069- Fire Fighter Party\n*4070- Ultimate Tournament\n*4071- Mexican Reunion\n*4072- World Cup Pub Fare\n*4073- Chinese Dinner BBQ\n*4074- Vegetarian Dinner\n*4075- Tennis Tournament\n*4076- Skateboard Dudes\n*4077- Road Hockey Tour